1
00:00:00,280 --> 00:00:05,220
CHAPTER ONE
Jamaica Inn

2
00:00:05,220 --> 00:00:11,089
It was a cold grey day in late November, and
although it was now only a little after two

3
00:00:11,089 --> 00:00:17,080
o'clock in the afternoon the dark of a winter
evening seemed to have come down over the

4
00:00:17,080 --> 00:00:18,080
hills, hiding them in mist.

5
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:26,090
The air was cold, and in spite of the tightly
closed windows, it found its way into the

6
00:00:26,090 --> 00:00:27,090
coach.

7
00:00:27,090 --> 00:00:32,800
There must have been a small crack in the
roof, because now and again little drops of

8
00:00:32,800 --> 00:00:35,410
rain fell softly through onto the leather
seats.

9
00:00:35,410 --> 00:00:43,550
The wind blew hard, and on high ground, it
blew with such force that the whole body of

10
00:00:43,550 --> 00:00:47,390
the coach trembled and struggled to stay upright.

11
00:00:47,390 --> 00:00:53,600
The wheels of the coach sank into the holes
in the road, and sometimes they threw up mud

12
00:00:53,600 --> 00:00:58,879
against the windows, where it mixed with the
rain so that any view there might have been

13
00:00:58,879 --> 00:01:00,539
was blocked out.

14
00:01:00,539 --> 00:01:06,020
The few passengers sat close together for
warmth.

15
00:01:06,020 --> 00:01:11,409
Mary Yellan was sitting where the drops of
rain came through the crack in the roof.

16
00:01:11,409 --> 00:01:15,670
She brushed them away with impatient fingers.

17
00:01:15,670 --> 00:01:22,540
Although she was only 40 miles by road from
what had been her home for 23 years, she was

18
00:01:22,540 --> 00:01:23,710
already beginning to miss it.

19
00:01:23,710 --> 00:01:31,399
The courage, which was so large a part of
her, and had helped her so much during the

20
00:01:31,399 --> 00:01:39,530
long unhappiness of her mother's illness and
death, was now shaken by this rain and wind.

21
00:01:39,530 --> 00:01:42,260
She remembered the letter from her aunt.

22
00:01:42,260 --> 00:01:47,310
The writer said that the news had shocked
her; that she had had no idea that her sister

23
00:01:47,310 --> 00:01:52,080
was ill, because it was many years since she
had been in Helford.

24
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:59,450
And she went on: 'There have been changes
with us that you will not know about.

25
00:01:59,450 --> 00:02:09,429
I no longer live in Bodmin, but nearly 12
miles outside it, on the road to Launceston.

26
00:02:09,429 --> 00:02:16,000
It's a wild and lonely spot, and if you were
to come to us I should be glad of your company

27
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,150
in wintertime.

28
00:02:18,150 --> 00:02:25,129
I have asked your uncle, and he does not object,
he says, if you do not talk too much and will

29
00:02:25,129 --> 00:02:27,379
give help when it is needed.

30
00:02:27,379 --> 00:02:33,440
He cannot give you money or feed you for nothing,
as you will understand.

31
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:38,209
He will expect your help in the bar in return
for your room and meals.

32
00:02:38,209 --> 00:02:44,700
You see, your uncle is the landlord of Jamaica
Inn.'

33
00:02:44,700 --> 00:02:51,920
The letter was a strange message of welcome
from the smiling Aunt Patience she remembered.

34
00:02:51,920 --> 00:03:00,080
A cold, empty letter, giving no word of comfort,
and little information, except that she must

35
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:02,689
not ask for money.

36
00:03:02,689 --> 00:03:11,129
Aunt Patience, with her silk skirts and delicate
ways, the wife of an innkeeper!

37
00:03:11,129 --> 00:03:16,220
So it was that Mary Yellan found herself travelling
north in the coach.

38
00:03:16,220 --> 00:03:22,610
Villages were scattered now, and there were
few smiling faces at the doors of the small

39
00:03:22,610 --> 00:03:24,350
houses.

40
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:26,849
There were almost no trees.

41
00:03:26,849 --> 00:03:30,629
The wind blew and the rain came with the wind.

42
00:03:30,629 --> 00:03:37,760
And so the coach rolled into Bodmin, grey
and unwelcoming like the hills around it,

43
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:44,189
and one by one the passengers collected up
their things ready to leave - all except Mary,

44
00:03:44,189 --> 00:03:48,540
who sat still in her corner.

45
00:03:48,540 --> 00:03:53,110
The driver, his face a stream of rain, looked
in at the window.

46
00:03:53,110 --> 00:03:57,030
'Are you going on to Launceston?'

47
00:03:57,030 --> 00:03:58,560
he said.

48
00:03:58,560 --> 00:04:02,480
'It'll be a wild drive tonight across the
moors.

49
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:06,819
You can stay in Bodmin, you know, and go on
by coach in the morning.

50
00:04:06,819 --> 00:04:11,219
There'll be no one but you going on in this
coach.'

51
00:04:11,219 --> 00:04:15,280
'My friends will be expecting me,' said Mary.

52
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:18,579
'I'm not afraid of the drive.

53
00:04:18,579 --> 00:04:25,510
And I don't want to go as far as Launceston;
will you please leave me at Jamaica Inn?'

54
00:04:25,510 --> 00:04:28,080
The man looked at her strangely.

55
00:04:28,080 --> 00:04:31,340
Jamaica Inn?' he said.

56
00:04:31,340 --> 00:04:35,330
'What would you do at Jamaica Inn?

57
00:04:35,330 --> 00:04:37,760
That's no place for a girl.

58
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:42,660
You must have made a mistake, surely?'

59
00:04:42,660 --> 00:04:46,750
He looked at her hard, not believing her.

60
00:04:46,750 --> 00:04:51,500
Then he called over his shoulder to a woman
who stood in the doorway of the Royal Hotel,

61
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:53,650
lighting a lamp.

62
00:04:53,650 --> 00:04:55,320
It was already getting dark.

63
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:59,300
'Come here and reason with this young girl.

64
00:04:59,300 --> 00:05:07,990
I was told she was going to Launceston, but
she has asked me to leave her at Jamaica Inn!'

65
00:05:07,990 --> 00:05:11,860
The woman came down the steps and looked into
the coach.

66
00:05:11,860 --> 00:05:18,280
'It's a wild, rough place up there,' she said,
'and if you're looking for work, you won't

67
00:05:18,280 --> 00:05:21,971
find it on the farms.

68
00:05:21,971 --> 00:05:24,050
They don't like strangers on the moors.

69
00:05:24,050 --> 00:05:28,320
You'd do better down here in Bodmin.'

70
00:05:28,320 --> 00:05:29,740
Mary smiled at her.

71
00:05:29,740 --> 00:05:32,819
'I shall be all right,' she said.

72
00:05:32,819 --> 00:05:34,789
'I'm going to relatives.

73
00:05:34,789 --> 00:05:38,669
My uncle is the landlord of Jamaica Inn.'

74
00:05:38,669 --> 00:05:42,550
There was a long silence.

75
00:05:42,550 --> 00:05:47,090
In the grey light of the coach, Mary could
see that the woman and the man were looking

76
00:05:47,090 --> 00:05:48,810
at her.

77
00:05:48,810 --> 00:05:51,830
She felt cold, suddenly, and anxious.

78
00:05:51,830 --> 00:05:55,330
Then the woman stepped back from the window.

79
00:05:55,330 --> 00:05:57,960
'I'm sorry,' she said.

80
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:01,599
'It's none of my business, of course.

81
00:06:01,599 --> 00:06:02,639
Good night.'

82
00:06:02,639 --> 00:06:09,069
The driver began to whistle, rather red in
the face, as one who wishes to end an awkward

83
00:06:09,069 --> 00:06:11,639
situation.

84
00:06:11,639 --> 00:06:14,050
Mary leant forward and touched his arm.

85
00:06:14,050 --> 00:06:16,819
'Would you tell me?'

86
00:06:16,819 --> 00:06:17,819
she said.

87
00:06:17,819 --> 00:06:20,490
'I shan't mind what you say.

88
00:06:20,490 --> 00:06:22,800
Is my uncle not liked?

89
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:24,419
Is something the matter?'

90
00:06:24,419 --> 00:06:28,400
The man looked very uncomfortable.

91
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:29,870
He avoided her eyes.

92
00:06:29,870 --> 00:06:40,680
'Jamaica Inn's got a bad name,' he said; 'strange
stories are told - you know how it is.

93
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,960
But I don't want to make any trouble.

94
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:44,699
Perhaps they're not true.'

95
00:06:44,699 --> 00:06:48,690
'What sort of stories?' asked Mary.

96
00:06:48,690 --> 00:06:52,259
'Do you mean that people get drunk there?

97
00:06:52,259 --> 00:06:55,460
Does my uncle encourage bad company?'

98
00:06:55,460 --> 00:06:58,300
The man did not answer.

99
00:06:58,300 --> 00:07:04,669
'I don't want to make trouble,' he repeated,
'and I don't know anything.

100
00:07:04,669 --> 00:07:09,030
It's only what people say.

101
00:07:09,030 --> 00:07:12,460
Respectable people don't go to Jamaica Inn
any more.

102
00:07:12,460 --> 00:07:14,440
That's all I know.

103
00:07:14,440 --> 00:07:21,349
In the old days, we used to water the horses
there, and feed them, and go in for a bite

104
00:07:21,349 --> 00:07:23,220
of food and drink.

105
00:07:23,220 --> 00:07:26,840
But we don't stop there anymore.'

106
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:30,100
'Why don't people go there?

107
00:07:30,100 --> 00:07:32,790
What is their reason?'

108
00:07:32,790 --> 00:07:38,509
The man paused; it was as if he were searching
for words.

109
00:07:38,509 --> 00:07:48,350
'They're afraid,' he said at last, and then
he shook his head; he had no more to say.

110
00:07:48,350 --> 00:07:51,810
He shut the door and climbed into his seat.

111
00:07:51,810 --> 00:07:59,280
The coach rolled away down the street, past
the safe and solid houses, the busy lights,

112
00:07:59,280 --> 00:08:04,990
the scattered people hurrying home for supper,
their figures bent against the weather.

113
00:08:04,990 --> 00:08:11,130
Now the horses were climbing the steep hill
out of the town and, looking through the window

114
00:08:11,130 --> 00:08:16,729
at the back of the coach, Mary could see the
lights of Bodmin fast disappearing, one by

115
00:08:16,729 --> 00:08:20,570
one, until the last was gone.

116
00:08:20,570 --> 00:08:26,800
She was alone now with the wind and the rain,
and 12 long miles of empty moor between her

117
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:29,770
and her journey's end.

118
00:08:29,770 --> 00:08:35,260
She sat in her corner, shaken from side to
side by the coach.

119
00:08:35,260 --> 00:08:39,910
On either side of the road, the countryside
stretched away into space.

120
00:08:39,910 --> 00:08:49,890
No trees, no paths, no houses, but mile after
mile of moor, dark and empty, rolling like

121
00:08:49,890 --> 00:08:52,270
a desert to the unseen horizon.

122
00:08:52,270 --> 00:08:59,370
No human being could live in this country,
thought Mary, and remain like other people;

123
00:08:59,370 --> 00:09:06,740
the children would be born twisted, like the
blackened bushes, bent by the force of a wind

124
00:09:06,740 --> 00:09:08,890
that never stopped blowing.

125
00:09:08,890 --> 00:09:16,190
Their minds would be twisted too, their thoughts
evil, living, as they must among rough bushes

126
00:09:16,190 --> 00:09:19,130
and hard stone.

127
00:09:19,130 --> 00:09:21,650
She lifted the window and looked out.

128
00:09:21,650 --> 00:09:27,940
Ahead of her, at the top of hill on the left,
was some sort of building, standing back from

129
00:09:27,940 --> 00:09:29,550
the road.

130
00:09:29,550 --> 00:09:32,250
She could see tall chimneys in the darkness.

131
00:09:32,250 --> 00:09:34,880
There was no other house near.

132
00:09:34,880 --> 00:09:41,930
If this was Jamaica Inn, it stood alone, unprotected
from the winds.

133
00:09:41,930 --> 00:09:49,200
The horses came to a stop, clouds of steam
rising from their hot, wet bodies.

134
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:55,950
The driver climbed down from his seat, pulling
her box down with him.

135
00:09:55,950 --> 00:10:01,180
He seemed to be in a hurry, and kept looking
over his shoulder towards the house.

136
00:10:01,180 --> 00:10:06,130
'Here you are,' he said, 'across the yard
over there.

137
00:10:06,130 --> 00:10:09,290
If you hammer on the door, they'll let you
in.

138
00:10:09,290 --> 00:10:13,980
I must be going on, or I'll not reach Launceston
tonight.'

139
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:22,300
In a moment, the coach was away down the road,
disappearing as if it had never existed, lost

140
00:10:22,300 --> 00:10:26,510
and swallowed up in the darkness.

141
00:10:26,510 --> 00:10:29,640
Mary stood alone, with her box at her feet.

142
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:35,960
She heard the sound of the door being unlocked
in the dark house behind her, and then it

143
00:10:35,960 --> 00:10:37,600
was thrown open.

144
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:44,310
A great figure walked into the yard, swinging
a light from side to side.

145
00:10:44,310 --> 00:10:46,470
'Who is it?'

146
00:10:46,470 --> 00:10:48,620
came a shout.

147
00:10:48,620 --> 00:10:51,350
'What do you want here?'

148
00:10:51,350 --> 00:10:56,750
Mary stepped forward and looked up into the
man's face.

149
00:10:56,750 --> 00:11:00,670
The light shone in her eyes, and she could
see nothing.

150
00:11:00,670 --> 00:11:06,660
'Oh, it's you, is it?' he said.

151
00:11:06,660 --> 00:11:10,880
'So you've come to us after all?

152
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:14,730
I'm your uncle, Joss Merlyn.

153
00:11:14,730 --> 00:11:20,100
Welcome to Jamaica Inn.'

154
00:11:20,100 --> 00:11:26,360
He pulled her into the shelter of the house,
laughing, then shut the door and put the light

155
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:29,230
on a table in the passage.

156
00:11:29,230 --> 00:11:35,240
And they looked at each other face to face.

157
00:11:35,240 --> 00:11:40,200
CHAPTER TWO
The Landlord

158
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:48,940
He was a great big man, nearly 7 feet high,
with a lined face and dark brown skin.

159
00:11:48,940 --> 00:11:54,410
His thick black hair hung down over his eyes
and round his ears.

160
00:11:54,410 --> 00:11:59,770
He looked as if he had the strength of a horse,
with large, powerful shoulders, long arms

161
00:11:59,770 --> 00:12:04,610
that reached almost to his knees, and big
hands.

162
00:12:04,610 --> 00:12:10,570
His nose was hooked, curving to a mouth that
might have been perfect once but was now sunken

163
00:12:10,570 --> 00:12:16,800
and fallen, but there was still something
fine about his great dark eyes, in spite of

164
00:12:16,800 --> 00:12:18,350
the lines around them.

165
00:12:18,350 --> 00:12:25,270
The best things left to him were his teeth,
which were all good still, and very white,

166
00:12:25,270 --> 00:12:32,100
so that when he smiled they showed up clearly
against the brown of his face; but it was

167
00:12:32,100 --> 00:12:35,250
a cold, evil smile.

168
00:12:35,250 --> 00:12:43,620
'So you are Mary Yellan,' he said at last,
towering above her, his head bent to examine

169
00:12:43,620 --> 00:12:51,910
her more closely, 'and you've come all this
way to look after your Uncle Joss.

170
00:12:51,910 --> 00:12:56,180
I call it very nice of you.'

171
00:12:56,180 --> 00:13:04,190
He laughed again, his laugh filling the house,
and striking Mary, in her cold, tired anxiety,

172
00:13:04,190 --> 00:13:05,890
like a whip.

173
00:13:05,890 --> 00:13:08,230
'Where is my Aunt Patience?'

174
00:13:08,230 --> 00:13:14,790
she asked, looking around her in the dark
passage, with its cold stone floor and narrow

175
00:13:14,790 --> 00:13:15,980
staircase.

176
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:19,790
'Is she not expecting me, then?'

177
00:13:19,790 --> 00:13:28,560
'Where's my Aunt Patience?' he repeated, copying
the rise and fall of her voice.

178
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:32,050
Then he lifted his face to the stairs.

179
00:13:32,050 --> 00:13:36,860
'Patience!' he shouted, 'What are you doing?

180
00:13:36,860 --> 00:13:42,000
Here's the girl arrived, crying for you.

181
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:45,120
She's tired of the sight of me already.'

182
00:13:45,120 --> 00:13:48,700
There was a noise at the top of the stairs.

183
00:13:48,700 --> 00:13:55,240
Then down came a woman, her hand raised to
keep the light from her eyes.

184
00:13:55,240 --> 00:14:00,690
She wore a cap on her thin grey hair, which
hung to her shoulders.

185
00:14:00,690 --> 00:14:06,410
Her eyes were large, as though they were continually
asking questions, and she had a little habit

186
00:14:06,410 --> 00:14:12,270
of moving her mouth - tightening her lips
and then relaxing them.

187
00:14:12,270 --> 00:14:19,440
She wore an old striped skirt that had once
been red and was now a pale pink.

188
00:14:19,440 --> 00:14:24,800
Mary watched her without speaking, full of
sorrow.

189
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:30,940
Was this poor creature the beautiful Aunt
Patience of her dreams - dressed like this,

190
00:14:30,940 --> 00:14:35,080
and looking twenty years older than she was?

191
00:14:35,080 --> 00:14:41,320
The little woman came down the stairs and
into the hall; she took Mary's hands in hers

192
00:14:41,320 --> 00:14:43,330
and looked closely into her face.

193
00:14:43,330 --> 00:14:47,310
'Have you really come?'

194
00:14:47,310 --> 00:14:48,750
she whispered.

195
00:14:48,750 --> 00:14:53,730
'It is Mary Yellan, isn't it?

196
00:14:53,730 --> 00:14:56,950
My dead sister's child?'

197
00:14:56,950 --> 00:15:00,570
Mary thanked God that her mother could not
see her now.

198
00:15:00,570 --> 00:15:07,430
'Dear Aunt Patience,' she said gently, 'I'm
glad to see you again.

199
00:15:07,430 --> 00:15:12,240
It's so many long years since you came to
us at Helford.'

200
00:15:12,240 --> 00:15:18,250
The woman suddenly held her tightly, burying
her head against her shoulder, and she began

201
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:20,560
to cry, loudly and fearfully.

202
00:15:20,560 --> 00:15:26,360
'Ah, stop that,' shouted the husband.

203
00:15:26,360 --> 00:15:29,990
'What sort of welcome is this?

204
00:15:29,990 --> 00:15:33,420
What have you got to cry about, you fool?

205
00:15:33,420 --> 00:15:37,490
Can't you see the girl wants her supper?

206
00:15:37,490 --> 00:15:43,530
Get out to the kitchen and give her some meat
and a drink.'

207
00:15:43,530 --> 00:15:45,600
Aunt Patience controlled herself.

208
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:52,840
She led the way to another dark passage, and
so into the kitchen where a low fire burned.

209
00:15:52,840 --> 00:16:00,120
'You mustn't mind your Uncle Joss,' she said,
her manner changing suddenly to that of a

210
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:06,750
dog that has been trained by continuous cruelty
to unquestioning obedience and who, in spite

211
00:16:06,750 --> 00:16:11,690
of kicks and shouts, will fight like a tiger
for his master.

212
00:16:11,690 --> 00:16:19,910
'Your uncle must be treated carefully, you
know; he has his ways, and strangers don't

213
00:16:19,910 --> 00:16:21,350
understand him at first.

214
00:16:21,350 --> 00:16:28,220
He's a very good husband to me, and has been
ever since our wedding day.'

215
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:34,800
She talked on and on, going backwards and
forwards across the stone-floored kitchen

216
00:16:34,800 --> 00:16:37,420
as she laid the table for supper.

217
00:16:37,420 --> 00:16:44,240
There was a footstep outside the door, and
with a sinking heart, Mary realized that Joss

218
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:47,420
Merlyn had come downstairs again.

219
00:16:47,420 --> 00:16:51,610
He entered the room, and looked from one to
the other.

220
00:16:51,610 --> 00:16:55,540
He pulled a chair from the wall, and crashed
it against the table.

221
00:16:55,540 --> 00:17:02,220
Then he sat down heavily and, reaching for
the loaf, cut himself a great piece of bread,

222
00:17:02,220 --> 00:17:06,680
which he pushed into his mouth, before calling
Mary to the table.

223
00:17:06,680 --> 00:17:13,500
'You need food, I can see that,' he said,
and carefully buttered the loaf.

224
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:21,310
He cut a thin piece from it and then cut this
into four quarters for her, the whole business

225
00:17:21,310 --> 00:17:27,500
very delicately done and quite different from
his manner in serving himself - so much, so

226
00:17:27,500 --> 00:17:34,500
that to Mary there was something almost frightening
in the change from roughness to gentle care.

227
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:39,540
It was as if there was some power in his fingers,
which turned them suddenly, and unexpectedly

228
00:17:39,540 --> 00:17:41,260
into skilful servants.

229
00:17:41,260 --> 00:17:50,330
'Patience,' he said, 'here's the key Go and
get me a bottle, in the Lords name - I've

230
00:17:50,330 --> 00:17:52,220
a terrible thirst!'

231
00:17:52,220 --> 00:17:59,600
In a few minutes his wife returned with the
alcohol, which she put in front of her husband,

232
00:17:59,600 --> 00:18:05,920
and while she finished her cooking and served
Mary and herself, he began drinking, kicking

233
00:18:05,920 --> 00:18:09,050
the leg of the table.

234
00:18:09,050 --> 00:18:14,600
Suddenly he struck the table with his hand,
shaking the plates and cups; one fell to the

235
00:18:14,600 --> 00:18:16,330
ground and broke.

236
00:18:16,330 --> 00:18:25,710
'I'll tell you something, Mary Yellan,' he
shouted, 'I'm master in this house, and I

237
00:18:25,710 --> 00:18:27,180
want you to know it.

238
00:18:27,180 --> 00:18:34,700
You'll do as you're told, and help in the
house and serve in the bar, and I'll not lay

239
00:18:34,700 --> 00:18:36,720
a finger on you.

240
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:43,400
But, by God, if you open your mouth, I'll
punish you until you eat out of my hand the

241
00:18:43,400 --> 00:18:47,060
same as your aunt there.'

242
00:18:47,060 --> 00:18:49,760
Mary faced him across the table.

243
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:54,610
She held her hands below the table so that
he could not see them tremble.

244
00:18:54,610 --> 00:18:57,930
'I understand you,' she said.

245
00:18:57,930 --> 00:19:01,530
'It doesn't matter to me what you do in the
inn.

246
00:19:01,530 --> 00:19:05,960
I'll do my work in the house, and you'll have
no cause to complain.

247
00:19:05,960 --> 00:19:14,480
But if you hurt my Aunt Patience in any way,
I tell you this - I'll leave Jamaica Inn immediately,

248
00:19:14,480 --> 00:19:20,290
and I'll find a magistrate and bring him here,
and use the law against you; and then try

249
00:19:20,290 --> 00:19:23,820
to punish me if you like!'

250
00:19:23,820 --> 00:19:26,630
Mary had turned very pale.

251
00:19:26,630 --> 00:19:32,180
She did not know it, but she had saved herself;
her little show of courage had an effect on

252
00:19:32,180 --> 00:19:36,080
the man, who leant back in his chair and relaxed.

253
00:19:36,080 --> 00:19:41,260
'That's very pretty,' he said; 'very prettily
put.

254
00:19:41,260 --> 00:19:47,910
Now we know just what sort of visitor we have.

255
00:19:47,910 --> 00:19:53,830
Make her angry, and she shows her teeth.

256
00:19:53,830 --> 00:19:59,570
All right, my dear; you and I are more like
each other than I thought.

257
00:19:59,570 --> 00:20:06,280
If we're going to play, we'll play together.

258
00:20:06,280 --> 00:20:14,640
I may have work for you at Jamaica Inn one
day, work that you've never done before.

259
00:20:14,640 --> 00:20:23,200
Man's work, Mary Yellan, where you play with
life and death.'

260
00:20:23,200 --> 00:20:27,430
Mary heard a faint cry from Aunt Patience
beside her.

261
00:20:27,430 --> 00:20:30,870
'Oh, Joss,' she whispered.

262
00:20:30,870 --> 00:20:34,170
'Oh, Joss, please!'

263
00:20:34,170 --> 00:20:40,460
There was so much fear in her voice that Mary
looked at her in surprise.

264
00:20:40,460 --> 00:20:42,460
Her uncle waved his hand impatiently.

265
00:20:42,460 --> 00:20:46,530
'Get up to bed, Patience,' he said.

266
00:20:46,530 --> 00:20:51,180
'I'm tired of your miserable face at my supper
table.

267
00:20:51,180 --> 00:20:55,690
This girl and I understand each other.

268
00:20:55,690 --> 00:21:01,260
The woman rose immediately and went to the
door.

269
00:21:01,260 --> 00:21:06,190
After a last helpless look over her shoulder,
she went upstairs.

270
00:21:06,190 --> 00:21:10,100
Joss Merlyn and Mary were alone.

271
00:21:10,100 --> 00:21:14,290
He pushed the empty glass away from him and
folded his arms on the table.

272
00:21:14,290 --> 00:21:21,620
'There's been one weakness in my life, and
I'll tell you what it is.

273
00:21:21,620 --> 00:21:22,620
It's drink.

274
00:21:22,620 --> 00:21:26,250
It's a curse, and I know it.

275
00:21:26,250 --> 00:21:28,730
I can't stop myself.

276
00:21:28,730 --> 00:21:34,250
One day it will be the end of me, and a good
thing too.

277
00:21:34,250 --> 00:21:38,320
Days go by and I don't touch more than a drop.

278
00:21:38,320 --> 00:21:46,530
And then I'll feel the thirst come on me and
I'll drink - drink for hours.

279
00:21:46,530 --> 00:21:53,230
I talk then - talk until everything I've done
is told to the four winds.

280
00:21:53,230 --> 00:21:57,910
I've told you because I've already had too
much and I can't hold my tongue.

281
00:21:57,910 --> 00:22:02,520
But I've not lost control of my head.

282
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:10,080
I've not had enough to tell you why I live
in this forgotten place, and why I'm the landlord

283
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:13,390
of Jamaica Inn.'

284
00:22:13,390 --> 00:22:16,070
His voice was hardly more than a whisper.

285
00:22:16,070 --> 00:22:22,180
The fire had sunk low, and dark shadows stretched
long fingers on the wall.

286
00:22:22,180 --> 00:22:28,630
The light on the table threw a great, ugly
shadow of Joss Merlyn on the ceiling.

287
00:22:28,630 --> 00:22:31,370
The coaches don't stop here now.

288
00:22:31,370 --> 00:22:34,280
I don't worry; I've visitors enough.

289
00:22:34,280 --> 00:22:42,750
The farther the gentlemen keep away, the better
pleased I am.

290
00:22:42,750 --> 00:22:48,530
Ah, there's drinking here all right, and plenty
of it too.

291
00:22:48,530 --> 00:22:55,870
There are some who come to Jamaica Inn on
Saturday night, and there are some who turn

292
00:22:55,870 --> 00:23:02,390
the key of their door and sleep with their
fingers in their ears.

293
00:23:02,390 --> 00:23:08,260
There are nights when every house on the moors
is dark and silent, and the only lights for

294
00:23:08,260 --> 00:23:11,710
miles are the windows of Jamaica Inn.

295
00:23:11,710 --> 00:23:19,750
They say the shouting and the singing can
be heard as far down as the farms below Roughtor.

296
00:23:19,750 --> 00:23:28,340
You'll be in the bar those nights, if you
like, and you'll see what company I keep.'

297
00:23:28,340 --> 00:23:33,720
Mary sat very still, holding tightly to the
sides of her chair.

298
00:23:33,720 --> 00:23:41,720
'They're all afraid of me,' he went on; 'the
whole cursed lot of them.

299
00:23:41,720 --> 00:23:46,060
Afraid of me, who's afraid of no man.

300
00:23:46,060 --> 00:23:50,320
It's the drink that's been against me.

301
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:51,890
Drink and my hot blood.

302
00:23:51,890 --> 00:23:56,380
It's the curse of all of us, Mary.

303
00:23:56,380 --> 00:24:01,870
There's never been a Merlyn yet that died
peaceful in his bed.

304
00:24:01,870 --> 00:24:09,070
'My father was hanged at Exeter - he had a
quarrel with a man, and killed him.

305
00:24:09,070 --> 00:24:18,110
I'm the oldest of three brothers, all born
under the shadow of Kilman You walk out over

306
00:24:18,110 --> 00:24:24,970
there across the moor, and you'll see a great
rock like a devil's hand sticking up into

307
00:24:24,970 --> 00:24:26,130
the sky.

308
00:24:26,130 --> 00:24:35,520
That's Kilman If you'd been born under its
shadow you'd start to drink, as I did.

309
00:24:35,520 --> 00:24:39,480
My brother Matthew was drowned in Trewartha
Marsh.

310
00:24:39,480 --> 00:24:47,780
We thought he'd gone to be a sailor, and had
no news of him, and then in the summer no

311
00:24:47,780 --> 00:24:54,710
rain fell for seven months, and there was
Matthew sticking up in the marsh, with his

312
00:24:54,710 --> 00:24:59,950
hands above his head, and the birds flying
round him.

313
00:24:59,950 --> 00:25:03,390
My brother Jem was the baby.

314
00:25:03,390 --> 00:25:07,480
Hanging on to mother's skirts when Matthew
and I were grown men.

315
00:25:07,480 --> 00:25:11,320
I never did agree with Jem.

316
00:25:11,320 --> 00:25:16,220
Too clever he is - too quick with his tongue.

317
00:25:16,220 --> 00:25:21,970
Oh, they will catch him in time and hang him,
as they did my father.'

318
00:25:21,970 --> 00:25:26,640
He was silent, looking into his empty glass.

319
00:25:26,640 --> 00:25:28,610
'I've said enough.

320
00:25:28,610 --> 00:25:32,000
I'll have no more tonight.

321
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:33,830
Go up to bed, Mary.

322
00:25:33,830 --> 00:25:39,430
You 11 find your room above the front door.'

323
00:25:39,430 --> 00:25:47,000
Mary was about to pass him when he seized
hold of her shoulder and twisted her round.

324
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:54,700
'There'll be nights sometimes when you hear
wheels on the road,' he said, 'and those wheels

325
00:25:54,700 --> 00:26:00,050
will not pass on, but they'll stop outside
Jamaica Inn.

326
00:26:00,050 --> 00:26:06,140
And you'll hear footsteps in the yard, and
voices beneath your window.

327
00:26:06,140 --> 00:26:13,480
When that happens, you'll stay in bed, Mary
Yellan, and cover your head with the bedclothes.

328
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:16,120
Do you understand?'

329
00:26:16,120 --> 00:26:17,890
'Yes, uncle.'

330
00:26:17,890 --> 00:26:19,650
'Very well.

331
00:26:19,650 --> 00:26:29,730
Now go, and if you ever ask me a question
'I'll break every bone in your body.'

332
00:26:29,730 --> 00:26:36,370
She went out of the room, into the dark passage
and up the stairs, feeling the wall with her

333
00:26:36,370 --> 00:26:37,890
hands.

334
00:26:37,890 --> 00:26:41,430
Her uncle had told her that her room was over
the front door.

335
00:26:41,430 --> 00:26:44,290
Her box lay on the floor.

336
00:26:44,290 --> 00:26:49,320
The walls were rough and unpapered and the
floorboards dirty.

337
00:26:49,320 --> 00:26:54,851
A box turned on its side served as a table,
with a cracked mirror on top.

338
00:26:54,851 --> 00:27:01,380
The thin bedclothes were not dry enough to
sleep under.

339
00:27:01,380 --> 00:27:04,480
She went to the window and looked out.

340
00:27:04,480 --> 00:27:11,330
The wind had gone down, but it was still raining
- a thin, miserable rain that ran down the

341
00:27:11,330 --> 00:27:15,440
side of the house and mixed with the dirt
on the window.

342
00:27:15,440 --> 00:27:22,100
Whatever she would have to face in the future,
and no matter how frightened she might be,

343
00:27:22,100 --> 00:27:24,429
she would not leave Jamaica Inn now.

344
00:27:24,429 --> 00:27:27,540
She must stay with Aunt Patience.

345
00:27:27,540 --> 00:27:28,760
She was needed here.

346
00:27:28,760 --> 00:27:36,300
And so Mary lay, fully dressed, on her hard
bed, her mind working while she prayed for

347
00:27:36,300 --> 00:27:37,300
sleep.

348
00:27:37,300 --> 00:27:43,530
She counted the minutes and the hours of an
endless night, and when the first bird sang

349
00:27:43,530 --> 00:27:52,980
in the field behind the house she counted
no more, but slept like a dead thing.

350
00:27:52,980 --> 00:27:57,470
CHAPTER THREE
The Locked Door

351
00:27:57,470 --> 00:28:02,810
Mary woke to a high wind from the west, and
a thin watery sun.

352
00:28:02,810 --> 00:28:09,000
After breakfast, during the usual morning
housework, Mary was able to explore the Inn

353
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:10,240
more thoroughly.

354
00:28:10,240 --> 00:28:16,800
It was a dark place, with long passages and
unexpected rooms.

355
00:28:16,800 --> 00:28:21,550
There was a separate entrance to the bar at
the side of the house, and though the room

356
00:28:21,550 --> 00:28:27,910
was empty now, there was something heavy in
the air from the last time it was full - a

357
00:28:27,910 --> 00:28:34,740
taste of old tobacco, the sour smell of drink
and the suggestion of warm, unclean people

358
00:28:34,740 --> 00:28:40,430
crowded one against the other on the dark
wooden seats.

359
00:28:40,430 --> 00:28:45,880
Down a passage in the opposite direction from
the kitchen was another room, the door of

360
00:28:45,880 --> 00:28:47,820
which was locked.

361
00:28:47,820 --> 00:28:53,809
Mary went out into the yard to look at it
through the window, but there was a board

362
00:28:53,809 --> 00:28:58,860
nailed up against the window frame, and she
could not see inside.

363
00:28:58,860 --> 00:29:04,820
The house and other buildings formed three
sides of the square that was the little yard.

364
00:29:04,820 --> 00:29:10,870
Beyond this lay the road, a thin white track
that stretched to the horizon, surrounded

365
00:29:10,870 --> 00:29:17,140
on each side by the moors, brown and wet from
the heavy rains.

366
00:29:17,140 --> 00:29:22,870
Mary went out on the road and looked round
her, and as far as the eye could see, there

367
00:29:22,870 --> 00:29:26,480
was nothing but the black hills and the moors.

368
00:29:26,480 --> 00:29:35,240
The grey stone inn, with its tall chimneys,
was the only house in view.

369
00:29:35,240 --> 00:29:38,780
She went back into the house to find Aunt
Patience.

370
00:29:38,780 --> 00:29:46,190
'Aunt Patience,' she began, 'why is my uncle
the landlord of Jamaica Inn?'

371
00:29:46,190 --> 00:29:52,940
The sudden direct attack took the woman by
surprise, and for a moment, she looked back

372
00:29:52,940 --> 00:29:54,920
at Mary without reply.

373
00:29:54,920 --> 00:29:57,890
Then she went red.

374
00:29:57,890 --> 00:30:06,559
'Well,' she said, 'it's - it's a very important
place here, on the road.

375
00:30:06,559 --> 00:30:09,040
You can see that.

376
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:11,940
This is the main road from the south.

377
00:30:11,940 --> 00:30:14,170
The coaches pass here twice a week.

378
00:30:14,170 --> 00:30:16,500
There are always travellers on the road.

379
00:30:16,500 --> 00:30:19,800
We do good trade here.'

380
00:30:19,800 --> 00:30:28,110
'How can you say that, when the rooms are
never used, and the bedrooms are fit only

381
00:30:28,110 --> 00:30:29,730
for rats and mice?

382
00:30:29,730 --> 00:30:33,390
I've seen them for myself.'

383
00:30:33,390 --> 00:30:39,500
Her aunt was silent for a moment, working
her mouth and twisting her fingers together.

384
00:30:39,500 --> 00:30:45,880
'Your Uncle Joss doesn't encourage people
to stay.

385
00:30:45,880 --> 00:30:50,670
We do a good trade, I've told you that.

386
00:30:50,670 --> 00:30:54,410
Men come in from the farms.

387
00:30:54,410 --> 00:31:02,910
There are farms and houses scattered all over
the moors for miles around, and men come from

388
00:31:02,910 --> 00:31:05,060
there for a drink.

389
00:31:05,060 --> 00:31:09,360
There are evenings when the bar is full.'

390
00:31:09,360 --> 00:31:14,660
'The driver of the coach yesterday said that
respectable people did not come to Jamaica

391
00:31:14,660 --> 00:31:15,750
Inn any more.

392
00:31:15,750 --> 00:31:19,940
He said they were afraid.'

393
00:31:19,940 --> 00:31:22,090
Aunt Patience changed colour.

394
00:31:22,090 --> 00:31:27,640
She was pale now, and her eyes moved from
side to side.

395
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:32,470
She swallowed, and ran her tongue over her
lips.

396
00:31:32,470 --> 00:31:40,900
'Your Uncle Joss has a quick temper,' she
said; 'you have seen that for yourself.

397
00:31:40,900 --> 00:31:43,530
He is easily angered.'

398
00:31:43,530 --> 00:31:48,130
Her eyes begged to be excused further questioning.

399
00:31:48,130 --> 00:31:54,520
Mary saw that she had suffered enough, but
tried one more question.

400
00:31:54,520 --> 00:32:02,140
'Aunt Patience,' she said, 'I want you to
look at me and answer me this, and then I

401
00:32:02,140 --> 00:32:03,980
won't worry you again.

402
00:32:03,980 --> 00:32:10,270
What has the locked room at the end of the
passage to do with the wheels that stop outside

403
00:32:10,270 --> 00:32:12,420
Jamaica Inn by night?'

404
00:32:12,420 --> 00:32:17,080
As soon as she had spoken, she was sorry.

405
00:32:17,080 --> 00:32:23,610
A strange expression came over the woman's
face, and her great hollow eyes looked across

406
00:32:23,610 --> 00:32:26,210
the table in fear.

407
00:32:26,210 --> 00:32:30,490
Her mouth trembled, and one hand wandered
to her throat.

408
00:32:30,490 --> 00:32:36,559
Mary pushed back her chair and knelt by her
side.

409
00:32:36,559 --> 00:32:42,880
She put her arms around Aunt Patience, and
held her close, and kissed her hair.

410
00:32:42,880 --> 00:32:46,649
'I'm sorry,' she said.

411
00:32:46,649 --> 00:32:48,200
'Don't be angry with me.

412
00:32:48,200 --> 00:32:54,910
It's not my business, and I've no right to
question you, and I'm ashamed of myself.

413
00:32:54,910 --> 00:32:57,720
Please, please forget what I said.'

414
00:32:57,720 --> 00:33:02,780
Her aunt buried her face in her hands.

415
00:33:02,780 --> 00:33:08,850
Then she looked over her shoulder, as if she
were afraid that Joss himself stood in the

416
00:33:08,850 --> 00:33:11,130
shadows behind the door.

417
00:33:11,130 --> 00:33:18,490
'Things happen at Jamaica Inn, Mary that I've
never dared to breathe a word about.

418
00:33:18,490 --> 00:33:20,190
Bad things.

419
00:33:20,190 --> 00:33:21,890
Evil things.

420
00:33:21,890 --> 00:33:25,320
I can't ever tell you.

421
00:33:25,320 --> 00:33:28,040
I can't even admit them to myself.

422
00:33:28,040 --> 00:33:35,890
Some of it you'll come to know in time.

423
00:33:35,890 --> 00:33:38,200
You can't avoid it, living here.

424
00:33:38,200 --> 00:33:46,630
Your Uncle Joss mixes with strange men, who
follow a strange trade.

425
00:33:46,630 --> 00:33:54,429
Sometimes they come by night, and from your
window you will hear footsteps, and voices,

426
00:33:54,429 --> 00:33:57,460
and knocking at the door.

427
00:33:57,460 --> 00:34:04,000
Your uncle lets them in, and he takes them
along the passage to that room with the locked

428
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:05,000
door.

429
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:11,110
Before day, they are gone, and no sign is
left that they have ever been.

430
00:34:11,110 --> 00:34:17,580
When they come, Mary, you will say nothing
to me or to your Uncle Joss.

431
00:34:17,580 --> 00:34:23,030
You must lie in bed and put your hands over
your ears.'

432
00:34:23,030 --> 00:34:31,600
Then she rose from the table, and pushed her
chair back, and Mary heard her climb the stairs

433
00:34:31,600 --> 00:34:34,490
with heavy feet.

434
00:34:34,490 --> 00:34:40,359
Joss Merlyn was away from the house for nearly
a week, and during that time, Mary learnt

435
00:34:40,359 --> 00:34:43,590
something about the area.

436
00:34:43,590 --> 00:34:48,730
After helping her aunt in the house and kitchen,
she was free to wander where she pleased.

437
00:34:48,730 --> 00:34:54,470
The moors were even wilder than she had at
first supposed.

438
00:34:54,470 --> 00:35:01,720
Like a wide desert, they rolled from east
to west, with paths here and there across

439
00:35:01,720 --> 00:35:06,800
the surface, and great hills breaking the
skyline.

440
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:14,880
It was a silent, empty country, untouched
by human hand; on the high tors the stones

441
00:35:14,880 --> 00:35:20,990
leant against one another in strange shapes,
great watchmen who had stood there since the

442
00:35:20,990 --> 00:35:24,870
hand of God first formed them.

443
00:35:24,870 --> 00:35:27,190
Wild sheep lived on the high tors.

444
00:35:27,190 --> 00:35:34,920
Black cattle fed on the moors beneath, their
careful feet choosing the firm ground, as

445
00:35:34,920 --> 00:35:41,700
with inborn knowledge they avoided the long,
green grass that was not grass at all, but

446
00:35:41,700 --> 00:35:43,980
soft, dangerous marsh.

447
00:35:43,980 --> 00:35:51,359
There was a silence on the tors that belonged
to another age; an age that is past and gone

448
00:35:51,359 --> 00:35:57,950
as though it had never been, an age when man
did not exist.

449
00:35:57,950 --> 00:36:03,590
One day Mary crossed the East Moor, in the
direction that Joss had described to her on

450
00:36:03,590 --> 00:36:09,870
the first evening; and when she had gone some
way and stood alone on a hill, surrounded

451
00:36:09,870 --> 00:36:16,800
on all sides by empty moors, she saw that
the land sloped down to a deep and dangerous

452
00:36:16,800 --> 00:36:19,960
marsh, through which ran a stream.

453
00:36:19,960 --> 00:36:27,250
And rising beyond the marsh, away on the other
side, pointing its fingers to the sky, was

454
00:36:27,250 --> 00:36:34,960
a great rock like a broken hand coming straight
out of the moor, its surface neatly formed

455
00:36:34,960 --> 00:36:37,540
as if cut by an artist.

456
00:36:37,540 --> 00:36:47,109
So this was Kilmar Tor; and somewhere over
there, where the hills hid the sun, Joss Merlyn

457
00:36:47,109 --> 00:36:50,170
had been born and his brother lived today.

458
00:36:50,170 --> 00:36:56,369
Below her in the marsh, Matthew Merlyn had
been drowned.

459
00:36:56,369 --> 00:37:04,590
Mary turned her back on Kilmar and began to
run across the moor; nor did she stop until

460
00:37:04,590 --> 00:37:11,180
the marsh disappeared below the level of the
hill, and the tor itself was hidden.

461
00:37:11,180 --> 00:37:16,140
She had come farther than she had intended,
and the way home was long.

462
00:37:16,140 --> 00:37:22,340
It seemed an age before the last hill was
behind her, and the tall chimneys of Jamaica

463
00:37:22,340 --> 00:37:24,920
Inn stood out in front of her.

464
00:37:24,920 --> 00:37:31,790
As she crossed the yard, she noticed with
a sinking heart that the stable door was open,

465
00:37:31,790 --> 00:37:34,760
and the horse was inside.

466
00:37:34,760 --> 00:37:36,440
Joss Merlyn had returned.

467
00:37:36,440 --> 00:37:43,680
She opened the door as silently as possible,
but it rubbed against the stone floor and

468
00:37:43,680 --> 00:37:45,510
made a noise in protest.

469
00:37:45,510 --> 00:37:51,930
In a moment, the landlord appeared and called
to her as she started up the stairs to her

470
00:37:51,930 --> 00:37:52,930
room.

471
00:37:52,930 --> 00:37:57,530
'Here,' he said, 'no hiding up there this
evening.

472
00:37:57,530 --> 00:38:01,540
There will be work for you in the bar, with
your uncle.

473
00:38:01,540 --> 00:38:06,360
Don't you know what day of the week it is?'

474
00:38:06,360 --> 00:38:08,690
Mary paused to think.

475
00:38:08,690 --> 00:38:11,060
She was losing count of time.

476
00:38:11,060 --> 00:38:13,640
Was it Monday's coach she had taken?

477
00:38:13,640 --> 00:38:19,640
That made today Saturday - Saturday night.

478
00:38:19,640 --> 00:38:23,870
Immediately she realized what Joss Merlyn
meant.

479
00:38:23,870 --> 00:38:31,270
Tonight there would be company at Jamaica
Inn.

480
00:38:31,270 --> 00:38:35,740
CHAPTER FOUR
Wagons in the Night

481
00:38:35,740 --> 00:38:42,400
They came one by one, the people of the moors,
crossing the yard quickly and silently, as

482
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:44,400
If they had no wish to be seen.

483
00:38:44,400 --> 00:38:50,040
They were a strange collection grouped around
Joss Merlyn in the bar.

484
00:38:50,040 --> 00:38:56,460
Half hidden by rows of bottles and glasses,
Mary could look down on the company and remain

485
00:38:56,460 --> 00:38:57,460
unseen.

486
00:38:57,460 --> 00:39:05,151
They lay on the seats; they leant against
the walls; they sat beside the tables; and

487
00:39:05,151 --> 00:39:11,180
one or two, whose heads or stomachs were weaker
than the rest, already lay full length on

488
00:39:11,180 --> 00:39:12,230
the floor.

489
00:39:12,230 --> 00:39:17,610
Most of them were dirty, with long hair and
broken fingernails: cattle-stealers, sailors,

490
00:39:17,610 --> 00:39:18,610
wandering salesmen, thieves.

491
00:39:18,610 --> 00:39:27,590
The 
smell of drink and tobacco and unwashed bodies

492
00:39:27,590 --> 00:39:30,040
was strong.

493
00:39:30,040 --> 00:39:35,420
Mary felt disgust rise up in her, and she
knew that she would give way to it if she

494
00:39:35,420 --> 00:39:37,040
stayed there long.

495
00:39:37,040 --> 00:39:41,480
The evening seemed endless, and her one thought
was of escape.

496
00:39:41,480 --> 00:39:48,180
The air was so thick with smoke and breath
that it was hard to see across the room, and

497
00:39:48,180 --> 00:39:56,770
to her tired, half-closed eyes the faces of
the men seemed shapeless, all hair and teeth,

498
00:39:56,770 --> 00:40:01,960
their mouths much too large for their bodies,
while those who had drunk too much lay on

499
00:40:01,960 --> 00:40:08,970
the seats or on the floor like dead men, their
faces in their hands.

500
00:40:08,970 --> 00:40:15,230
Those who could still stand had crowded round
a dirty little pedlar from Redruth, who had

501
00:40:15,230 --> 00:40:18,470
made himself the joker of the group.

502
00:40:18,470 --> 00:40:24,180
The mine where he had worked was now in ruins,
and he had taken to the road as a pedlar,

503
00:40:24,180 --> 00:40:29,360
and had stored up a collection of songs with
which he now entertained the company.

504
00:40:29,360 --> 00:40:34,619
The laughter that greeted his rude songs and
jokes nearly shook the roof.

505
00:40:34,619 --> 00:40:41,910
To Mary there was something horrible in this
ugly, shouting laughter, which in some strange

506
00:40:41,910 --> 00:40:49,230
way held no note of amusement, but rang down
the dark stone passages and into the empty

507
00:40:49,230 --> 00:40:53,490
rooms above, filling them with hopelessness.

508
00:40:53,490 --> 00:40:56,380
Mary could bear it no longer.

509
00:40:56,380 --> 00:41:01,510
She touched her uncle on the shoulder, and
he turned to her, his face red with the heat

510
00:41:01,510 --> 00:41:02,930
of the room.

511
00:41:02,930 --> 00:41:06,810
'I can't stand this,' she said.

512
00:41:06,810 --> 00:41:10,240
'You'll have to serve your friends yourself.

513
00:41:10,240 --> 00:41:12,040
I'm going upstairs to my room.'

514
00:41:12,040 --> 00:41:16,190
'Had enough of it, have you?

515
00:41:16,190 --> 00:41:18,780
Think yourself too good for us?

516
00:41:18,780 --> 00:41:26,060
Get out, then; it's nearly midnight, in any
case, and I don't want you.

517
00:41:26,060 --> 00:41:29,440
You'll lock your door tonight, Mary.

518
00:41:29,440 --> 00:41:35,780
Your aunt's been in bed for an hour with the
bedclothes over her head.'

519
00:41:35,780 --> 00:41:42,570
He lowered his voice; bending down to her
ear and seizing her wrist, he twisted it behind

520
00:41:42,570 --> 00:41:45,890
her back until she cried out in pain.

521
00:41:45,890 --> 00:41:51,390
'Keep your mouth shut and I'll treat you gently.

522
00:41:51,390 --> 00:42:00,720
It is unwise to put your nose in where it
is not wanted at Jamaica Inn, and you'd better

523
00:42:00,720 --> 00:42:02,780
remember that.'

524
00:42:02,780 --> 00:42:11,730
Mary ran out of the room, shutting the door
hard behind her, and as she went up the stairs,

525
00:42:11,730 --> 00:42:16,660
her hands over her ears, she could not keep
out that sound of laughter and wild singing

526
00:42:16,660 --> 00:42:22,470
that sounded down the empty passage, following
her to her room and even coming up through

527
00:42:22,470 --> 00:42:25,120
the cracks between the floorboards.

528
00:42:25,120 --> 00:42:28,360
Then she did as her uncle had told her.

529
00:42:28,360 --> 00:42:35,210
She undressed hurriedly and crept into bed,
pulling the bedclothes over her head and putting

530
00:42:35,210 --> 00:42:42,930
her fingers in her ears, her only thought
now to shut out the noise below.

531
00:42:42,930 --> 00:42:44,170
She slept.

532
00:42:44,170 --> 00:42:50,580
Then, without warning, she was suddenly awake,
sitting up in bed.

533
00:42:50,580 --> 00:42:58,310
She listened, hearing nothing at first except
the beating of her own heart, but in a few

534
00:42:58,310 --> 00:43:06,160
minutes there came another sound, from beneath
her room this time - the sound of heavy objects

535
00:43:06,160 --> 00:43:11,820
being dragged along the stone floor in the
passage downstairs.

536
00:43:11,820 --> 00:43:17,550
She got out of bed and went to the window,
opening the shutters a crack.

537
00:43:17,550 --> 00:43:22,940
By the light of the moon, she could see five
wagons in the yard outside.

538
00:43:22,940 --> 00:43:30,700
Three were covered, each pulled by a pair
of horses, and the remaining two were not.

539
00:43:30,700 --> 00:43:37,540
One of the covered wagons stood directly beneath
the window, and the horses were steaming.

540
00:43:37,540 --> 00:43:41,460
Around the wagons were some of the men who
had been drinking in the bar earlier in the

541
00:43:41,460 --> 00:43:42,460
evening.

542
00:43:42,460 --> 00:43:48,300
And there were strangers in the yard whom
Mary had never seen before.

543
00:43:48,300 --> 00:43:52,510
She watched and began to understand.

544
00:43:52,510 --> 00:43:56,840
Packages and boxes were brought by the wagons
and unloaded at Jamaica Inn.

545
00:43:56,840 --> 00:44:01,140
They were now being stored in the locked room.

546
00:44:01,140 --> 00:44:07,540
Everything was done in complete silence; the
men who had shouted and sung earlier that

547
00:44:07,540 --> 00:44:15,340
night were now quiet and serious, their thoughts
on nothing but the job.

548
00:44:15,340 --> 00:44:20,859
Joss Merlyn came out of the front door, the
pedlar at his side.

549
00:44:20,859 --> 00:44:28,369
'Is that everything?' he called softly, and
the driver of the last wagon waved and held

550
00:44:28,369 --> 00:44:30,700
up his hand.

551
00:44:30,700 --> 00:44:37,230
So the wagons moved away from Jamaica Inn,
moving out of the yard one after another,

552
00:44:37,230 --> 00:44:42,990
some turning north and some south when they
came out on to the road, until they had all

553
00:44:42,990 --> 00:44:48,760
gone, and there was no one left standing in
the yard but one man whom Mary had not seen

554
00:44:48,760 --> 00:44:53,440
before, the pedlar, and the landlord of Jamaica
Inn himself.

555
00:44:53,440 --> 00:44:58,780
Then they, too, turned and went back into
the house.

556
00:44:58,780 --> 00:45:04,270
She heard them go along the passage in the
direction of the bar, and then a door closed.

557
00:45:04,270 --> 00:45:09,930
There was no other sound except that of the
big clock in the hall, which rang the hour

558
00:45:09,930 --> 00:45:14,440
- three o'clock.

559
00:45:14,440 --> 00:45:18,080
Mary came away from the window and sat down
on the bed.

560
00:45:18,080 --> 00:45:23,930
The cold air blew in onto her shoulders, and
she trembled.

561
00:45:23,930 --> 00:45:27,290
This was smuggling on a grand scale.

562
00:45:27,290 --> 00:45:33,859
Had Joss Merlyn the necessary brain and skills
to lead such a business?

563
00:45:33,859 --> 00:45:39,030
Had he been making preparations for tonight's
work during the past week, when he was away

564
00:45:39,030 --> 00:45:40,750
from home?

565
00:45:40,750 --> 00:45:47,820
The men working for him must be carefully
picked, in spite of their wild appearance,

566
00:45:47,820 --> 00:45:52,910
and the whole business carefully controlled,
or they could never have escaped the law for

567
00:45:52,910 --> 00:45:54,119
so long.

568
00:45:54,119 --> 00:46:01,710
A magistrate who suspected smuggling would
surely have suspected the inn unless he were

569
00:46:01,710 --> 00:46:03,690
involved himself.

570
00:46:03,690 --> 00:46:08,970
If it were not for Aunt Patience, she would
walk out of the inn now, find her way to the

571
00:46:08,970 --> 00:46:13,480
nearest town and give information about Joss
Merlyn.

572
00:46:13,480 --> 00:46:18,869
He would soon be in prison, and the rest of
them with him, and there would be an end to

573
00:46:18,869 --> 00:46:20,040
the trade.

574
00:46:20,040 --> 00:46:28,180
But had she seen only part of the business,
and was there still more for her to learn?

575
00:46:28,180 --> 00:46:33,970
She remembered the fear in Aunt Patience's
eyes, and those words spoken when the shadows

576
00:46:33,970 --> 00:46:41,600
crept across the kitchen floor: 'There are
things happen at Jamaica Inn, Mary that I've

577
00:46:41,600 --> 00:46:46,590
never dared to breathe a word about.

578
00:46:46,590 --> 00:46:48,380
Bad things.

579
00:46:48,380 --> 00:46:50,170
Evil things.

580
00:46:50,170 --> 00:46:52,170
I can't ever tell you.

581
00:46:52,170 --> 00:46:56,700
I can't even admit them to myself.'

582
00:46:56,700 --> 00:47:02,741
And she had climbed the stairs to her room,
dragging her feet as she went, like an old

583
00:47:02,741 --> 00:47:04,070
woman.

584
00:47:04,070 --> 00:47:11,580
Smuggling was dangerous; it was dishonest;
it was strictly forbidden by the law of the

585
00:47:11,580 --> 00:47:16,430
land; but was it evil?

586
00:47:16,430 --> 00:47:20,420
Mary needed advice, and there was no one she
could ask.

587
00:47:20,420 --> 00:47:27,060
Here she was, a girl of twenty-three, with
no weapons except her own brain to fight a

588
00:47:27,060 --> 00:47:32,150
man twice her size and eight times her strength.

589
00:47:32,150 --> 00:47:38,500
'I'll not show fear before Joss Merlyn or
any man,' she said.

590
00:47:38,500 --> 00:47:44,880
'I will go down now and take a look at them
in the bar, and if they kill me it will be

591
00:47:44,880 --> 00:47:47,040
my own fault.'

592
00:47:47,040 --> 00:47:54,000
She dressed hurriedly, and then, opening her
bedroom door, she stood and listened for a

593
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:58,910
moment, hearing nothing but the sound of the
clock in the hall.

594
00:47:58,910 --> 00:48:03,080
She crept out into the passage, and came to
the stairs.

595
00:48:03,080 --> 00:48:09,109
By now, she knew that the third step from
the top would make a noise, and so would the

596
00:48:09,109 --> 00:48:10,849
last.

597
00:48:10,849 --> 00:48:17,640
She stepped gently, and so she came to the
dark hall by the front door, empty except

598
00:48:17,640 --> 00:48:21,050
for one unsteady chair and the great clock.

599
00:48:21,050 --> 00:48:29,060
As she paused, a sudden beam of light shone
into the passage, and she heard voices.

600
00:48:29,060 --> 00:48:31,250
The door of the bar had swung open.

601
00:48:31,250 --> 00:48:37,690
The men must be sitting in silence on the
seats against the outside wall, because she

602
00:48:37,690 --> 00:48:40,750
could not see or hear them.

603
00:48:40,750 --> 00:48:48,270
Then suddenly a voice rang out, high and trembling,
the voice of a stranger.

604
00:48:48,270 --> 00:48:51,250
'No, and no again.

605
00:48:51,250 --> 00:48:55,310
I tell you for the last time, I'll have no
part in it.

606
00:48:55,310 --> 00:49:00,990
I'll break with you now, and forever, and
put an end to the agreement.

607
00:49:00,990 --> 00:49:06,570
That's murder you want me to do, Mr Merlyn;
there's no other name for it - it's common

608
00:49:06,570 --> 00:49:09,440
murder.'

609
00:49:09,440 --> 00:49:15,480
Someone - the landlord himself, no doubt - answered
in a low voice.

610
00:49:15,480 --> 00:49:21,250
Mary could not catch his words, but his speech
was broken by a burst of laughter that she

611
00:49:21,250 --> 00:49:24,230
recognized as belonging to the pedlar.

612
00:49:24,230 --> 00:49:30,180
He must have asked a question because the
stranger's voice was heard again.

613
00:49:30,180 --> 00:49:32,119
'Hanging, is it?

614
00:49:32,119 --> 00:49:36,180
I've risked hanging before, and I'm not afraid
for my neck.

615
00:49:36,180 --> 00:49:41,750
No, I'm thinking of my soul and of God above.

616
00:49:41,750 --> 00:49:47,849
When it comes to the killing of harmless people,
and perhaps women and children among them,

617
00:49:47,849 --> 00:49:54,630
that's evil, joss Merlyn, and you know it
as well as I do.'

618
00:49:54,630 --> 00:50:01,230
Mary heard the sound of a chair being pulled
back, and the man rising to his feet; then

619
00:50:01,230 --> 00:50:04,610
her uncle raised his voice for the first time.

620
00:50:04,610 --> 00:50:12,080
'Not so fast, my friend,' he said, 'not so
fast!

621
00:50:12,080 --> 00:50:16,210
You're in this business as far as you can
be.

622
00:50:16,210 --> 00:50:25,230
I tell you there's no going back now; it's
too late; too late for you and for all of

623
00:50:25,230 --> 00:50:26,230
us.

624
00:50:26,230 --> 00:50:31,859
I've been doubtful of you from the first,
with your gentleman's ways and your clean

625
00:50:31,859 --> 00:50:35,599
shirts, and by God I've proved myself right.

626
00:50:35,599 --> 00:50:40,740
Harry, lock the door over there and put the
bar across it.'

627
00:50:40,740 --> 00:50:48,609
There was a sudden cry, and the sound of someone
falling, and at the same time, the table crashed

628
00:50:48,609 --> 00:50:50,930
to the floor.

629
00:50:50,930 --> 00:50:56,220
Once more, the pedlar laughed his disgusting
laugh, and he began to whistle one of his

630
00:50:56,220 --> 00:50:57,220
songs.

631
00:50:57,220 --> 00:51:04,010
'Harry, stand where you are by the door, and
put your knife in him if he tries to pass

632
00:51:04,010 --> 00:51:05,010
you.

633
00:51:05,010 --> 00:51:14,160
Now, look here, Mr Lawyer-clerk, or whatever
you are, you've made a fool of yourself tonight,

634
00:51:14,160 --> 00:51:20,140
but you're not going to make a fool of me.

635
00:51:20,140 --> 00:51:25,770
You'd like to walk out of that door, wouldn't
you, and get on your horse, and ride away

636
00:51:25,770 --> 00:51:27,410
to Bodmin?

637
00:51:27,410 --> 00:51:34,940
Yes, and by nine in the morning you'd have
every magistrate in the country at Jamaica

638
00:51:34,940 --> 00:51:38,050
Inn, and a group of soldiers too.

639
00:51:38,050 --> 00:51:42,960
That's your fine idea, isn't it?'

640
00:51:42,960 --> 00:51:48,910
Mary could hear the stranger breathing heavily,
and he must have been hurt; for when his voice

641
00:51:48,910 --> 00:51:52,620
came, it was sharp but faint.

642
00:51:52,620 --> 00:51:55,350
'Do your devil's work if you must.

643
00:51:55,350 --> 00:52:01,270
I can't stop you, and I give you my word that
I'll not give information about you.

644
00:52:01,270 --> 00:52:07,750
But join you I will not, and there's my last
word to you both.'

645
00:52:07,750 --> 00:52:13,820
There was a silence, and then Joss Merlyn
spoke again.

646
00:52:13,820 --> 00:52:17,910
'Take care,' he said softly.

647
00:52:17,910 --> 00:52:26,610
'I heard another man say that once, and five
minutes later he was walking in air.

648
00:52:26,610 --> 00:52:33,859
On the end of a rope, it was, my friend, and
his big toe just missed the floor.

649
00:52:33,859 --> 00:52:40,720
I asked him if he liked to be so near the
ground, but he didn't answer.

650
00:52:40,720 --> 00:52:48,680
The rope forced the tongue out of his mouth,
and he bit it in two.

651
00:52:48,680 --> 00:52:57,420
They said afterwards that he had taken seven
and three-quarter minutes to die.'

652
00:52:57,420 --> 00:53:03,970
Outside in the passage, Mary felt herself
go cold and her arms and legs were suddenly

653
00:53:03,970 --> 00:53:05,320
as heavy as lead.

654
00:53:05,320 --> 00:53:12,940
With a growing sense of fear she realized
that she was probably going to faint.

655
00:53:12,940 --> 00:53:16,200
Her uncle's voice came from very far away.

656
00:53:16,200 --> 00:53:20,130
'Leave me alone with him, Harry,' he said.

657
00:53:20,130 --> 00:53:24,940
'There'll be no more work for you tonight
at Jamaica Inn.

658
00:53:24,940 --> 00:53:28,010
Take his horse and go.

659
00:53:28,010 --> 00:53:31,599
I'll settle this business by myself.'

660
00:53:31,599 --> 00:53:39,170
Somehow, Mary found her way back down the
passage and, hardly knowing what she was doing,

661
00:53:39,170 --> 00:53:44,280
she turned the handle of a door in the hall
and fell inside.

662
00:53:44,280 --> 00:53:51,250
She must have fainted and been unconscious
for a minute or two, before she sat up again.

663
00:53:51,250 --> 00:53:56,950
She heard the sound of a horse in the yard
outside, Harry the pedlar riding away, and

664
00:53:56,950 --> 00:54:00,500
then a sound from above made her lift her
head.

665
00:54:00,500 --> 00:54:07,260
A floorboard once, and then again: quiet footsteps
above.

666
00:54:07,260 --> 00:54:12,750
Mary's heart began to beat faster, and her
breath came quickly.

667
00:54:12,750 --> 00:54:16,940
Whoever was hiding up above must have been
there for hours.

668
00:54:16,940 --> 00:54:22,339
He must have hidden so that he would remain
unseen by the smugglers.

669
00:54:22,339 --> 00:54:27,980
Someone - a friend perhaps - was hiding in
the room next to her bedroom, and could help

670
00:54:27,980 --> 00:54:30,490
her to save the stranger in the bar.

671
00:54:30,490 --> 00:54:38,510
But as she waited, trembling, she heard the
landlord pass across the hall and climb the

672
00:54:38,510 --> 00:54:40,030
stairs.

673
00:54:40,030 --> 00:54:43,040
His footsteps stopped above her head.

674
00:54:43,040 --> 00:54:49,280
Then he knocked, very softly, on the door.

675
00:54:49,280 --> 00:54:55,000
Once more the floorboard made a noise as someone
crossed the floor, and the door was opened

676
00:54:55,000 --> 00:54:57,640
from inside.

677
00:54:57,640 --> 00:55:02,200
Mary's heart sank, and her misery returned.

678
00:55:02,200 --> 00:55:07,750
Her uncle had known him to be there all the
time and that was why he had sent the pedlar

679
00:55:07,750 --> 00:55:09,190
away.

680
00:55:09,190 --> 00:55:13,460
He did not wish the pedlar to see his friend.

681
00:55:13,460 --> 00:55:18,680
Now they were coming down the stairs; they
stopped for a moment outside the door of the

682
00:55:18,680 --> 00:55:24,270
room that Mary had entered, and for a moment,
she thought that they were coming inside.

683
00:55:24,270 --> 00:55:30,310
They were so close to her that she could have
touched her uncle on the shoulder through

684
00:55:30,310 --> 00:55:32,839
the crack of the door.

685
00:55:32,839 --> 00:55:37,620
Then he spoke, and his voice whispered right
against her ear.

686
00:55:37,620 --> 00:55:39,500
'You must say.

687
00:55:39,500 --> 00:55:43,980
It's your judgment now, not mine.

688
00:55:43,980 --> 00:55:47,500
I'll do it, or we'll do it between us.

689
00:55:47,500 --> 00:55:49,530
It's you who must say the word.'

690
00:55:49,530 --> 00:55:57,580
Hidden as she was by the door, Mary could
neither see nor hear her uncle's new companion,

691
00:55:57,580 --> 00:56:00,500
and whatever sign he made in reply escaped
her.

692
00:56:00,500 --> 00:56:06,710
They did not stay outside the room, but went
off along the passage to the bar.

693
00:56:06,710 --> 00:56:12,339
Then the door closed, and she heard them no
more.

694
00:56:12,339 --> 00:56:18,849
Her first desire was to run out into the road,
and so away from them, but she soon realized

695
00:56:18,849 --> 00:56:24,540
that by doing that she would gain nothing;
quite possibly there might be other men on

696
00:56:24,540 --> 00:56:27,160
guard along the high road.

697
00:56:27,160 --> 00:56:33,210
She must have stood for ten minutes or more
waiting for some sound or signal, but everything

698
00:56:33,210 --> 00:56:34,260
was still.

699
00:56:34,260 --> 00:56:40,869
Only the clock in the hall made its usual
noises, unaffected by events.

700
00:56:40,869 --> 00:56:44,480
Then she went out into the dark passage.

701
00:56:44,480 --> 00:56:49,300
No crack of light came out under the door
to the bar.

702
00:56:49,300 --> 00:56:51,440
She laid her ear against it.

703
00:56:51,440 --> 00:56:54,910
There was no sound.

704
00:56:54,910 --> 00:56:59,920
Through the keyhole came a steady current
of cold air.

705
00:56:59,920 --> 00:57:05,369
Mary thought for a moment; then she opened
the door and stepped into the room.

706
00:57:05,369 --> 00:57:08,000
There was nobody there.

707
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:15,380
The door leading to the yard was open, and
the room was filled with fresh November air.

708
00:57:15,380 --> 00:57:20,980
The seats were empty, and the table that had
crashed to the ground still lay on the floor,

709
00:57:20,980 --> 00:57:23,880
its legs pointing to the ceiling.

710
00:57:23,880 --> 00:57:31,230
A last little beam of moonlight made a white
circle on the floor, and into the circle moved

711
00:57:31,230 --> 00:57:34,970
a dark shape like a finger.

712
00:57:34,970 --> 00:57:37,670
It was a shadow.

713
00:57:37,670 --> 00:57:44,060
Mary looked up to the ceiling and saw that
a rope had been thrown over a hook in a beam.

714
00:57:44,060 --> 00:57:49,829
It was the rope's end that made the shadow
in the circle; and it kept moving backwards

715
00:57:49,829 --> 00:57:57,200
and forwards, blown by the wind from the open
door.

716
00:57:57,200 --> 00:57:59,840
CHAPTER FIVE
Jem Merlyn

717
00:57:59,840 --> 00:58:09,530
As the days passed, Mary Yellan settled down
to life at Jamaica Inn with a sense of determination.

718
00:58:09,530 --> 00:58:14,050
It was clear that she could not leave her
aunt to face the winter alone; she must make

719
00:58:14,050 --> 00:58:17,329
the best of the six months that lay ahead.

720
00:58:17,329 --> 00:58:23,820
If possible, she was determined to defeat
her uncle and deliver him and his companions

721
00:58:23,820 --> 00:58:24,820
to the law.

722
00:58:24,820 --> 00:58:31,010
The events of that first Saturday night were
never far from her mind, and the meaning of

723
00:58:31,010 --> 00:58:34,220
the rope's end hanging from the beam was clear.

724
00:58:34,220 --> 00:58:40,880
Mary had no doubt that the stranger had been
killed by her uncle and another man, and his

725
00:58:40,880 --> 00:58:43,660
body buried somewhere on the moors.

726
00:58:43,660 --> 00:58:50,980
There was nothing to prove it, though, and
in the light of day, the story seemed unlikely.

727
00:58:50,980 --> 00:58:57,350
Two weeks went by, and there was no Saturday
night like the first one.

728
00:58:57,350 --> 00:58:59,130
No one came to the inn.

729
00:58:59,130 --> 00:59:05,940
The future seemed very black at times, especially
as Aunt Patience made little effort to be

730
00:59:05,940 --> 00:59:11,589
a close companion; and though now and again
she took hold of Mary's hand, telling her

731
00:59:11,589 --> 00:59:17,570
how glad she was to have her in the house,
most of the time the poor woman existed in

732
00:59:17,570 --> 00:59:24,500
a dream, going about her duties without thinking
and rarely speaking.

733
00:59:24,500 --> 00:59:30,080
One morning Mary decided to clean down the
long stone passage that ran the full width

734
00:59:30,080 --> 00:59:31,970
of the back of the house.

735
00:59:31,970 --> 00:59:39,460
As she was doing this, she heard the sound
of a horse in the yard, and a moment later,

736
00:59:39,460 --> 00:59:42,020
someone thundered on the closed door of the
bar.

737
00:59:42,020 --> 00:59:50,580
No one had come near Jamaica Inn before, and
this knock on the door was an unusual event.

738
00:59:50,580 --> 00:59:53,490
Mary wiped her hands and went into the bar.

739
00:59:53,490 --> 01:00:02,180
A man was sitting there, with a glass in his
hand, which he had calmly filled for himself.

740
01:00:02,180 --> 01:00:05,240
For a few minutes, they considered each other
in silence.

741
01:00:05,240 --> 01:00:11,891
Something about him was familiar, and Mary
wondered where she had seen him before.

742
01:00:11,891 --> 01:00:20,510
The heavy eyes, the curve of his mouth, and
the shape of his jaw, even the look which

743
01:00:20,510 --> 01:00:23,810
he gave her, were known to her and disliked.

744
01:00:23,810 --> 01:00:30,960
The sight of him examining her and drinking
at the same time made her angry.

745
01:00:30,960 --> 01:00:34,220
'What do you think you're doing?' she said.

746
01:00:34,220 --> 01:00:38,829
'You haven't any right to walk in here and
help yourself.'

747
01:00:38,829 --> 01:00:44,370
The man finished his drink, and held out his
glass to be refilled.

748
01:00:44,370 --> 01:00:52,490
'Since when have they kept a bar girl at Jamaica
Inn?' he asked her, and, feeling in his pocket

749
01:00:52,490 --> 01:00:59,150
for a pipe, he lit it, blowing a great cloud
of smoke in her face.

750
01:00:59,150 --> 01:01:05,720
His manner angered Mary even more, and she
leant forward and pulled the pipe out of his

751
01:01:05,720 --> 01:01:09,710
hand, throwing it behind her onto the floor,
where it broke.

752
01:01:09,710 --> 01:01:14,329
Is this how they train you to serve your customers?

753
01:01:14,329 --> 01:01:18,130
I don't think much of their choice.

754
01:01:18,130 --> 01:01:19,849
Fill up my glass!

755
01:01:19,849 --> 01:01:23,410
That's what you're here for, isn't it?' he
said.

756
01:01:23,410 --> 01:01:30,280
'As you seem to know your way about here,
you can fill your own glass.

757
01:01:30,280 --> 01:01:35,640
I'll tell Mr Merlyn you are in the bar, and
he can serve you himself if he likes.'

758
01:01:35,640 --> 01:01:38,589
'Oh, don't worry Joss.

759
01:01:38,589 --> 01:01:41,790
What's happened to his wife?

760
01:01:41,790 --> 01:01:45,550
Has he sent her away to make room for you?

761
01:01:45,550 --> 01:01:49,820
I call that unkind to the poor woman!'

762
01:01:49,820 --> 01:01:53,552
'Do you want to speak to the landlord or not?

763
01:01:53,552 --> 01:01:57,300
I can't stand here all day.

764
01:01:57,300 --> 01:02:03,650
If you don't want to see him, and you have
finished your drink, you can put your money

765
01:02:03,650 --> 01:02:06,079
on the table and leave.'

766
01:02:06,079 --> 01:02:08,710
The man laughed.

767
01:02:08,710 --> 01:02:15,410
'Do you give orders to Joss in that way?'
he said.

768
01:02:15,410 --> 01:02:19,150
'He must be a changed man if you do.'

769
01:02:19,150 --> 01:02:24,440
'Joss Merlyn is my uncle by marriage,' she
said.

770
01:02:24,440 --> 01:02:29,320
'My name is Mary Yellan, if that means anything
to you.

771
01:02:29,320 --> 01:02:31,630
There's the door behind you.

772
01:02:31,630 --> 01:02:33,950
Good morning.'

773
01:02:33,950 --> 01:02:38,240
She left the bar, meeting the landlord himself
in the doorway.

774
01:02:38,240 --> 01:02:42,050
'Oh, it's you, Jem, is it?

775
01:02:42,050 --> 01:02:45,970
What do you want at Jamaica Inn?'

776
01:02:45,970 --> 01:02:51,710
He closed the door behind him, leaving Mary
in the passage outside.

777
01:02:51,710 --> 01:02:54,030
She went back to her bucket of water.

778
01:02:54,030 --> 01:03:00,619
So that was Jem Merlyn, her uncle's younger
brother.

779
01:03:00,619 --> 01:03:07,240
Of course - he had reminded her of her uncle
all through the conversation, though she had

780
01:03:07,240 --> 01:03:09,319
not realized it.

781
01:03:09,319 --> 01:03:15,869
He had Joss Merlyn's eyes, without the lines
round them, and he had Joss Merlyn's mouth

782
01:03:15,869 --> 01:03:21,180
- firm, though, where the landlord's was weak.

783
01:03:21,180 --> 01:03:28,920
He was what Joss Merlyn might have been 18
or 20 years ago, but smaller and neater.

784
01:03:28,920 --> 01:03:34,680
This Jem had the same cruelty in him as his
brother - she could see it in the shape of

785
01:03:34,680 --> 01:03:36,990
his mouth.

786
01:03:36,990 --> 01:03:41,800
Aunt Patience had said he was the worst of
the family.

787
01:03:41,800 --> 01:03:47,660
She was so busy that she did not hear the
stones thrown at the window of the room, and

788
01:03:47,660 --> 01:03:53,599
it was not until one cracked the glass that,
looking out of the window, she saw Jem Merlyn

789
01:03:53,599 --> 01:03:57,790
standing in the yard beside his horse.

790
01:03:57,790 --> 01:04:01,119
Mary unlocked the heavy entrance door and
went out.

791
01:04:01,119 --> 01:04:04,060
'What do you want now?'

792
01:04:04,060 --> 01:04:05,770
she asked him.

793
01:04:05,770 --> 01:04:10,100
'Forgive me if I was rude to you just now,'
he said.

794
01:04:10,100 --> 01:04:17,010
'Somehow I didn't expect to see a woman at
Jamaica Inn - well, not a young girl like

795
01:04:17,010 --> 01:04:18,010
you.

796
01:04:18,010 --> 01:04:24,500
I know I deserve black looks for behaving
as I did, but if you knew my brother as well

797
01:04:24,500 --> 01:04:28,140
as I do you'd understand how I made the mistake.

798
01:04:28,140 --> 01:04:32,780
It looks strange, having a girl at Jamaica
Inn.

799
01:04:32,780 --> 01:04:37,600
Why did you come here in the first place?'

800
01:04:37,600 --> 01:04:42,920
He looked serious now, and his likeness to
Joss had gone for the moment.

801
01:04:42,920 --> 01:04:46,720
She wished he were not a Merlyn.

802
01:04:46,720 --> 01:04:51,070
'I came here to be with my Aunt Patience,'
she said.

803
01:04:51,070 --> 01:04:55,690
'My mother died some weeks ago, and I have
no other relative.

804
01:04:55,690 --> 01:05:02,609
I'll tell you one thing, Mr Merlyn - I am
thankful my mother isn't alive to see her

805
01:05:02,609 --> 01:05:04,150
sister now.'

806
01:05:04,150 --> 01:05:07,619
'You haven't a good opinion of the landlord,
then?'

807
01:05:07,619 --> 01:05:11,810
'No, I have not,' she replied.

808
01:05:11,810 --> 01:05:17,450
'He's turned my aunt from a laughing, happy
woman into a miserable slave, and I'll never

809
01:05:17,450 --> 01:05:20,609
forgive him for that as long as I live.'

810
01:05:20,609 --> 01:05:23,960
'We Merlyns have never been good to our women.

811
01:05:23,960 --> 01:05:28,930
I can remember my father beating my mother
until she couldn't stand.

812
01:05:28,930 --> 01:05:31,000
She never left him, though.

813
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:36,380
When he was hanged at Exeter, she never spoke
a word for three months.

814
01:05:36,380 --> 01:05:39,600
Her hair went white with the shock.

815
01:05:39,600 --> 01:05:46,480
What she found to love in him, I can't say
- he never asked for her after he'd been taken,

816
01:05:46,480 --> 01:05:52,390
and he left all his money to another woman
on the other side of the river.'

817
01:05:52,390 --> 01:05:53,660
Mary was silent.

818
01:05:53,660 --> 01:05:58,369
The lack of feeling in his voice shocked her.

819
01:05:58,369 --> 01:06:04,160
He spoke without shame or sorrow, and she
supposed that he had been born, like the rest

820
01:06:04,160 --> 01:06:08,130
of his family, without any warmth or gentleness.

821
01:06:08,130 --> 01:06:14,270
'How long do you mean to stay at Jamaica Inn?'
he asked suddenly.

822
01:06:14,270 --> 01:06:18,400
'There's not much company for you here.'

823
01:06:18,400 --> 01:06:21,760
'I'm not going away unless I take my aunt
with me.

824
01:06:21,760 --> 01:06:25,430
I'd never leave her alone, after what I have
seen.'

825
01:06:25,430 --> 01:06:28,970
'What have you learnt, in your short time?

826
01:06:28,970 --> 01:06:30,640
It's quiet enough here.'

827
01:06:30,640 --> 01:06:35,160
Mary thought that he might be trying to make
her talk.

828
01:06:35,160 --> 01:06:41,190
It was possible that her uncle had suggested
that his brother should speak to her, hoping

829
01:06:41,190 --> 01:06:43,490
in this way to obtain information.

830
01:06:43,490 --> 01:06:50,570
'I helped my uncle in the bar one Saturday
night, and I didn't care for the company he

831
01:06:50,570 --> 01:06:51,570
kept.'

832
01:06:51,570 --> 01:06:55,170
'I don't suppose you did.

833
01:06:55,170 --> 01:06:59,140
The men who come to Jamaica Inn have never
been taught manners.

834
01:06:59,140 --> 01:07:01,619
They spend too much time in prison.'

835
01:07:01,619 --> 01:07:09,490
'What do you do for a living?' asked Mary
with sudden interest, for he spoke better

836
01:07:09,490 --> 01:07:10,680
than his brother.

837
01:07:10,680 --> 01:07:18,490
'I'm a horse thief,' he said cheerfully, 'but
there's not much money in it, really.

838
01:07:18,490 --> 01:07:20,819
My pockets are always empty.'

839
01:07:20,819 --> 01:07:27,790
'Aren't you afraid of being caught?' said
Mary.

840
01:07:27,790 --> 01:07:30,589
'Stealing is an awkward thing to prove.

841
01:07:30,589 --> 01:07:36,350
Suppose a horse wanders away and his owner
goes to look for him.

842
01:07:36,350 --> 01:07:40,589
These moors are full of wild horses and cattle.

843
01:07:40,589 --> 01:07:44,140
It's not going to be easy to find his horse.

844
01:07:44,140 --> 01:07:53,349
Say the horse had long hair, and one white
foot, and a diamond mark in his ear.

845
01:07:53,349 --> 01:07:58,470
Off goes the owner to Launceston market with
his eyes wide open.

846
01:07:58,470 --> 01:08:01,980
But he doesn't find his horse.

847
01:08:01,980 --> 01:08:11,130
It's there, of course, but its hair is cut
short, its four feet are all the same colour,

848
01:08:11,130 --> 01:08:15,610
and the mark in its ear is a square not a
diamond.

849
01:08:15,610 --> 01:08:18,209
The owner doesn't look at it twice.

850
01:08:18,209 --> 01:08:22,159
That's simple enough, isn't it?'

851
01:08:22,159 --> 01:08:24,929
Mary laughed, in spite of herself.

852
01:08:24,929 --> 01:08:31,869
He was so open in his dishonesty that she
could not be angry with him.

853
01:08:31,869 --> 01:08:38,159
Jem Merlyn looked at her seriously, and then
he bent towards her, first looking quickly

854
01:08:38,159 --> 01:08:40,829
over her head into the door beyond.

855
01:08:40,829 --> 01:08:48,509
'Took here,' he said, 'I'm serious now; you
can forget all the nonsense I've told you.

856
01:08:48,509 --> 01:08:54,969
Jamaica Inn is no place for a girl - nor for
any woman, if it comes to that.

857
01:08:54,969 --> 01:08:57,900
Why don't you run away?

858
01:08:57,900 --> 01:09:01,519
I could put you on the road to Bodmin.'

859
01:09:01,519 --> 01:09:04,679
Mary could almost have trusted him.

860
01:09:04,679 --> 01:09:11,130
But she could not forget that he was Joss
Merlyn's brother, and, being that, might deceive

861
01:09:11,130 --> 01:09:12,949
her.

862
01:09:12,949 --> 01:09:15,699
Time would show whose side he was on.

863
01:09:15,699 --> 01:09:19,509
'I don't need any help,' she said.

864
01:09:19,509 --> 01:09:23,269
'I can look after myself.'

865
01:09:23,269 --> 01:09:26,339
Jem threw his leg over his horse's back.

866
01:09:26,339 --> 01:09:28,909
'All right,' he said.

867
01:09:28,909 --> 01:09:30,819
'I won't worry you.

868
01:09:30,819 --> 01:09:34,849
My house is the other side of Trewartha Marsh.

869
01:09:34,849 --> 01:09:37,849
I shall be there until the spring, at least.

870
01:09:37,849 --> 01:09:40,130
Good day to you.'

871
01:09:40,130 --> 01:09:47,549
And he was off, and away down the road before
she had time to say a word in reply.

872
01:09:47,549 --> 01:09:52,999
Mary went slowly back into the house, and
the cold, dead air of Jamaica Inn closed round

873
01:09:52,999 --> 01:09:57,079
her again.

874
01:09:57,079 --> 01:10:00,119
CHAPTER SIX
Mr Bassat's Visit

875
01:10:00,119 --> 01:10:06,349
That night the wagons came again.

876
01:10:06,349 --> 01:10:11,939
This time they arrived empty, and were loaded
with the last of the goods, which had been

877
01:10:11,939 --> 01:10:15,500
left at the inn the time before.

878
01:10:15,500 --> 01:10:18,620
Mary guessed that this was their way of working.

879
01:10:18,620 --> 01:10:25,679
The inn was used as a store for a few weeks
at a time and then, when the opportunity came,

880
01:10:25,679 --> 01:10:31,489
the wagons set out once more, and the goods
were carried to the riverbank and transported

881
01:10:31,489 --> 01:10:34,099
to different places from there.

882
01:10:34,099 --> 01:10:41,179
The organization must be a big one, and there
would be agents scattered far and wide who

883
01:10:41,179 --> 01:10:43,670
kept the necessary watch on events.

884
01:10:43,670 --> 01:10:50,479
It was with a sudden sting of disappointment
that Mary wondered whether the visit of Jem

885
01:10:50,479 --> 01:10:55,199
Merlyn to Jamaica Inn that morning had been
important.

886
01:10:55,199 --> 01:11:01,179
How strange that the wagons came so soon after
him!

887
01:11:01,179 --> 01:11:08,530
He had come from Launceston, he said, and
Launceston stood on the riverbank.

888
01:11:08,530 --> 01:11:12,110
Mary was angry with him and with herself.

889
01:11:12,110 --> 01:11:21,150
In spite of everything, her last thought before
sleeping had been the possibility of his friendship.

890
01:11:21,150 --> 01:11:25,229
She would be a fool if she had hopes of it
now.

891
01:11:25,229 --> 01:11:30,610
Jem might disagree with his brother, but it
was clear that they were both in the same

892
01:11:30,610 --> 01:11:31,610
trade.

893
01:11:31,610 --> 01:11:38,840
It was a miserable, bad business in every
way, and here she was in the middle of it

894
01:11:38,840 --> 01:11:42,309
all, with Aunt Patience like a child to be
looked after.

895
01:11:42,309 --> 01:11:46,380
The next few days passed uneventfully.

896
01:11:46,380 --> 01:11:54,489
Then there came a fine cold morning when,
for a change, the sun shone in a cloudless

897
01:11:54,489 --> 01:11:55,960
sky.

898
01:11:55,960 --> 01:12:02,150
Mary, whose spirits always rose at the sight
of the sun, had turned her morning into a

899
01:12:02,150 --> 01:12:08,619
washing day; she felt well, and sang as she
worked.

900
01:12:08,619 --> 01:12:14,239
Her uncle had ridden away on the moors somewhere,
and a sense of freedom possessed her whenever

901
01:12:14,239 --> 01:12:15,590
he was away.

902
01:12:15,590 --> 01:12:22,640
An urgent knocking at the window made her
look up and she saw Aunt Patience making signs

903
01:12:22,640 --> 01:12:28,420
to her, very white in the face and clearly
frightened.

904
01:12:28,420 --> 01:12:32,039
Mary wiped her hands and ran to the back door
of the house.

905
01:12:32,039 --> 01:12:38,570
'It's Mr Bassat from North Hill,' Aunt Patience
whispered.

906
01:12:38,570 --> 01:12:41,310
'I saw him from the window.

907
01:12:41,310 --> 01:12:46,590
He's come on horseback, and another gentleman
with him.

908
01:12:46,590 --> 01:12:53,459
Oh, my dear, my dear, what are we going to
do?'

909
01:12:53,459 --> 01:12:55,749
Mary thought quickly.

910
01:12:55,749 --> 01:12:59,110
She was in a very difficult position.

911
01:12:59,110 --> 01:13:04,739
If this Mr Bassat represented the law, it
was her one chance of telling someone about

912
01:13:04,739 --> 01:13:06,730
her uncle.

913
01:13:06,730 --> 01:13:13,719
She could tell him about the wagons and about
everything that she had seen since her arrival.

914
01:13:13,719 --> 01:13:17,329
She looked down at the trembling woman at
her side.

915
01:13:17,329 --> 01:13:22,159
By now, there was a continuous hammering on
the door.

916
01:13:22,159 --> 01:13:29,499
'Mary, if Mr Bassat asks you what you know,
you won't answer him, will you?

917
01:13:29,499 --> 01:13:31,650
I can trust you, can't I?

918
01:13:31,650 --> 01:13:34,190
You'll not tell him of the wagons?

919
01:13:34,190 --> 01:13:40,599
If any danger came to Joss, I'd kill myself,
Mary.

920
01:13:40,599 --> 01:13:44,530
There was no argument after that.

921
01:13:44,530 --> 01:13:47,050
Mary opened the heavy entrance door.

922
01:13:47,050 --> 01:13:50,559
There were two men outside.

923
01:13:50,559 --> 01:13:56,229
One had climbed down from his horse; it was
he who had rained the blows on the door.

924
01:13:56,229 --> 01:13:58,639
The other was still on horseback.

925
01:13:58,639 --> 01:14:05,050
His face was brown and heavily lined; Mary
judged him to be about fifty years of age.

926
01:14:05,050 --> 01:14:09,640
'You don't hurry here, do you?' he called.

927
01:14:09,640 --> 01:14:13,650
'There doesn't seem to be much of a welcome
for travellers.

928
01:14:13,650 --> 01:14:15,130
Is the landlord at home?'

929
01:14:15,130 --> 01:14:20,842
'If you please, Mr Bassat, my husband went
out as soon as he had eaten his breakfast,

930
01:14:20,842 --> 01:14:25,039
and whether he will be back before night I
cannot say.'

931
01:14:25,039 --> 01:14:26,530
'That's a pity.

932
01:14:26,530 --> 01:14:32,099
I wanted a word or two with Mr Joss Merlyn.'

933
01:14:32,099 --> 01:14:34,889
Mr Bassat climbed heavily to the ground.

934
01:14:34,889 --> 01:14:41,519
'While I'm here I may as well look round,
and I'll tell you here and now it's useless

935
01:14:41,519 --> 01:14:43,249
to refuse me.

936
01:14:43,249 --> 01:14:48,499
I am a magistrate, and I have the necessary
documents.'

937
01:14:48,499 --> 01:14:51,650
He pushed his way past the two women.

938
01:14:51,650 --> 01:14:56,590
Aunt Patience made a movement as though to
prevent him, but Mary said quietly.

939
01:14:56,590 --> 01:14:58,090
Let him go.

940
01:14:58,090 --> 01:15:04,510
If we try to stop him now we shall only anger
him the more.'

941
01:15:04,510 --> 01:15:07,909
The rooms were thoroughly explored.

942
01:15:07,909 --> 01:15:15,090
The magistrate looked into the dusty corners,
lifted old bags and boxes, examined the stores

943
01:15:15,090 --> 01:15:20,130
of food, all the time crying out in anger
and disgust.

944
01:15:20,130 --> 01:15:22,469
'Gall this an inn, do you?

945
01:15:22,469 --> 01:15:26,280
You haven't even got a bed fit for a cat to
sleep on.

946
01:15:26,280 --> 01:15:27,920
The place is horrible.

947
01:15:27,920 --> 01:15:30,439
What does it mean, eh?

948
01:15:30,439 --> 01:15:33,130
Have you lost your tongue, Mrs Merlyn?'

949
01:15:33,130 --> 01:15:41,440
The poor woman could not reply; she kept shaking
her head and working her mouth, and Mary knew

950
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:46,540
that she was wondering what would happen when
they came to the locked room in the passage.

951
01:15:46,540 --> 01:15:49,360
'What about you, young woman?

952
01:15:49,360 --> 01:15:51,840
Have you anything to say?'

953
01:15:51,840 --> 01:15:55,449
'I'm here to look after my aunt.

954
01:15:55,449 --> 01:15:58,400
She's not very strong; you can see that for
yourself.

955
01:15:58,400 --> 01:15:59,909
She's easily frightened.'

956
01:15:59,909 --> 01:16:04,760
'I don't blame her, living in a place like
this.

957
01:16:04,760 --> 01:16:09,449
Well, kindly show me the room that has barred
windows.

958
01:16:09,449 --> 01:16:13,780
I noticed it from the yard, and I'd like to
see inside.'

959
01:16:13,780 --> 01:16:20,559
'I'm very sorry, sir,' Mary replied, 'but
if you mean the old store room at the end

960
01:16:20,559 --> 01:16:24,320
of the passage, I'm afraid the door is locked.

961
01:16:24,320 --> 01:16:29,130
My uncle always keeps the key, and where he
puts it I don't know.'

962
01:16:29,130 --> 01:16:30,949
Well, that's easily settled.

963
01:16:30,949 --> 01:16:35,189
We'll have the door down in no time.'

964
01:16:35,189 --> 01:16:37,920
He went out into the yard to call his servant.

965
01:16:37,920 --> 01:16:44,150
In a few minutes, he returned with his man,
Richards, who was carrying an iron bar, which

966
01:16:44,150 --> 01:16:47,260
he had found in the stable.

967
01:16:47,260 --> 01:16:51,020
For a few minutes, the door bore every blow.

968
01:16:51,020 --> 01:16:56,969
Then there was a splitting of wood and a crash,
and the door gave way.

969
01:16:56,969 --> 01:17:01,670
It was dark of course; the blocked windows
kept the light out.

970
01:17:01,670 --> 01:17:08,330
The servant produced a light, and the magistrate
stepped into the room.

971
01:17:08,330 --> 01:17:16,000
For a moment there was silence as the magistrate
turned, letting the light shine in every corner,

972
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:23,710
and then, making sounds of annoyance and disappointment,
he faced the little group behind him.

973
01:17:23,710 --> 01:17:28,249
'Nothing,' he said; 'nothing at all.

974
01:17:28,249 --> 01:17:30,610
The landlord has made a fool of me again.'

975
01:17:30,610 --> 01:17:37,059
Except for a pile of empty bags in one corner,
there was nothing in the room.

976
01:17:37,059 --> 01:17:40,499
It was thick with dust.

977
01:17:40,499 --> 01:17:47,239
There was no furniture of any sort, the fireplace
had been blocked up with stones and the floor

978
01:17:47,239 --> 01:17:51,050
itself was of stone like the passage outside.

979
01:17:51,050 --> 01:17:56,980
On top of the bags lay a length of twisted
rope.

980
01:17:56,980 --> 01:18:00,790
Then the magistrate turned once more into
the passage.

981
01:18:00,790 --> 01:18:04,920
'Well, Mr Joss Merlyn has won this time.

982
01:18:04,920 --> 01:18:07,920
I'll admit myself beaten.

983
01:18:07,920 --> 01:18:12,989
Now listen to me,' he said, pointing his whip
at Mary.

984
01:18:12,989 --> 01:18:18,820
'This aunt of yours may have lost her tongue,
but you can understand plain English, I hope.

985
01:18:18,820 --> 01:18:24,170
Do you mean to tell me you know nothing of
your uncle's business?

986
01:18:24,170 --> 01:18:30,749
Does nobody ever call here, by day or night?'

987
01:18:30,749 --> 01:18:33,209
Mary looked him straight in the eye.

988
01:18:33,209 --> 01:18:37,500
'I've never seen anyone,' she said.

989
01:18:37,500 --> 01:18:42,619
'Have you ever looked into that locked room
before today?'

990
01:18:42,619 --> 01:18:43,630
'No.'

991
01:18:43,630 --> 01:18:49,160
'Have you any idea why he should keep it locked
up?'

992
01:18:49,160 --> 01:18:52,130
'No, none at all.'

993
01:18:52,130 --> 01:18:57,070
'Have you ever heard wheels in the yard by
night?'

994
01:18:57,070 --> 01:18:59,199
'I'm a very heavy sleeper.

995
01:18:59,199 --> 01:19:00,469
Nothing ever wakes me?'

996
01:19:00,469 --> 01:19:04,809
'Where does your uncle go when he's away from
home?'

997
01:19:04,809 --> 01:19:06,900
'I don't know'

998
01:19:06,900 --> 01:19:13,829
'Don't you think it's very strange, to keep
an inn on the main road and then to close

999
01:19:13,829 --> 01:19:16,400
your door to every traveller?'

1000
01:19:16,400 --> 01:19:19,260
'My uncle is a very strange man.'

1001
01:19:19,260 --> 01:19:22,550
'That is true.

1002
01:19:22,550 --> 01:19:28,400
In fact, he's so strange that half the people
in the countryside won't sleep quietly in

1003
01:19:28,400 --> 01:19:34,929
their beds until he's been hanged, like his
father before him.

1004
01:19:34,929 --> 01:19:38,159
You can tell him that from me.'

1005
01:19:38,159 --> 01:19:40,260
He climbed onto his horse.

1006
01:19:40,260 --> 01:19:43,389
'One other thing,' he called.

1007
01:19:43,389 --> 01:19:51,219
'Have you seen anything of your uncle's younger
brother, Jem Merlyn, of Trewartha?'

1008
01:19:51,219 --> 01:19:53,939
'No,' said Mary steadily.

1009
01:19:53,939 --> 01:19:56,300
'He never comes here.'

1010
01:19:56,300 --> 01:19:58,510
'Oh, doesn't he?

1011
01:19:58,510 --> 01:20:01,949
Well, that's all I want from you this morning.

1012
01:20:01,949 --> 01:20:04,920
'Good day to you both?'

1013
01:20:04,920 --> 01:20:14,310
And away the two men went from the yard, and
so on to the road.

1014
01:20:14,310 --> 01:20:18,289
Joss Merlyn returned just before midday.

1015
01:20:18,289 --> 01:20:22,079
Mary told him calmly what had happened during
the morning.

1016
01:20:22,079 --> 01:20:29,219
He swore and shouted, but he was frightened,
she could see that, and his confidence was

1017
01:20:29,219 --> 01:20:30,219
shaken.

1018
01:20:30,219 --> 01:20:34,079
'Get me something to eat,' he said.

1019
01:20:34,079 --> 01:20:38,610
'I must go out again, and there's no time
to waste.

1020
01:20:38,610 --> 01:20:45,419
You've done well today, Mary, and I'll not
forget it.'

1021
01:20:45,419 --> 01:20:46,590
She looked him in the eyes.

1022
01:20:46,590 --> 01:20:50,659
'You don't think I did it for you, do you?'

1023
01:20:50,659 --> 01:20:55,969
'I don't care why you did it; the result's
the same?

1024
01:20:55,969 --> 01:21:04,489
As soon as he had finished his meal, the landlord
rose to his feet and left the kitchen.

1025
01:21:04,489 --> 01:21:07,099
Mary watched him cross the moor.

1026
01:21:07,099 --> 01:21:12,880
She thought for a moment, doubting the wisdom
of the sudden plan in her head, and then she

1027
01:21:12,880 --> 01:21:15,959
ran down the field after her uncle.

1028
01:21:15,959 --> 01:21:22,170
When she reached the bottom, she bent down
beside the stonewall until his figure crossed

1029
01:21:22,170 --> 01:21:29,329
the skyline and disappeared, and then she
jumped up again and followed him, picking

1030
01:21:29,329 --> 01:21:31,920
her way across the rough grass and stones.

1031
01:21:31,920 --> 01:21:40,400
It was crazy, no doubt, but her idea was to
keep Joss Merlyn in view, and in this way

1032
01:21:40,400 --> 01:21:43,280
to learn something of his secret plan.

1033
01:21:43,280 --> 01:21:49,459
After a few miles, she realized how difficult
it was.

1034
01:21:49,459 --> 01:21:55,289
She had to keep a good distance between them
in order to remain unseen, and the landlord

1035
01:21:55,289 --> 01:22:00,570
walked at such a speed that before long she
saw that she would be left behind.

1036
01:22:00,570 --> 01:22:06,900
The ground was now soft beneath her feet;
the whole of the low- lying plain ahead of

1037
01:22:06,900 --> 01:22:09,449
her was wet with winter rains.

1038
01:22:09,449 --> 01:22:15,070
Her uncle had crossed the worst of the low
ground with the quickness given by many years

1039
01:22:15,070 --> 01:22:17,090
of practice.

1040
01:22:17,090 --> 01:22:21,639
Then he was hidden by a big rock and she saw
him no more.

1041
01:22:21,639 --> 01:22:28,389
It was impossible to discover the path, which
he had taken across the marsh, but Mary followed

1042
01:22:28,389 --> 01:22:30,810
as best she could.

1043
01:22:30,810 --> 01:22:39,310
She was a fool to attempt it, she knew, but
a sort of determined stupidity made her continue.

1044
01:22:39,310 --> 01:22:44,469
When she reached the top of the hill, the
evening clouds were thick and the world was

1045
01:22:44,469 --> 01:22:46,260
grey.

1046
01:22:46,260 --> 01:22:48,679
The horizon was hidden.

1047
01:22:48,679 --> 01:22:52,300
Mary would never find her uncle now.

1048
01:22:52,300 --> 01:22:58,199
She knew herself to be a fool for having gone
so far on a December afternoon; experience

1049
01:22:58,199 --> 01:23:05,449
had proved to her that when darkness came
on Bodmin moor it was sudden and without warning.

1050
01:23:05,449 --> 01:23:08,829
The low cloud over the marshes was dangerous
too.

1051
01:23:08,829 --> 01:23:14,099
But there was less danger from the marshes
if she kept to the high ground, so, pulling

1052
01:23:14,099 --> 01:23:20,519
up her skirt, she walked steadily forward,
feeling the ground with some care when in

1053
01:23:20,519 --> 01:23:25,860
doubt, and avoiding those places where the
grass felt soft and gave way under her feet.

1054
01:23:25,860 --> 01:23:32,239
Her legs were heavy, and her feet felt as
if they hardly belonged to her, and her eyes

1055
01:23:32,239 --> 01:23:34,920
felt sunken away back in her head.

1056
01:23:34,920 --> 01:23:42,639
She walked on, her head low and her hands
at her side, thinking that the tall grey chimneys

1057
01:23:42,639 --> 01:23:48,860
of Jamaica Inn would be, for the first time,
a welcome sight.

1058
01:23:48,860 --> 01:23:54,749
The path was wider now, and was crossed by
another running from left to right, and Mary

1059
01:23:54,749 --> 01:24:00,150
stood uncertainly for a few moments, wondering
which to take.

1060
01:24:00,150 --> 01:24:07,409
It was then that she heard the sound of a
horse coming out of the darkness to the left.

1061
01:24:07,409 --> 01:24:12,539
Mary waited in the middle of the track, and
after some time the horse appeared out of

1062
01:24:12,539 --> 01:24:15,510
the low cloud in front of her.

1063
01:24:15,510 --> 01:24:20,739
The horseman turned sharply to the side as
he saw Mary, and stopped.

1064
01:24:20,739 --> 01:24:24,510
'Hello,' he cried, 'who's there?

1065
01:24:24,510 --> 01:24:27,460
Is anyone in trouble?'

1066
01:24:27,460 --> 01:24:31,949
Then, looking down closely, he said in surprise,
'A woman!

1067
01:24:31,949 --> 01:24:37,489
What in the world are you doing out here?'

1068
01:24:37,489 --> 01:24:39,519
'Can you help me to find the road?

1069
01:24:39,519 --> 01:24:43,119
I'm miles from home and hopelessly lost.'

1070
01:24:43,119 --> 01:24:47,090
'Steady there!' he said to his horse.

1071
01:24:47,090 --> 01:24:48,611
'Stand still, will you?

1072
01:24:48,611 --> 01:24:52,829
Where have you come from?

1073
01:24:52,829 --> 01:24:56,300
Of course I will help you if I can.'

1074
01:24:56,300 --> 01:24:58,989
His voice was low and gentle.

1075
01:24:58,989 --> 01:25:05,789
'I live at Jamaica Inn,' she said, and as
soon as the words were out of her mouth, she

1076
01:25:05,789 --> 01:25:08,010
wished she had not said them.

1077
01:25:08,010 --> 01:25:15,199
For a moment, the man was silent, but when
he spoke again his voice had not changed,

1078
01:25:15,199 --> 01:25:17,960
but was quiet and gentle as before.

1079
01:25:17,960 --> 01:25:21,179
'Jamaica Inn?' he said.

1080
01:25:21,179 --> 01:25:24,750
'You've come a long way in the wrong direction,
I'm afraid.

1081
01:25:24,750 --> 01:25:26,860
You're tired out.

1082
01:25:26,860 --> 01:25:33,030
You're not fit to walk another step; and what's
more, I'm not going to let you.

1083
01:25:33,030 --> 01:25:36,919
We're not far from the village, and you shall
ride there.

1084
01:25:36,919 --> 01:25:42,999
You shall come home with me, and dry your
clothes and rest a little and have some supper

1085
01:25:42,999 --> 01:25:47,760
before I take you back myself to Jamaica Inn.'

1086
01:25:47,760 --> 01:25:54,579
He spoke with such kindness, but with such
firmness, that Mary trusted him.

1087
01:25:54,579 --> 01:25:58,479
Then she saw his eyes for the first time beneath
the edge of his hat.

1088
01:25:58,479 --> 01:26:06,619
They were strange eyes, like glass, and so
pale in colour that they seemed near to white.

1089
01:26:06,619 --> 01:26:13,420
His hair was white, too, under his black hat,
and Mary looked at him in some surprise, because

1090
01:26:13,420 --> 01:26:18,300
his face was unlined and his voice was not
that of an old man.

1091
01:26:18,300 --> 01:26:25,820
Then, with sudden embarrassment, she understood,
and she turned away her eyes.

1092
01:26:25,820 --> 01:26:28,400
He was an albino.

1093
01:26:28,400 --> 01:26:29,619
He took off his hat.

1094
01:26:29,619 --> 01:26:35,030
'Perhaps I had better introduce myself,' he
said with a smile.

1095
01:26:35,030 --> 01:26:40,630
'Even if the meeting is unusual, it is the
right thing to do I believe.

1096
01:26:40,630 --> 01:26:50,000
My name is Francis Davey, and I am the Vicar
of Altarnun.'

1097
01:26:50,000 --> 01:26:55,650
CHAPTER SEVEN
The Vicar of Altarnun

1098
01:26:55,650 --> 01:27:00,050
There was something strangely peaceful about
his house.

1099
01:27:00,050 --> 01:27:02,969
Mary stretched out her hands towards the fire.

1100
01:27:02,969 --> 01:27:08,699
The silence pleased her; it took away her
fear.

1101
01:27:08,699 --> 01:27:13,730
She watched Francis Davey as he laid the table
for supper.

1102
01:27:13,730 --> 01:27:16,469
'Hannah lives in the village,' he said.

1103
01:27:16,469 --> 01:27:19,320
'She leaves every afternoon at four.

1104
01:27:19,320 --> 01:27:21,689
I prefer to be by myself.

1105
01:27:21,689 --> 01:27:28,630
I like getting my own supper, and then I can
choose my own time.'

1106
01:27:28,630 --> 01:27:34,360
She had not yet become used to his white hair
and his eyes; his black clothes made them

1107
01:27:34,360 --> 01:27:37,039
even more noticeable.

1108
01:27:37,039 --> 01:27:41,110
She was tired, but she swallowed her supper.

1109
01:27:41,110 --> 01:27:44,679
He poured her out a steaming cup of tea.

1110
01:27:44,679 --> 01:27:50,550
Now and again, she took a quick look at him,
but he seemed to sense it immediately, for

1111
01:27:50,550 --> 01:27:55,889
he would turn, his eyes on her with their
cold white look - like that of a blind man

1112
01:27:55,889 --> 01:27:57,909
- and she would look away again.

1113
01:27:57,909 --> 01:28:05,409
The warmth of the room and the hot tea made
her sleepy, and his gentle voice came from

1114
01:28:05,409 --> 01:28:06,570
far away.

1115
01:28:06,570 --> 01:28:10,920
'Why were you wandering on the moor tonight?'

1116
01:28:10,920 --> 01:28:17,719
Hardly knowing how it happened, she heard
her voice reply to his.

1117
01:28:17,719 --> 01:28:20,830
'I'm in terrible trouble,' she said.

1118
01:28:20,830 --> 01:28:25,880
'Sometimes I think I shall become like my
aunt, and go out of my mind.

1119
01:28:25,880 --> 01:28:32,159
I've not been at Jamaica Inn much more than
a month, but it seems like twenty years.

1120
01:28:32,159 --> 01:28:37,390
It's my aunt that worries me; if only I could
take her away!

1121
01:28:37,390 --> 01:28:42,929
But she won't leave Uncle Joss, in spite of
his treatment of her.

1122
01:28:42,929 --> 01:28:48,869
Every night when I go to bed I wonder if I
shall wake up and hear the wagons.

1123
01:28:48,869 --> 01:28:55,110
The first time they came, there were six or
seven of them, and they brought great packages

1124
01:28:55,110 --> 01:29:00,999
and boxes that the men stored in the locked
room at the end of the passage.

1125
01:29:00,999 --> 01:29:08,400
A man was killed that night; I saw the rope
hanging from a beam downstairs.'

1126
01:29:08,400 --> 01:29:12,360
She stopped, the warm colour flooding her
face.

1127
01:29:12,360 --> 01:29:15,130
'I've never told anyone before.

1128
01:29:15,130 --> 01:29:17,400
It had to come out.

1129
01:29:17,400 --> 01:29:20,469
I couldn't keep it to myself any longer.

1130
01:29:20,469 --> 01:29:24,050
I've done something terrible.'

1131
01:29:24,050 --> 01:29:30,669
For a moment or two, he did not answer; then
he spoke gently and slowly.

1132
01:29:30,669 --> 01:29:33,130
'Don't be afraid.

1133
01:29:33,130 --> 01:29:39,320
Your secret is safe; no one shall know of
this but me.

1134
01:29:39,320 --> 01:29:45,989
When you have rested, I'll take you back,
and I'll make your excuses to the landlord

1135
01:29:45,989 --> 01:29:47,100
if you wish.'

1136
01:29:47,100 --> 01:29:52,010
'Oh, you mustn't do that,' said Mary quickly.

1137
01:29:52,010 --> 01:29:59,235
'If he suspects half of what I've done tonight
he would kill me and you too.

1138
01:29:59,235 --> 01:30:01,269
You don't understand.

1139
01:30:01,269 --> 01:30:05,469
He's a violent man, and nothing would stop
him.'

1140
01:30:05,469 --> 01:30:12,199
'Isn't your imagination running away with
you a little?' said the vicar.

1141
01:30:12,199 --> 01:30:18,849
'This is the nineteenth century, you know,
and men don't murder one another without reason.

1142
01:30:18,849 --> 01:30:27,360
Having gone so far, don't you think you had
better let me hear the rest of your story?

1143
01:30:27,360 --> 01:30:34,159
'What is your name, and why are you living
at Jamaica Inn?'

1144
01:30:34,159 --> 01:30:40,959
Mary looked up at the pale eyes in the colourless
face, at his white hair, and she thought again

1145
01:30:40,959 --> 01:30:48,559
how strange he was, this man who might be
twenty-one, who might be sixty, and who with

1146
01:30:48,559 --> 01:30:55,159
his soft voice could persuade her to admit
every secret she possessed if he wanted.

1147
01:30:55,159 --> 01:31:01,520
She could trust him; that, at least, was certain.

1148
01:31:01,520 --> 01:31:07,320
The first part of her story was told in short
and broken sentences, beginning with that

1149
01:31:07,320 --> 01:31:13,110
first Saturday night at the bar, and then
working backwards to her arrival at the inn.

1150
01:31:13,110 --> 01:31:21,539
Her report did not sound true, even to her
who knew the truth of it, and she was so tired

1151
01:31:21,539 --> 01:31:26,939
that she often could not find the words, but
paused for thought and then went back in her

1152
01:31:26,939 --> 01:31:29,019
story and repeated herself.

1153
01:31:29,019 --> 01:31:36,239
He heard her to the end with patience, but
all the time she felt his eyes watching her,

1154
01:31:36,239 --> 01:31:42,300
and he had a habit of swallowing from time
to time, which she came to recognize, and

1155
01:31:42,300 --> 01:31:44,830
wait for.

1156
01:31:44,830 --> 01:31:50,689
When she had finished, the vicar got up from
his chair and began to walk around the room.

1157
01:31:50,689 --> 01:31:59,880
'I believe you, of course,' he said, after
a moment or so, 'but your story wouldn't be

1158
01:31:59,880 --> 01:32:02,719
believed in a court of law.

1159
01:32:02,719 --> 01:32:10,679
And another thing - it's wrong, we all know
that, but smuggling goes on all over the country,

1160
01:32:10,679 --> 01:32:14,309
and half the magistrates make a profit out
of it.

1161
01:32:14,309 --> 01:32:16,409
That shocks you, doesn't it?

1162
01:32:16,409 --> 01:32:20,469
But you can be sure that it's the truth.

1163
01:32:20,469 --> 01:32:27,139
I have met Mr Bassat once or twice, and I
believe him to be an honest sort of man, but

1164
01:32:27,139 --> 01:32:30,829
between ourselves, a bit of a fool.

1165
01:32:30,829 --> 01:32:37,539
I can tell you one thing, though; his visit
will have frightened your uncle.

1166
01:32:37,539 --> 01:32:44,969
There won't be any more wagons to Jamaica
Inn for some time; I think you can be certain

1167
01:32:44,969 --> 01:32:46,449
of that.

1168
01:32:46,449 --> 01:32:49,199
If I were you, I should just wait.

1169
01:32:49,199 --> 01:32:57,110
Keep a close watch on your uncle, and when
the wagons do come again you can tell me immediately.

1170
01:32:57,110 --> 01:33:00,949
We can then decide together what should be
done.'

1171
01:33:00,949 --> 01:33:05,429
'What about the stranger who disappeared?

1172
01:33:05,429 --> 01:33:07,320
He was murdered, I'm certain of that.

1173
01:33:07,320 --> 01:33:12,229
Do you mean to say that nothing can ever be
done about it?'

1174
01:33:12,229 --> 01:33:21,619
'I'm afraid not, unless his body is found,
which is extremely unlikely,' said the vicar.

1175
01:33:21,619 --> 01:33:26,949
'In fact it's quite possible that he was never
killed at all.

1176
01:33:26,949 --> 01:33:33,090
Forgive me, but I think you allowed your imagination
to run away with you over that.

1177
01:33:33,090 --> 01:33:37,400
All you saw was a piece of rope remember.

1178
01:33:37,400 --> 01:33:44,409
If you had actually seen the man dead, or
even wounded, well, that would be a different

1179
01:33:44,409 --> 01:33:45,409
matter.'

1180
01:33:45,409 --> 01:33:48,739
'I heard my uncle threaten him.

1181
01:33:48,739 --> 01:33:50,929
Isn't that enough?'

1182
01:33:50,929 --> 01:33:58,289
'My dear child, people threaten one another
every day of the year, but they don't hang

1183
01:33:58,289 --> 01:33:59,289
for it.

1184
01:33:59,289 --> 01:34:00,289
Now listen to me.

1185
01:34:00,289 --> 01:34:05,689
I am your friend, and you can trust me.

1186
01:34:05,689 --> 01:34:12,039
If you ever become worried or frightened,
I want you to come and tell me about it.

1187
01:34:12,039 --> 01:34:15,570
Altarnun is only a few miles by the road.

1188
01:34:15,570 --> 01:34:19,170
That's agreed between us, isn't it?'

1189
01:34:19,170 --> 01:34:21,559
'Thank you very much.'

1190
01:34:21,559 --> 01:34:25,999
'And now I'm going to drive you back to Jamaica
Inn.'

1191
01:34:25,999 --> 01:34:33,230
The thought of returning was hateful to Mary,
but it had to be faced.

1192
01:34:33,230 --> 01:34:38,590
The night was fine; the dark clouds of the
early evening had passed away, and the sky

1193
01:34:38,590 --> 01:34:40,169
was bright with stars.

1194
01:34:40,169 --> 01:34:43,929
It was a strange, exciting drive.

1195
01:34:43,929 --> 01:34:47,059
The wind blew in Mary's face.

1196
01:34:47,059 --> 01:34:54,579
The horse thundered along the hard white road,
and the vicar made no attempt to control it.

1197
01:34:54,579 --> 01:34:56,679
Mary saw that he was smiling.

1198
01:34:56,679 --> 01:35:05,770
'Go on,' he urged the animal, 'go on; you
can go faster than this,' and his voice was

1199
01:35:05,770 --> 01:35:10,199
low and excited, as if he were talking to
himself.

1200
01:35:10,199 --> 01:35:13,820
The effect was unnatural.

1201
01:35:13,820 --> 01:35:17,810
Mary felt as if he were in another world and
had forgotten her existence.

1202
01:35:17,810 --> 01:35:25,760
He looked like a bird, bending forward in
his seat; with his clothes blown by the wind,

1203
01:35:25,760 --> 01:35:28,420
his arms were like wings.

1204
01:35:28,420 --> 01:35:31,229
He might be any age.

1205
01:35:31,229 --> 01:35:34,560
Then he smiled down at her, and was human
again.

1206
01:35:34,560 --> 01:35:38,320
'I love these moors,' he said.

1207
01:35:38,320 --> 01:35:44,550
'If you knew them as well as I do, and had
seen them in every type of weather, winter

1208
01:35:44,550 --> 01:35:48,189
and summer, you would love them too.

1209
01:35:48,189 --> 01:35:52,340
They go back a long way in time.

1210
01:35:52,340 --> 01:35:55,550
Sometimes I think that they have lived on
from another age.

1211
01:35:55,550 --> 01:36:03,130
The moors were the first things to be made;
afterwards came the forests and the valleys

1212
01:36:03,130 --> 01:36:06,869
and the sea.'

1213
01:36:06,869 --> 01:36:11,780
Already Mary could see the tall chimneys of
Jamaica Inn against the sky.

1214
01:36:11,780 --> 01:36:15,469
The drive was ended, and the excitement left
her.

1215
01:36:15,469 --> 01:36:18,610
The old fear and hatred of her uncle returned.

1216
01:36:18,610 --> 01:36:24,719
The vicar stopped his horse just before the
yard, beside a grassy bank.

1217
01:36:24,719 --> 01:36:29,829
'There's no sign of anyone,' he said quietly.

1218
01:36:29,829 --> 01:36:33,869
'It's like a house of the dead.

1219
01:36:33,869 --> 01:36:37,550
I'm going to look in at the window.'

1220
01:36:37,550 --> 01:36:43,300
She watched him go to the side of the house
and he stood there for a few minutes looking.

1221
01:36:43,300 --> 01:36:45,679
Then he made a sign to her to follow.

1222
01:36:45,679 --> 01:36:52,639
'There'll be no argument tonight with the
landlord of Jamaica Inn.'

1223
01:36:52,639 --> 01:36:57,889
Mary followed the direction of his eyes and
came forward to the window.

1224
01:36:57,889 --> 01:37:03,840
Joss Merlyn sat at the table unconscious,
his great legs stretched out on either side

1225
01:37:03,840 --> 01:37:08,199
of him, his hat on the back of his head.

1226
01:37:08,199 --> 01:37:14,280
He looked straight in front of him at the
light, his eyes fixed like those of a dead

1227
01:37:14,280 --> 01:37:15,280
man.

1228
01:37:15,280 --> 01:37:21,820
A bottle lay with its neck broken on the table,
and beside it an empty glass.

1229
01:37:21,820 --> 01:37:25,320
The fire had burnt away to nothing.

1230
01:37:25,320 --> 01:37:27,889
Francis Davey pointed to the door.

1231
01:37:27,889 --> 01:37:33,039
'You can walk inside and go upstairs to bed.

1232
01:37:33,039 --> 01:37:35,429
Your uncle will not even see you.

1233
01:37:35,429 --> 01:37:38,670
Good night to you, Mary Yellan.

1234
01:37:38,670 --> 01:37:47,729
If you're ever in trouble and need me, I shall
be waiting for you at Altarnun.'

1235
01:37:47,729 --> 01:37:52,829
Then he turned the corner of the house and
was gone.

1236
01:37:52,829 --> 01:37:57,650
CHAPTER EIGHT
Joss's Dreams

1237
01:37:57,650 --> 01:38:02,769
Joss Merlyn was drunk for five days.

1238
01:38:02,769 --> 01:38:08,149
He was unconscious most of the time, and lay
stretched out on a bed in the kitchen that

1239
01:38:08,149 --> 01:38:11,420
Mary and her aunt had made up.

1240
01:38:11,420 --> 01:38:16,119
He slept with his mouth wide open, and the
sound of his breathing could be heard from

1241
01:38:16,119 --> 01:38:18,000
the bedrooms above.

1242
01:38:18,000 --> 01:38:24,590
At about five in the evening, he would wake
for about half an hour, shouting for drink

1243
01:38:24,590 --> 01:38:27,139
and crying like a child.

1244
01:38:27,139 --> 01:38:34,039
His wife went to him immediately, talking
to him gently, holding a glass to his lips;

1245
01:38:34,039 --> 01:38:41,369
and he looked wildly around, talking to himself
and trembling like a frightened dog.

1246
01:38:41,369 --> 01:38:46,709
Aunt Patience became another woman, showing
a calm, which Mary would not have believed

1247
01:38:46,709 --> 01:38:48,769
her to possess.

1248
01:38:48,769 --> 01:38:54,340
It seemed that every two months or so Joss
Merlyn would have these periods of uncontrolled

1249
01:38:54,340 --> 01:38:55,340
drinking.

1250
01:38:55,340 --> 01:39:02,039
They were becoming more frequent, and Aunt
Patience was never quite certain when they

1251
01:39:02,039 --> 01:39:04,010
would happen.

1252
01:39:04,010 --> 01:39:09,229
On the fifth morning, the wind dropped and
the sun shone, and in spite of the adventure

1253
01:39:09,229 --> 01:39:14,320
of a few days before, Mary decided to try
the moors again.

1254
01:39:14,320 --> 01:39:19,920
This time she made for the East Moor, walking
towards Kilmar.

1255
01:39:19,920 --> 01:39:27,300
With many hours of daylight to come, there
was no danger of being lost.

1256
01:39:27,300 --> 01:39:32,709
Mary had walked for an hour or more before
she stopped, her progress barred by a stream

1257
01:39:32,709 --> 01:39:35,090
that divided and ran in different directions.

1258
01:39:35,090 --> 01:39:40,729
It lay in a valley in the hills, and was surrounded
by marshes.

1259
01:39:40,729 --> 01:39:48,349
The country was not unknown to her; looking
out beyond the green face of the tor ahead,

1260
01:39:48,349 --> 01:39:53,679
she saw the great hand of Kilmar pointing
its fingers to the sky.

1261
01:39:53,679 --> 01:39:59,130
She was looking at Trewartha Moor once again,
where she had wandered that first Saturday,

1262
01:39:59,130 --> 01:40:07,590
but this time her face was turned to the southeast,
and the hills looked different in the sunshine.

1263
01:40:07,590 --> 01:40:11,409
The stream ran cheerfully over the stones.

1264
01:40:11,409 --> 01:40:17,729
As Mary crossed it by a rough bridge, a group
of horses came down the hill beyond and pushed

1265
01:40:17,729 --> 01:40:20,869
into the stream to drink.

1266
01:40:20,869 --> 01:40:26,571
Out of the corner of her eye, she saw a man
following them down the path, carrying a bucket

1267
01:40:26,571 --> 01:40:29,139
in each hand.

1268
01:40:29,139 --> 01:40:35,059
She was about to continue her walk when he
waved a bucket in the air and shouted to her.

1269
01:40:35,059 --> 01:40:38,459
It was Jem Merlyn.

1270
01:40:38,459 --> 01:40:44,599
There was no time to escape, so she stood
where she was until he came to her, looking

1271
01:40:44,599 --> 01:40:50,199
just as his brother must have looked twenty
years ago.

1272
01:40:50,199 --> 01:40:55,050
'So you've found your way to me, have you?'
he said.

1273
01:40:55,050 --> 01:41:00,429
'I didn't expect you so soon, or I'd have
made some bread in your honour.

1274
01:41:00,429 --> 01:41:03,199
I haven't washed for three days and I've been
living on potatoes.

1275
01:41:03,199 --> 01:41:08,570
Here, take hold of this bucket.'

1276
01:41:08,570 --> 01:41:14,170
He pushed one of the buckets into her hand
and ran down to the water after the horses.

1277
01:41:14,170 --> 01:41:18,199
'Come out of it!' he shouted.

1278
01:41:18,199 --> 01:41:20,909
'Dirtying my drinking water!

1279
01:41:20,909 --> 01:41:25,059
Go on, you big black devil.'

1280
01:41:25,059 --> 01:41:30,119
He hit the largest of the horses with the
end of the bucket, and they all ran back up

1281
01:41:30,119 --> 01:41:32,750
the hill, kicking their feet in the air.

1282
01:41:32,750 --> 01:41:40,519
What would you have done if you hadn't found
me at home?' he said, wiping his face on his

1283
01:41:40,519 --> 01:41:42,179
arm.

1284
01:41:42,179 --> 01:41:45,110
Mary could not help smiling.

1285
01:41:45,110 --> 01:41:50,690
'I didn't even know you lived here, and I
certainly never walked this way with the intention

1286
01:41:50,690 --> 01:41:52,070
of finding you.

1287
01:41:52,070 --> 01:41:55,090
I'd have turned left if I'd known.'

1288
01:41:55,090 --> 01:41:56,520
'I don't believe you.

1289
01:41:56,520 --> 01:42:05,309
You started out with the hope of seeing me,
and it's no use pretending anything different.'

1290
01:42:05,309 --> 01:42:11,469
He led the way up the path and, turning the
corner, they came to a small grey house built

1291
01:42:11,469 --> 01:42:13,110
on the side of the hill.

1292
01:42:13,110 --> 01:42:19,619
There were some rough farm buildings at the
back, and a piece of land for potatoes.

1293
01:42:19,619 --> 01:42:23,619
She followed him in, bending her head under
the low doorway.

1294
01:42:23,619 --> 01:42:26,919
The room was small and square.

1295
01:42:26,919 --> 01:42:31,349
Mary looked around her in disgust.

1296
01:42:31,349 --> 01:42:34,899
'Don't you ever do any cleaning?'

1297
01:42:34,899 --> 01:42:35,979
she asked him.

1298
01:42:35,979 --> 01:42:38,989
'You ought to be ashamed of yourself.

1299
01:42:38,989 --> 01:42:45,090
Leave me that bucket of water and find me
a brush.'

1300
01:42:45,090 --> 01:42:47,139
She set to work immediately.

1301
01:42:47,139 --> 01:42:51,199
'How long has your mother been dead?'

1302
01:42:51,199 --> 01:42:55,139
'Seven years this Christmas,' he answered.

1303
01:42:55,139 --> 01:43:01,409
'Because of my father being hanged and Matt
drowned and Joss gone off to America and me

1304
01:43:01,409 --> 01:43:08,119
growing up wild, she turned religious, and
used to pray here by the hour, calling on

1305
01:43:08,119 --> 01:43:09,599
the Lord.

1306
01:43:09,599 --> 01:43:13,719
I couldn't bear that, so I ran away to sea.

1307
01:43:13,719 --> 01:43:18,369
But the sea didn't suit my stomach, and I
came back home.

1308
01:43:18,369 --> 01:43:21,149
I found Mother very thin.

1309
01:43:21,149 --> 01:43:25,179
"You ought to eat more, I said.

1310
01:43:25,179 --> 01:43:31,289
But she wouldn't listen to me, so I went off
again and stayed in Plymouth for a time, earning

1311
01:43:31,289 --> 01:43:33,439
a little in my own way.

1312
01:43:33,439 --> 01:43:38,199
I came back and found the place empty and
the door locked.

1313
01:43:38,199 --> 01:43:40,630
They told me my mother had died.

1314
01:43:40,630 --> 01:43:43,320
She'd been buried three weeks...

1315
01:43:43,320 --> 01:43:44,449
What's the matter?'

1316
01:43:44,449 --> 01:43:49,560
'It'll be a good thing when there's not a
Merlyn left in Cornwall!

1317
01:43:49,560 --> 01:43:54,479
It's better to have disease in a country than
a family like yours.

1318
01:43:54,479 --> 01:43:58,159
You and your brothers were born twisted and
evil.

1319
01:43:58,159 --> 01:44:02,769
Do you never think of what your mother must
have suffered?'

1320
01:44:02,769 --> 01:44:05,030
Jem looked at her in surprise.

1321
01:44:05,030 --> 01:44:07,949
'Mother was all right.

1322
01:44:07,949 --> 01:44:09,630
She never complained.

1323
01:44:09,630 --> 01:44:11,219
She was used to us.

1324
01:44:11,219 --> 01:44:15,840
How's the landlord of Jamaica Inn, then?'

1325
01:44:15,840 --> 01:44:20,090
'He's had too much to drink, like his father
before him.'

1326
01:44:20,090 --> 01:44:24,719
'That'll be the ruin of Joss,' said his brother
seriously.

1327
01:44:24,719 --> 01:44:28,670
'One day he'll kill himself with drink.

1328
01:44:28,670 --> 01:44:29,670
The fool!

1329
01:44:29,670 --> 01:44:33,570
Has anything been - happening at Jamaica Inn?'

1330
01:44:33,570 --> 01:44:37,800
'We had Mr Bassat from North Hill last week.'

1331
01:44:37,800 --> 01:44:39,679
'You did?

1332
01:44:39,679 --> 01:44:42,349
What did the magistrate have to say to you?'

1333
01:44:42,349 --> 01:44:45,960
'Uncle Joss was away from home.

1334
01:44:45,960 --> 01:44:51,280
Mr Bassat was determined to come into the
inn and search the rooms.

1335
01:44:51,280 --> 01:44:56,389
He broke down the door at the end of the passage,
but the room was empty.

1336
01:44:56,389 --> 01:45:03,280
He seemed disappointed, and very surprised,
and he rode away in a bad temper.

1337
01:45:03,280 --> 01:45:10,380
He asked about you, as it happened, and I
told him I had never seen you.'

1338
01:45:10,380 --> 01:45:15,789
Jem's face was without expression as she told
her story, but when she came to the end of

1339
01:45:15,789 --> 01:45:19,789
her sentence, and the mention of himself,
he laughed.

1340
01:45:19,789 --> 01:45:24,679
'Why did you lie to him? he asked.

1341
01:45:24,679 --> 01:45:27,119
'It seemed less trouble at the time.

1342
01:45:27,119 --> 01:45:31,889
If I'd thought longer, no doubt I'd have told
him the truth.

1343
01:45:31,889 --> 01:45:35,610
You've got nothing to hide, have you?'

1344
01:45:35,610 --> 01:45:43,840
'Nothing much, except that the black horse
you saw by the stream belongs to him.

1345
01:45:43,840 --> 01:45:49,659
He was grey last week, and worth a small fortune
to Mr Bassat.

1346
01:45:49,659 --> 01:45:53,649
I'll get a few pounds for him at Launceston
if I'm lucky.

1347
01:45:53,649 --> 01:45:56,769
Come down and have a look at him.'

1348
01:45:56,769 --> 01:45:59,750
They went out into the sun.

1349
01:45:59,750 --> 01:46:01,530
Then Jem spoke again.

1350
01:46:01,530 --> 01:46:07,969
'What did Mr Bassat expect to see at Jamaica
Inn?'

1351
01:46:07,969 --> 01:46:11,639
Mary looked him straight in the eyes.

1352
01:46:11,639 --> 01:46:16,599
'You ought to know that better than I do,'
she answered.

1353
01:46:16,599 --> 01:46:21,659
It was lucky for Joss that everything had
been moved,' he said quietly.

1354
01:46:21,659 --> 01:46:25,260
'It's only a matter of time before they catch
him.

1355
01:46:25,260 --> 01:46:31,499
All he does in self-defense is to get drunk,
the fool,'

1356
01:46:31,499 --> 01:46:33,269
Mary said nothing.

1357
01:46:33,269 --> 01:46:38,829
If Jem was trying to trap her by his openness,
he would be disappointed.

1358
01:46:38,829 --> 01:46:44,659
'You must have a good view from that little
room over the front door,' he said.

1359
01:46:44,659 --> 01:46:47,229
'Do they wake you from your sleep?'

1360
01:46:47,229 --> 01:46:51,510
'How do you know that's my room?'

1361
01:46:51,510 --> 01:46:54,019
Mary asked quickly.

1362
01:46:54,019 --> 01:46:56,590
She saw the surprise in his eyes.

1363
01:46:56,590 --> 01:46:58,070
Then he laughed.

1364
01:46:58,070 --> 01:47:03,599
'The window was wide open when I rode into
the yard the other morning; I've never seen

1365
01:47:03,599 --> 01:47:05,380
a window open at Jamaica Inn before.'

1366
01:47:05,380 --> 01:47:13,959
The excuse was hardly good enough for Mary,
and a horrible suspicion came into her mind.

1367
01:47:13,959 --> 01:47:20,929
Could it have been Jem who had hidden in the
empty guest room that Saturday night?

1368
01:47:20,929 --> 01:47:23,320
Something went cold inside her.

1369
01:47:23,320 --> 01:47:26,860
'What does it matter to you how much I know?

1370
01:47:26,860 --> 01:47:31,769
All I think about is getting my aunt away
from the place as soon as possible.

1371
01:47:31,769 --> 01:47:37,559
As for your brother, he can drink himself
to death for all I care.

1372
01:47:37,559 --> 01:47:40,559
His life is his own, and so is his business.

1373
01:47:40,559 --> 01:47:45,059
It's nothing to do with me.'

1374
01:47:45,059 --> 01:47:46,559
Jem whistled.

1375
01:47:46,559 --> 01:47:50,399
'So smuggling doesn't worry you after all?

1376
01:47:50,399 --> 01:47:57,399
But supposing he were concerned with other
things - supposing it were a question of life

1377
01:47:57,399 --> 01:48:02,130
and death, and perhaps murder - what then?'

1378
01:48:02,130 --> 01:48:07,769
'I don't know what you mean,' said Mary.

1379
01:48:07,769 --> 01:48:11,510
He looked at her for a long time without speaking.

1380
01:48:11,510 --> 01:48:17,919
'Perhaps not,' he said at last, 'but you'll
come to know, if you stay long enough.

1381
01:48:17,919 --> 01:48:21,800
Why does your aunt look so pale?

1382
01:48:21,800 --> 01:48:26,309
Ask her, next time the wind blows from, the
north-west...

1383
01:48:26,309 --> 01:48:27,939
Why are you going?

1384
01:48:27,939 --> 01:48:31,749
It's early yet; it won't be dark until after
four.

1385
01:48:31,749 --> 01:48:34,820
What's the matter with you?'

1386
01:48:34,820 --> 01:48:38,469
He took her face in his hands and looked into
her eyes.

1387
01:48:38,469 --> 01:48:41,760
'I believe you're frightened of me.

1388
01:48:41,760 --> 01:48:48,159
You think I've got boxes of wine and spirits
and tobacco in the little bedrooms above,

1389
01:48:48,159 --> 01:48:53,199
and that I'm going to show them to you, and
then cut your throat.

1390
01:48:53,199 --> 01:48:54,969
That's it, isn't it?

1391
01:48:54,969 --> 01:49:00,320
We're a wild lot, we Merlyns, and Jem is the
worst of us all.

1392
01:49:00,320 --> 01:49:03,520
Is that what you're thinking?'

1393
01:49:03,520 --> 01:49:06,840
She smiled back at him in spite of herself.

1394
01:49:06,840 --> 01:49:09,010
'Something of the sort.

1395
01:49:09,010 --> 01:49:14,489
But I'm not afraid of you; you needn't think
that.

1396
01:49:14,489 --> 01:49:18,789
I would even like you, if you didn't remind
me so much of your brother.'

1397
01:49:18,789 --> 01:49:27,649
'I can't help my face,' he said, 'and I'm
a much better-looking man than Joss; you must

1398
01:49:27,649 --> 01:49:29,409
admit that.'

1399
01:49:29,409 --> 01:49:35,769
'Oh, you've confidence enough to make up for
all the other qualities you lack, and I'll

1400
01:49:35,769 --> 01:49:37,329
not argue about your face.

1401
01:49:37,329 --> 01:49:38,729
Now let me go.'

1402
01:49:38,729 --> 01:49:44,179
'Are you coming to Launceston with me on Christmas
Eve?

1403
01:49:44,179 --> 01:49:50,290
'What will you be doing over at Launceston,
Jem Merlyn?'

1404
01:49:50,290 --> 01:49:54,300
'Only selling Mr Bassat's horse for him, my
dear.

1405
01:49:54,300 --> 01:49:55,809
Say you'll come.'

1406
01:49:55,809 --> 01:50:00,669
'Supposing you are caught in Launceston with
Mr Bassat's horse?'

1407
01:50:00,669 --> 01:50:04,110
'No one's going to catch me.

1408
01:50:04,110 --> 01:50:08,159
Take a risk, Mary; don't you like excitement?

1409
01:50:08,159 --> 01:50:12,920
You must be soft, down near Helford.

1410
01:50:12,920 --> 01:50:15,729
'All right, Jem Merlyn.

1411
01:50:15,729 --> 01:50:18,610
You needn't think that I'm afraid.

1412
01:50:18,610 --> 01:50:23,280
I'd be just as happy imprison as at Jamaica
Inn, anyway.

1413
01:50:23,280 --> 01:50:25,849
How do we get to Launceston?'

1414
01:50:25,849 --> 01:50:32,679
'I'll take you there in my carriage, with
Mr Bassat's horse tied up behind us.'

1415
01:50:32,679 --> 01:50:36,229
Mary was not afraid of him.

1416
01:50:36,229 --> 01:50:42,229
To prove it, she would ride beside him to
Launceston on Christmas Eve.

1417
01:50:42,229 --> 01:50:49,539
She walked away up the hill without a backward
look.

1418
01:50:49,539 --> 01:50:54,989
Darkness was falling as she crossed the road
and entered the yard at Jamaica Inn.

1419
01:50:54,989 --> 01:50:59,929
The door was opened by her aunt, who seemed
pale and anxious.

1420
01:50:59,929 --> 01:51:03,929
'Your uncle has been asking for you all day.

1421
01:51:03,929 --> 01:51:06,309
Where have you been?'

1422
01:51:06,309 --> 01:51:12,149
'I was walking on the moors - why should Uncle
Joss ask for me?

1423
01:51:12,149 --> 01:51:15,670
He never has anything to say to me.'

1424
01:51:15,670 --> 01:51:18,829
'You must speak nicely to him.

1425
01:51:18,829 --> 01:51:23,030
This is the bad time, when he's getting over
it.

1426
01:51:23,030 --> 01:51:26,610
He'll be bad-tempered - violent perhaps.

1427
01:51:26,610 --> 01:51:30,130
You mustn't pay any attention to him at times
like these.

1428
01:51:30,130 --> 01:51:32,709
He's not really himself.'

1429
01:51:32,709 --> 01:51:40,829
The long evening passed, and still there was
no call from the landlord.

1430
01:51:40,829 --> 01:51:43,159
Mary's eyes closed in spite of herself.

1431
01:51:43,159 --> 01:51:49,399
In a dream, she heard her aunt whisper: 'I'm
going to bed.

1432
01:51:49,399 --> 01:51:54,579
Your uncle must have settled down for the
night.'

1433
01:51:54,579 --> 01:51:57,320
Mary felt sleep come over her.

1434
01:51:57,320 --> 01:52:00,639
She dreamed that she was crossing the stream
again.

1435
01:52:00,639 --> 01:52:04,559
Her feet were wet.

1436
01:52:04,559 --> 01:52:09,999
It was cold... much too cold... she must climb
up the bank...

1437
01:52:09,999 --> 01:52:15,909
Mary opened her eyes and found that she was
lying on the kitchen floor beside the ashes

1438
01:52:15,909 --> 01:52:17,780
of the fire.

1439
01:52:17,780 --> 01:52:19,989
The kitchen was cold.

1440
01:52:19,989 --> 01:52:22,249
The light was low.

1441
01:52:22,249 --> 01:52:26,749
She trembled, and stretched her stiff arms.

1442
01:52:26,749 --> 01:52:34,149
Then she saw the door of the kitchen open
very slowly, little by little.

1443
01:52:34,149 --> 01:52:38,889
Suddenly it was thrown wide open, and Joss
Merlyn stood there.

1444
01:52:38,889 --> 01:52:45,349
At first, she thought that he had not seen
her; his eyes were fixed on the wall in front

1445
01:52:45,349 --> 01:52:46,360
of him.

1446
01:52:46,360 --> 01:52:52,820
She bent low, her head beneath the level of
the table, hearing nothing except the steady

1447
01:52:52,820 --> 01:52:55,629
beating of her heart.

1448
01:52:55,629 --> 01:52:58,519
Slowly he turned in her direction.

1449
01:52:58,519 --> 01:53:04,789
When his voice came, it was hardly above a
whisper: 'Who's there?

1450
01:53:04,789 --> 01:53:07,709
What are you doing?

1451
01:53:07,709 --> 01:53:11,010
Why don't you speak?'

1452
01:53:11,010 --> 01:53:13,380
His face was grey.

1453
01:53:13,380 --> 01:53:17,599
His eyes looked towards her without recognition.

1454
01:53:17,599 --> 01:53:20,110
Mary did not move.

1455
01:53:20,110 --> 01:53:23,320
She waited, holding her breath.

1456
01:53:23,320 --> 01:53:29,739
He moved forward into the room, his head bent,
his hands feeling the air, and he crept slowly

1457
01:53:29,739 --> 01:53:35,590
along the floor towards her until Mary could
feel his breath on her face.

1458
01:53:35,590 --> 01:53:42,099
'Uncle Joss,' she said softly, 'Uncle Joss...'

1459
01:53:42,099 --> 01:53:49,050
He stayed where he was, looking down at her,
and then he leant forward and touched her.

1460
01:53:49,050 --> 01:53:50,369
'Mary?

1461
01:53:50,369 --> 01:53:52,900
Is it you, Mary?

1462
01:53:52,900 --> 01:53:55,170
Why don't you speak to me?

1463
01:53:55,170 --> 01:53:57,340
Where have they gone?

1464
01:53:57,340 --> 01:53:58,989
Have you seen them?'

1465
01:53:58,989 --> 01:54:03,979
'You've made a mistake, Uncle Joss,' she said.

1466
01:54:03,979 --> 01:54:08,040
'There's no one here - only myself.

1467
01:54:08,040 --> 01:54:09,869
Aunt Patience is upstairs.

1468
01:54:09,869 --> 01:54:11,289
Are you ill?

1469
01:54:11,289 --> 01:54:14,550
Can I help you?'

1470
01:54:14,550 --> 01:54:19,129
He looked around him in the half-light, searching
the corners of the room.

1471
01:54:19,129 --> 01:54:23,309
'They can't frighten me,' he whispered.

1472
01:54:23,309 --> 01:54:27,730
'Dead men can't harm the living.

1473
01:54:27,730 --> 01:54:30,670
It's dreams; all dreams!

1474
01:54:30,670 --> 01:54:37,849
Their faces stand out like living things in
the darkness, and I wake trembling.

1475
01:54:37,849 --> 01:54:50,149
I'm thirsty, Mary; here's the key; go into
the bar and find me something to drink.'

1476
01:54:50,149 --> 01:54:54,860
When she got back, he was sitting at the table
with his head in his hands.

1477
01:54:54,860 --> 01:55:01,070
At first, she thought that he was asleep again,
but at the sound of her footsteps, he lifted

1478
01:55:01,070 --> 01:55:03,059
his head.

1479
01:55:03,059 --> 01:55:06,929
She put the bottle and the glass on the table
in front of him.

1480
01:55:06,929 --> 01:55:08,249
He filled the glass.

1481
01:55:08,249 --> 01:55:10,929
'You're a good girl.

1482
01:55:10,929 --> 01:55:14,249
I'm fond of you, Mary.

1483
01:55:14,249 --> 01:55:16,769
You've got sense, and you've got courage.

1484
01:55:16,769 --> 01:55:21,749
They ought to have made you a boy.'

1485
01:55:21,749 --> 01:55:26,130
He swallowed the drink, smiling foolishly.

1486
01:55:26,130 --> 01:55:28,269
Then he pointed at the bottle.

1487
01:55:28,269 --> 01:55:31,300
'They pay gold for this.

1488
01:55:31,300 --> 01:55:35,239
It's the best that money can buy.

1489
01:55:35,239 --> 01:55:38,190
King George himself hasn't anything better.

1490
01:55:38,190 --> 01:55:48,499
They can't catch me, Mary: I'm too clever;
I've been at the game too long.

1491
01:55:48,499 --> 01:55:56,050
There are over a hundred of us now, working
towards the border from the coast.

1492
01:55:56,050 --> 01:56:04,190
I've seen blood in my time, Mary, and I've
seen men killed many times, but this game

1493
01:56:04,190 --> 01:56:10,909
beats it all - it's running side by side with
death.'

1494
01:56:10,909 --> 01:56:13,349
He seized hold of Mary's arm.

1495
01:56:13,349 --> 01:56:17,610
'It's that cursed drink that makes a fool
of me.

1496
01:56:17,610 --> 01:56:24,010
I'm as weak as a rat when it has hold of me,
you can see that.

1497
01:56:24,010 --> 01:56:29,530
And I have dreams; I see things that frighten
me.

1498
01:56:29,530 --> 01:56:38,309
I've killed men with my own hands, pushed
them under water with my feet, beaten them

1499
01:56:38,309 --> 01:56:45,629
with rocks and stones, and I've never thought
more about it - I've slept in my bed like

1500
01:56:45,629 --> 01:56:46,959
a child.

1501
01:56:46,959 --> 01:56:55,070
But when I've had too much to drink I see
them in my dreams.

1502
01:56:55,070 --> 01:57:04,930
I see their white-green faces in front of
me, with their eyes eaten by fish; and some

1503
01:57:04,930 --> 01:57:11,139
of them are torn, with the flesh hanging off
their bones...'

1504
01:57:11,139 --> 01:57:17,559
His face was close to Mary's, his reddened
eyes looking into hers, and his breath on

1505
01:57:17,559 --> 01:57:19,079
her cheek.

1506
01:57:19,079 --> 01:57:25,999
'Did you never hear of wreckers before?' he
whispered.

1507
01:57:25,999 --> 01:57:34,090
'I've seen men hanging on the ropes of their
ships for safety, shouting in terror at the

1508
01:57:34,090 --> 01:57:36,439
sight of the breaking waves.

1509
01:57:36,439 --> 01:57:45,260
Just like flies they are, spread out on the
ropes - little black dots of men.

1510
01:57:45,260 --> 01:57:53,570
I've seen the ship break up beneath them,
and the ropes break like thread, and all of

1511
01:57:53,570 --> 01:57:59,019
them thrown into the sea, to swim for their
lives.

1512
01:57:59,019 --> 01:58:06,020
But when they reach the shore they're dead
men, Mary.'

1513
01:58:06,020 --> 01:58:12,459
He wiped his mouth on the back of his hand;
his eyes never left her face.

1514
01:58:12,459 --> 01:58:17,829
'Dead men tell no stories, Mary.'

1515
01:58:17,829 --> 01:58:24,689
She felt sick, and her hands and her feet
were icy-cold.

1516
01:58:24,689 --> 01:58:31,369
She could see the pale faces of the drowned
men, their arms above their heads; she could

1517
01:58:31,369 --> 01:58:34,409
hear the cries of fear.

1518
01:58:34,409 --> 01:58:35,809
She trembled again.

1519
01:58:35,809 --> 01:58:42,860
She looked at her uncle, and saw that he had
slipped forward in his chair, and his head

1520
01:58:42,860 --> 01:58:45,780
had fallen on his chest.

1521
01:58:45,780 --> 01:58:51,869
His mouth was wide open, and he breathed noisily
as he slept.

1522
01:58:51,869 --> 01:59:01,769
His arms rested on the table in front of him,
and his hands were folded as if in prayer.

1523
01:59:01,769 --> 01:59:06,649
CHAPTER NINE
Christmas Eve

1524
01:59:06,649 --> 01:59:12,280
On Christmas Eve, the sky was cloudy and threatened
rain.

1525
01:59:12,280 --> 01:59:17,169
Mary leant out of the window, and the soft
wet wind blew on her face.

1526
01:59:17,169 --> 01:59:25,099
In an hour's time, Jem Merlyn would be waiting
for her on the moor, to take her to Launceston

1527
01:59:25,099 --> 01:59:26,099
market.

1528
01:59:26,099 --> 01:59:33,550
Whether she met him or not depended on herself,
and she could not make up her mind.

1529
01:59:33,550 --> 01:59:38,439
She had grown older in four days, and the
face that looked back at her from her cracked

1530
01:59:38,439 --> 01:59:41,090
mirror was pale and tired.

1531
01:59:41,090 --> 01:59:45,409
There were dark rings under her eyes.

1532
01:59:45,409 --> 01:59:50,340
Sleep came to her late at night, and she had
no desire for food.

1533
01:59:50,340 --> 01:59:56,300
For the first time in her life, she saw a
likeness between herself and Aunt Patience.

1534
01:59:56,300 --> 02:00:02,079
If she tightened her mouth and bit her lips,
it could be Aunt Patience who stood there,

1535
02:00:02,079 --> 02:00:06,719
with the straight brown hair framing her face.

1536
02:00:06,719 --> 02:00:11,579
The habit of working her mouth was an easy
one to catch, as was the continuous twisting

1537
02:00:11,579 --> 02:00:14,429
of her hands.

1538
02:00:14,429 --> 02:00:18,769
Mary turned away from the mirror and began
to walk up and down her small room.

1539
02:00:18,769 --> 02:00:25,619
They shared a secret now, a secret that must
never be spoken between them.

1540
02:00:25,619 --> 02:00:31,289
Mary wondered how many years Aunt Patience
had kept that knowledge to herself in silence.

1541
02:00:31,289 --> 02:00:36,369
In her own way, Aunt Patience was a murderer
too.

1542
02:00:36,369 --> 02:00:39,010
She had killed by her silence.

1543
02:00:39,010 --> 02:00:42,519
There remained Jem Merlyn.

1544
02:00:42,519 --> 02:00:46,980
He broke into her thoughts against her will,
and she did not want him there.

1545
02:00:46,980 --> 02:00:51,039
She had enough on her mind without Jem.

1546
02:00:51,039 --> 02:00:53,039
He was too like his brother.

1547
02:00:53,039 --> 02:00:58,550
His eyes, and his mouth, and his smile.

1548
02:00:58,550 --> 02:01:03,099
She knew why Aunt Patience had made a fool
of herself ten years ago.

1549
02:01:03,099 --> 02:01:06,979
It would be easy enough to fall in love with
Jem Merlyn.

1550
02:01:06,979 --> 02:01:13,459
He was rough; he was rude; he was a thief
and a liar.

1551
02:01:13,459 --> 02:01:21,170
He stood for everything she feared and hated,
but she knew she could love him.

1552
02:01:21,170 --> 02:01:27,179
Jem Merlyn was a man, and she was a woman,
and something inside her wanted him.

1553
02:01:27,179 --> 02:01:31,460
She knew she would have to see him again.

1554
02:01:31,460 --> 02:01:38,519
Today she would go to Launceston, and this
time it was he who would answer her questions;

1555
02:01:38,519 --> 02:01:43,869
he would realize that she was no longer afraid
of the Merlyns, but could destroy them when

1556
02:01:43,869 --> 02:01:45,770
she chose.

1557
02:01:45,770 --> 02:01:50,579
And tomorrow - well, tomorrow could take care
of itself.

1558
02:01:50,579 --> 02:01:57,159
There was always Francis Davey and his promise;
there would be peace and shelter for her in

1559
02:01:57,159 --> 02:02:00,610
the house at Altarnun.

1560
02:02:00,610 --> 02:02:09,059
This was a strange Christmas, she thought,
as she walked across the East Moor.

1561
02:02:09,059 --> 02:02:15,709
In the distance, she saw a little group coming
towards her - the horse, the cart, and two

1562
02:02:15,709 --> 02:02:17,139
horses led behind.

1563
02:02:17,139 --> 02:02:21,909
The driver raised his whip in a signal of
welcome.

1564
02:02:21,909 --> 02:02:24,090
Mary felt the colour in her face.

1565
02:02:24,090 --> 02:02:29,039
He whistled as he came near, and threw a package
at her feet.

1566
02:02:29,039 --> 02:02:32,780
'A happy Christmas to you,' he said.

1567
02:02:32,780 --> 02:02:37,340
'I had a silver piece in my pocket, so I had
to spend it.

1568
02:02:37,340 --> 02:02:40,959
There's a new hat for you.'

1569
02:02:40,959 --> 02:02:45,229
She had meant to be silent on meeting him,
but this made it difficult.

1570
02:02:45,229 --> 02:02:52,059
'That's very kind of you,' she said, 'but
I'm afraid you've wasted your money.'

1571
02:02:52,059 --> 02:02:54,070
'That doesn't worry me.

1572
02:02:54,070 --> 02:02:59,369
I'm used to it,' and he looked at her in that
cool way of his.

1573
02:02:59,369 --> 02:03:01,639
'You were here early.

1574
02:03:01,639 --> 02:03:05,280
Were you afraid I'd go without you?'

1575
02:03:05,280 --> 02:03:07,590
She climbed up beside him.

1576
02:03:07,590 --> 02:03:12,019
'Mother and I used to drive into Helford once
a week on market days.

1577
02:03:12,019 --> 02:03:14,510
It all seems very long ago.

1578
02:03:14,510 --> 02:03:20,419
It hurts me when I think of it, and how we
used to laugh together, even when times were

1579
02:03:20,419 --> 02:03:21,619
bad.

1580
02:03:21,619 --> 02:03:24,409
You wouldn't understand that, of course.

1581
02:03:24,409 --> 02:03:26,300
You've never cared for anything but yourself.'

1582
02:03:26,300 --> 02:03:30,510
They rode along in silence.

1583
02:03:30,510 --> 02:03:33,079
Jem was playing with his whip.

1584
02:03:33,079 --> 02:03:38,090
Mary looked out of the corner of her eye at
his hands, and saw that they were long and

1585
02:03:38,090 --> 02:03:44,050
thin; they had the same strength, the same
sensitivity, as his brother's.

1586
02:03:44,050 --> 02:03:50,070
These hands attracted her; the others frightened
her.

1587
02:03:50,070 --> 02:03:55,329
She realized for the first time that love
and hate ran side by side; that the borderline

1588
02:03:55,329 --> 02:03:57,809
was thin between them.

1589
02:03:57,809 --> 02:04:00,439
The thought was an unpleasant one.

1590
02:04:00,439 --> 02:04:07,239
Supposing this had been Joss beside her, ten,
twenty years ago.

1591
02:04:07,239 --> 02:04:11,219
She pushed the comparison to the back of her
mind, fearing it.

1592
02:04:11,219 --> 02:04:15,369
She knew now why she hated her uncle.

1593
02:04:15,369 --> 02:04:17,150
His voice interrupted her thoughts.

1594
02:04:17,150 --> 02:04:20,909
'What are you looking at?'

1595
02:04:20,909 --> 02:04:22,300
She lifted her eyes.

1596
02:04:22,300 --> 02:04:29,369
'I happened to notice your hands,' she said
shortly; 'they are like your brother's...

1597
02:04:29,369 --> 02:04:32,780
How far do we go across the moor?

1598
02:04:32,780 --> 02:04:35,480
Isn't that the road over there?'

1599
02:04:35,480 --> 02:04:40,530
'We join it lower down and miss two or three
miles of it.

1600
02:04:40,530 --> 02:04:44,269
So you notice a man's hands, do you?

1601
02:04:44,269 --> 02:04:46,929
I should never have believed it of you.

1602
02:04:46,929 --> 02:04:51,381
You're a woman after all, then, and not a
half-grown farm boy!

1603
02:04:51,381 --> 02:04:57,999
Are you going to tell me why you have sat
in your room for days, or do you want me to

1604
02:04:57,999 --> 02:04:59,579
guess?

1605
02:04:59,579 --> 02:05:01,789
Women love to be mysterious.'

1606
02:05:01,789 --> 02:05:04,650
'There's no mystery in it.

1607
02:05:04,650 --> 02:05:09,979
You asked me last time we met why my aunt
looked as she does.

1608
02:05:09,979 --> 02:05:13,689
Well, I know now, that's all.'

1609
02:05:13,689 --> 02:05:17,419
'What are you going to do about it?'

1610
02:05:17,419 --> 02:05:20,329
Mary said: 'I haven't made up my mind.

1611
02:05:20,329 --> 02:05:23,519
I have to consider Aunt Patience.

1612
02:05:23,519 --> 02:05:27,689
You don't expect me to tell you, do you?'

1613
02:05:27,689 --> 02:05:29,709
'Why not?

1614
02:05:29,709 --> 02:05:31,320
I'm not concerned with Joss.'

1615
02:05:31,320 --> 02:05:35,989
'You're his brother, and that's enough for
me.'

1616
02:05:35,989 --> 02:05:40,859
'Do you think I'd waste my time working for
my brother?

1617
02:05:40,859 --> 02:05:43,689
He can put a rope round his own neck.

1618
02:05:43,689 --> 02:05:49,499
I may have helped myself to some tobacco now
and then, and I've smuggled goods, but I'll

1619
02:05:49,499 --> 02:05:56,269
tell you one thing, Mary Yellan, and you can
believe it or not as you like; I've never

1620
02:05:56,269 --> 02:05:59,829
killed a man - yet.'

1621
02:05:59,829 --> 02:06:03,059
He cracked the whip hard over the horse's
head.

1622
02:06:03,059 --> 02:06:09,909
'So you think I wreck ships, do you, and stand
on the shore and watch men drown?

1623
02:06:09,909 --> 02:06:14,250
And then put my hands into their pockets afterwards,
when they're swollen with water?

1624
02:06:14,250 --> 02:06:18,010
It makes a pretty picture.'

1625
02:06:18,010 --> 02:06:23,659
Whether his anger was pretended or sincere
she could not say, but his mouth was set firmly

1626
02:06:23,659 --> 02:06:28,099
and there was a flaming spot of colour high
on his cheek.

1627
02:06:28,099 --> 02:06:31,939
'You haven't said yet that you don't.'

1628
02:06:31,939 --> 02:06:36,949
'If you believe it of me, why do you drive
with me to Launceston?'

1629
02:06:36,949 --> 02:06:40,939
'Because of your bright eyes, Jem Merlyn!

1630
02:06:40,939 --> 02:06:47,760
I ride with you for no other reason,' and
she met his eyes with a directness that surprised

1631
02:06:47,760 --> 02:06:48,760
him.

1632
02:06:48,760 --> 02:06:56,469
He laughed at that, and shook his head, and
began whistling again; and suddenly there

1633
02:06:56,469 --> 02:06:59,229
was a relaxed familiarity between them.

1634
02:06:59,229 --> 02:07:03,800
The very directness of her words had deceived
him.

1635
02:07:03,800 --> 02:07:09,729
He suspected nothing of the weakness that
lay behind them, and for the moment, they

1636
02:07:09,729 --> 02:07:14,539
were companions in spite of being man and
woman.

1637
02:07:14,539 --> 02:07:21,649
They came now to the road, and as the horse
increased speed, the cart rolled along, with

1638
02:07:21,649 --> 02:07:26,159
the two stolen horses running behind.

1639
02:07:26,159 --> 02:07:31,829
It was a happy and rather heated party that
reached Launceston that afternoon.

1640
02:07:31,829 --> 02:07:37,059
Mary had thrown worry and responsibility to
the winds and in spite of her determination

1641
02:07:37,059 --> 02:07:40,699
in the morning; she had given herself to enjoyment.

1642
02:07:40,699 --> 02:07:48,420
Away from the shadow of Jamaica Inn, her natural
youth and high spirits returned.

1643
02:07:48,420 --> 02:07:56,559
She laughed because he made her laugh; there
was excitement in the air - a sense of Christmas;

1644
02:07:56,559 --> 02:08:02,129
the streets were filled with people; the little
shops were bright and cheerful.

1645
02:08:02,129 --> 02:08:06,239
This was a world that Mary loved.

1646
02:08:06,239 --> 02:08:11,729
She wore the hat that Jem had given her and
even allowed him to tie the ends under her

1647
02:08:11,729 --> 02:08:12,729
chin.

1648
02:08:12,729 --> 02:08:19,059
They had left the horse and carriage at the
top of the town, and now Jem pushed his way

1649
02:08:19,059 --> 02:08:27,189
through the crowd, leading his two stolen
horses, Mary following close behind him.

1650
02:08:27,189 --> 02:08:31,570
He led the way with confidence, making straight
for the main square.

1651
02:08:31,570 --> 02:08:37,809
Before long, a man pushed through the crowd
and came up to the horses.

1652
02:08:37,809 --> 02:08:40,869
His voice was loud and important.

1653
02:08:40,869 --> 02:08:46,559
He kept hitting his boot with his whip, and
then pointing to the horses.

1654
02:08:46,559 --> 02:08:48,780
Mary imagined him to be a dealer.

1655
02:08:48,780 --> 02:08:55,340
Soon he was joined by a little sharp-eyed
man in a black coat, who now and again touched

1656
02:08:55,340 --> 02:08:57,699
his arm and whispered in his ear.

1657
02:08:57,699 --> 02:09:05,340
Mary saw him look hard at the black horse
that had belonged to Mr Bassat; he went up

1658
02:09:05,340 --> 02:09:08,609
to him, and bent down and felt his legs.

1659
02:09:08,609 --> 02:09:13,920
Then he whispered something in the ear of
the loud-voiced man.

1660
02:09:13,920 --> 02:09:16,499
Mary watched him, nervously.

1661
02:09:16,499 --> 02:09:22,469
'Where did you get this horse?' said the dealer,
touching Jem on the shoulder.

1662
02:09:22,469 --> 02:09:26,800
'Never on the moors, not with that head and
shoulders.'

1663
02:09:26,800 --> 02:09:31,389
'I bought him from old Tim Bray; you remember
Tim?

1664
02:09:31,389 --> 02:09:34,869
He sold his farm last year and went to Dorset.

1665
02:09:34,869 --> 02:09:38,460
Tim always told me I'd get my money back on
this horse.

1666
02:09:38,460 --> 02:09:41,109
Have a look at him, won't you?

1667
02:09:41,109 --> 02:09:44,429
But he's not going cheap, I'll tell you that.

1668
02:09:44,429 --> 02:09:49,239
Look at those shoulders; there's quality for
you!

1669
02:09:49,239 --> 02:09:54,139
I tell you what, I'll take eighteen pounds
for him.'

1670
02:09:54,139 --> 02:10:01,059
The sharp-eyed man shook his head but the
dealer was interested.

1671
02:10:01,059 --> 02:10:05,960
'Make it fifteen and we might do business,'
he suggested.

1672
02:10:05,960 --> 02:10:11,030
'No, eighteen is my price, and no less.'

1673
02:10:11,030 --> 02:10:16,340
The dealer talked to his companion, and they
appeared to disagree.

1674
02:10:16,340 --> 02:10:23,179
'All right,' the dealer said finally, 'I've
no doubt you're right.

1675
02:10:23,179 --> 02:10:27,519
Perhaps we would be wise to have nothing to
do with it.

1676
02:10:27,519 --> 02:10:30,849
You can keep your horse,' he added to Jem.

1677
02:10:30,849 --> 02:10:33,539
'My friend doesn't like him.

1678
02:10:33,539 --> 02:10:38,159
Take my advice and bring down your price.

1679
02:10:38,159 --> 02:10:42,110
If you have him for long you'll be sorry.'

1680
02:10:42,110 --> 02:10:48,469
And he pushed his way through the crowd, with
the sharp-eyed man beside him, and they disappeared

1681
02:10:48,469 --> 02:10:51,149
in the direction of the local hotel.

1682
02:10:51,149 --> 02:10:55,599
Mary was glad to see them go.

1683
02:10:55,599 --> 02:11:02,329
Jem sold the other horse to a cheerful, honest-looking
farmer.

1684
02:11:02,329 --> 02:11:07,899
It began to get dark in the market square,
and the lamps were lit.

1685
02:11:07,899 --> 02:11:12,959
Mary was thinking of going back to the cart
when she heard a woman's voice behind her.

1686
02:11:12,959 --> 02:11:14,699
'Oh, look James!

1687
02:11:14,699 --> 02:11:20,300
Did you ever see such a beautiful horse in
your life?

1688
02:11:20,300 --> 02:11:23,689
He holds his head just like poor Beauty did.

1689
02:11:23,689 --> 02:11:33,760
The likeness would be quite striking, only
this animal of course is black.

1690
02:11:33,760 --> 02:11:37,059
What a pity Roger isn't here.

1691
02:11:37,059 --> 02:11:38,090
He's in his meeting.

1692
02:11:38,090 --> 02:11:39,889
What do you think of him, James?'

1693
02:11:39,889 --> 02:11:43,449
Her companion said, 'Come on, Maria, I don't
know anything about horses.

1694
02:11:43,449 --> 02:11:46,409
The horse you lost was grey, wasn't it?

1695
02:11:46,409 --> 02:11:49,309
This thing is black, coal black, my dear.

1696
02:11:49,309 --> 02:11:51,659
Do you want to buy him?'

1697
02:11:51,659 --> 02:11:55,679
'It would be such a good Christmas present
for the children.

1698
02:11:55,679 --> 02:12:01,429
They've been begging poor Roger for another
horse ever since Beauty disappeared.

1699
02:12:01,429 --> 02:12:05,219
Ask the price, James, will you?'

1700
02:12:05,219 --> 02:12:06,889
The man came forward.

1701
02:12:06,889 --> 02:12:14,459
'Here, my good man,' he called to Jem, 'do
you want to sell that black horse of yours?

1702
02:12:14,459 --> 02:12:16,749
What is your price?'

1703
02:12:16,749 --> 02:12:19,050
'Twenty-five pounds,' said Jem.

1704
02:12:19,050 --> 02:12:22,340
'I'm not anxious to sell him.

1705
02:12:22,340 --> 02:12:25,099
The lady swept towards him.

1706
02:12:25,099 --> 02:12:28,050
'I'll give you thirty for him.

1707
02:12:28,050 --> 02:12:34,909
I'm Mrs Bassat, from North Hill, and I want
the horse as a Christmas present for my children.

1708
02:12:34,909 --> 02:12:41,699
Mr Bassat is in Launceston now, but I want
the horse to be a surprise to him as well.

1709
02:12:41,699 --> 02:12:48,649
My man shall take the horse immediately, and
ride him to North Hill before Mr Bassat leaves

1710
02:12:48,649 --> 02:12:49,980
the town.

1711
02:12:49,980 --> 02:12:52,979
Here's the money.'

1712
02:12:52,979 --> 02:12:55,059
Jem took off his hat to her.

1713
02:12:55,059 --> 02:12:58,379
'Thank you, madam,' he said.

1714
02:12:58,379 --> 02:13:02,760
'I hope Mr Bassat will be pleased.

1715
02:13:02,760 --> 02:13:05,869
You'll find the horse very safe with children.'

1716
02:13:05,869 --> 02:13:10,189
'Oh, I'm certain he'll be very happy.

1717
02:13:10,189 --> 02:13:15,639
Of course, the horse is not at all like the
one we had stolen.

1718
02:13:15,639 --> 02:13:20,340
Beauty was a fine horse, and worth a great
deal of money.

1719
02:13:20,340 --> 02:13:26,239
But this little animal is pretty enough, and
will please the children.

1720
02:13:26,239 --> 02:13:29,769
Come along, James; it's getting quite dark.'

1721
02:13:29,769 --> 02:13:34,969
Jem looked quickly over his shoulder, and
touched on the arm a boy who stood behind

1722
02:13:34,969 --> 02:13:36,110
him.

1723
02:13:36,110 --> 02:13:39,949
'Here,' he said, 'would you like to earn some
money?'

1724
02:13:39,949 --> 02:13:45,239
The boy showed that he would, his mouth open
in surprise.

1725
02:13:45,239 --> 02:13:51,169
'Hold on to this horse, then, until the servant
comes for him, will you?

1726
02:13:51,169 --> 02:13:53,139
Here, take him.

1727
02:13:53,139 --> 02:13:56,709
A happy Christmas to you!'

1728
02:13:56,709 --> 02:14:05,579
And he was away in a moment, walking quickly
across the square, his hands in his pockets.

1729
02:14:05,579 --> 02:14:08,889
Mary followed, ten yards behind.

1730
02:14:08,889 --> 02:14:14,090
She struggled to hide her laughter, and was
near to bursting when they got out of sight

1731
02:14:14,090 --> 02:14:15,090
of the people.

1732
02:14:15,090 --> 02:14:23,579
'Jem Merlyn, you deserve to be hanged,' she
said, when she could speak again.

1733
02:14:23,579 --> 02:14:31,019
'To stand there in the market square and sell
that stolen horse back to Mrs Bassat herself!

1734
02:14:31,019 --> 02:14:36,929
The hair on my head has gone grey with watching
you.'

1735
02:14:36,929 --> 02:14:42,879
He threw back his head and laughed, and she
could not help herself.

1736
02:14:42,879 --> 02:14:46,189
Their laughter filled the street.

1737
02:14:46,189 --> 02:14:48,619
Jem caught her hand.

1738
02:14:48,619 --> 02:14:52,619
'You're glad you came now, aren't you?'

1739
02:14:52,619 --> 02:15:00,369
They threw themselves into the crowded market,
where Jem bought Mary gold rings for her ears.

1740
02:15:00,369 --> 02:15:07,559
They sucked oranges beneath a striped tent,
and had their fortunes told by an old woman.

1741
02:15:07,559 --> 02:15:17,479
'Do not trust a dark stranger,' she said to
Mary, and they looked at each other and laughed

1742
02:15:17,479 --> 02:15:18,479
again.

1743
02:15:18,479 --> 02:15:24,739
'There's blood on your hand, young man,' she
told him.

1744
02:15:24,739 --> 02:15:29,280
'You'll kill a man one day.'

1745
02:15:29,280 --> 02:15:35,019
'What did I tell you on the cart this morning?'
said Jem.

1746
02:15:35,019 --> 02:15:39,070
'There's no blood on my hands yet.

1747
02:15:39,070 --> 02:15:41,159
Do you believe me now?'

1748
02:15:41,159 --> 02:15:45,480
But she shook her head at him and would not
say.

1749
02:15:45,480 --> 02:15:51,289
Drops of rain fell on their faces, but they
did not care.

1750
02:15:51,289 --> 02:15:54,940
The wind rose.

1751
02:15:54,940 --> 02:16:01,329
Jem dragged Mary into the shelter of a doorway,
his arms around her shoulders, and he turned

1752
02:16:01,329 --> 02:16:05,789
her face towards him, and kissed her.

1753
02:16:05,789 --> 02:16:13,699
'Do not trust a dark stranger,' he said, and
he laughed, and kissed her again.

1754
02:16:13,699 --> 02:16:19,550
The night clouds had come up with the rain,
and it was dark in a moment.

1755
02:16:19,550 --> 02:16:24,199
'You don't want to ride on an open cart in
this wind, do you?

1756
02:16:24,199 --> 02:16:29,459
It's coming from the coast, and we'll be blown
over on the high ground.

1757
02:16:29,459 --> 02:16:32,550
We'll have to spend the night together in
Launceston.'

1758
02:16:32,550 --> 02:16:33,550
'Very likely!

1759
02:16:33,550 --> 02:16:39,840
Go and get the horse and cart, Jem, while
this rain stops for the moment.

1760
02:16:39,840 --> 02:16:42,179
I'll wait for you here.'

1761
02:16:42,179 --> 02:16:46,050
'You'll be wet to the skin on the Bodmin road!

1762
02:16:46,050 --> 02:16:50,590
Pretend you're in love with me, can't you?

1763
02:16:50,590 --> 02:16:52,340
You'd stay with me then.'

1764
02:16:52,340 --> 02:16:58,120
'Are you talking to me like this because I'm
the bar girl at Jamaica Inn?'

1765
02:16:58,120 --> 02:17:02,690
'I like the look of you, and that's enough
for any man.

1766
02:17:02,690 --> 02:17:06,389
It ought to be enough for a woman, too.'

1767
02:17:06,389 --> 02:17:09,150
'Perhaps it is, for some.

1768
02:17:09,150 --> 02:17:12,070
I'm just not made that way.'

1769
02:17:12,070 --> 02:17:20,429
'All right, I'll get the horse and cart, and
take you home to your aunt, but I'll kiss

1770
02:17:20,429 --> 02:17:24,880
you first, whether you like it or not.'

1771
02:17:24,880 --> 02:17:27,150
He took her face in his hands.

1772
02:17:27,150 --> 02:17:30,969
'One for sorrow, two for joy!

1773
02:17:30,969 --> 02:17:36,139
I'll give you the rest when you are more ready
to accept them.'

1774
02:17:36,139 --> 02:17:42,810
Then he bent his head against the rain and
she saw him disappear round the corner.

1775
02:17:42,810 --> 02:17:47,200
Mary waited, moving her feet and blowing on
her hands.

1776
02:17:47,200 --> 02:17:52,550
The long minutes passed, and still he did
not come.

1777
02:17:52,550 --> 02:17:57,050
Mary was cold and tired.

1778
02:17:57,050 --> 02:18:03,710
At last, she could bear it no longer, and
she set off up the hill in search of him.

1779
02:18:03,710 --> 02:18:09,860
The long street was empty, except for one
or two people who sheltered in doorways as

1780
02:18:09,860 --> 02:18:11,840
she had done.

1781
02:18:11,840 --> 02:18:15,940
The rain was continuous, and the wind blew
hard.

1782
02:18:15,940 --> 02:18:21,530
There was nothing left now of the Christmas
spirit.

1783
02:18:21,530 --> 02:18:27,380
The hotel looked welcoming enough, with its
lighted windows, but there was no sign of

1784
02:18:27,380 --> 02:18:28,910
the horse and cart.

1785
02:18:28,910 --> 02:18:32,120
Mary's heart sank.

1786
02:18:32,120 --> 02:18:35,910
Surely, Jem had not started back without her?

1787
02:18:35,910 --> 02:18:43,030
She paused for a moment, and then she went
to the door and entered the hotel.

1788
02:18:43,030 --> 02:18:47,440
The hall seemed to be full of gentlemen, talking
and laughing.

1789
02:18:47,440 --> 02:18:54,050
Her country clothes and wet hair caused surprise,
and a servant came up to her immediately and

1790
02:18:54,050 --> 02:18:56,610
told her to leave.

1791
02:18:56,610 --> 02:19:00,599
'I've come in search of Mr Jem Merlyn,' said
Mary firmly.

1792
02:19:00,599 --> 02:19:03,620
'He came here with a horse and cart.

1793
02:19:03,620 --> 02:19:07,420
I'm sorry to trouble you, but I'm anxious
to find him.

1794
02:19:07,420 --> 02:19:11,671
Will you please ask if he's here?'

1795
02:19:11,671 --> 02:19:16,219
She turned her back on the little group of
men who stood by the fire and watched her.

1796
02:19:16,219 --> 02:19:21,660
Among them, she recognized the dealer and
the sharp-eyed man.

1797
02:19:21,660 --> 02:19:27,820
'If it's the dark one who tried to sell my
friend a horse this afternoon, I can tell

1798
02:19:27,820 --> 02:19:33,730
you about him,' said the little man, showing
a row of broken teeth.

1799
02:19:33,730 --> 02:19:37,960
Laughter came from the group by the fire.

1800
02:19:37,960 --> 02:19:39,820
She looked from one to the other.

1801
02:19:39,820 --> 02:19:43,050
'What do you have to say?'

1802
02:19:43,050 --> 02:19:49,561
'He was in the company of a gentleman only
ten minutes ago,' answered the sharp-eyed

1803
02:19:49,561 --> 02:19:53,100
man, still smiling, and looking at her rudely.

1804
02:19:53,100 --> 02:19:59,550
'With the help of some of us he was persuaded
to enter a carriage that was waiting at the

1805
02:19:59,550 --> 02:20:00,550
door.

1806
02:20:00,550 --> 02:20:06,590
He was not keen at first, but a look from
the gentleman appeared to decide him.

1807
02:20:06,590 --> 02:20:11,350
No doubt you know what happened to the black
horse?

1808
02:20:11,350 --> 02:20:15,710
The price he was asking was undoubtedly high.'

1809
02:20:15,710 --> 02:20:20,301
His remark brought fresh laughter from the
group by the fire.

1810
02:20:20,301 --> 02:20:24,410
Mary looked steadily at the little sharp-eyed
man.

1811
02:20:24,410 --> 02:20:26,930
'Do you know where he went?'

1812
02:20:26,930 --> 02:20:27,930
'No.

1813
02:20:27,930 --> 02:20:33,530
And I'm afraid that your companion left you
no parting message.

1814
02:20:33,530 --> 02:20:37,171
But, it is Christmas.

1815
02:20:37,171 --> 02:20:40,061
It's not pleasant weather outside.

1816
02:20:40,061 --> 02:20:46,120
If you'd like to wait here until your friend
returns, myself and these gentlemen will be

1817
02:20:46,120 --> 02:20:48,460
happy to entertain you.

1818
02:20:48,460 --> 02:20:52,570
Come in and rest, and forget him.'

1819
02:20:52,570 --> 02:20:56,771
Mary turned her back on him and went out through
the door once more.

1820
02:20:56,771 --> 02:21:05,170
As it closed behind her, she could hear their
laughter.

1821
02:21:05,170 --> 02:21:10,580
She stood in the empty market square with
the wind and the rain for company.

1822
02:21:10,580 --> 02:21:15,830
So the worst had happened, and the stolen
horse had been recognized.

1823
02:21:15,830 --> 02:21:19,630
There was no other explanation.

1824
02:21:19,630 --> 02:21:20,630
Jem had gone.

1825
02:21:20,630 --> 02:21:26,300
Did they hang men for stealing as well as
for murder?

1826
02:21:26,300 --> 02:21:30,280
She felt ill, and her brain was in confusion.

1827
02:21:30,280 --> 02:21:32,840
She could make no plans.

1828
02:21:32,840 --> 02:21:38,440
She supposed that Jem was lost to her now,
anyway, and she would never see him again.

1829
02:21:38,440 --> 02:21:41,260
The adventure was over.

1830
02:21:41,260 --> 02:21:49,880
There was no happiness left in Launceston
anymore; it was a cold, grey, hateful place.

1831
02:21:49,880 --> 02:21:55,120
She walked along with the rain beating in
her face, caring little where she went, or

1832
02:21:55,120 --> 02:22:00,341
that 11 miles lay between her and her bedroom
at Jamaica Inn.

1833
02:22:00,341 --> 02:22:01,630
She walked on.

1834
02:22:01,630 --> 02:22:08,511
Then out of the darkness, she saw a carriage
coming up the hill.

1835
02:22:08,511 --> 02:22:13,950
Its progress was slow, with the full force
of the wind against it.

1836
02:22:13,950 --> 02:22:16,460
She watched it with dull eyes.

1837
02:22:16,460 --> 02:22:21,640
It was passing her, when suddenly she ran
after it and called to the driver wrapped

1838
02:22:21,640 --> 02:22:23,400
up in a coat on the seat.

1839
02:22:23,400 --> 02:22:26,530
'Are you taking the Bodmin road?

1840
02:22:26,530 --> 02:22:29,140
Have you a passenger inside?'

1841
02:22:29,140 --> 02:22:36,380
The driver shook his head and whipped his
horse, but before Mary could step to one side,

1842
02:22:36,380 --> 02:22:41,510
an arm came out of the carriage window and
a hand was laid on her shoulder.

1843
02:22:41,510 --> 02:22:50,670
'What does Mary Yellan do alone in Launceston
on Christmas Eve?' said a voice from inside.

1844
02:22:50,670 --> 02:22:52,181
The voice was gentle.

1845
02:22:52,181 --> 02:23:00,750
A pale face looked out at her from inside
the carriage; white hair and white eyes beneath

1846
02:23:00,750 --> 02:23:02,710
the broad black hat.

1847
02:23:02,710 --> 02:23:08,690
It was the Vicar of Altarnun.

1848
02:23:08,690 --> 02:23:14,830
She watched his face in the darkness; his
thin nose curved down like the beak of a bird,

1849
02:23:14,830 --> 02:23:20,181
his lips narrow and colourless, pressed firmly
together.

1850
02:23:20,181 --> 02:23:25,931
He leant forward with his chin resting on
a walking stick that he held between his knees.

1851
02:23:25,931 --> 02:23:32,000
For the moment, she could see nothing of his
eyes: they were hidden by his short white

1852
02:23:32,000 --> 02:23:34,390
eyelashes.

1853
02:23:34,390 --> 02:23:39,750
Then he turned in his seat and looked at her,
and the eyes that looked at her were white

1854
02:23:39,750 --> 02:23:43,240
too, expressionless as glass.

1855
02:23:43,240 --> 02:23:52,610
'So we ride together for the second time,'
he said, and his voice was soft and low, like

1856
02:23:52,610 --> 02:23:53,940
the voice of a woman.

1857
02:23:53,940 --> 02:24:00,400
'Once more I have the good fortune to help
you on your way.

1858
02:24:00,400 --> 02:24:02,141
Well?'

1859
02:24:02,141 --> 02:24:08,910
He looked steadily at her, and she found herself
trying to give an explanation of her day.

1860
02:24:08,910 --> 02:24:15,250
As before at Altarnun, there was something
about him that made her sound like a fool,

1861
02:24:15,250 --> 02:24:21,521
for she came out of the story badly - just
another woman who had made herself cheap at

1862
02:24:21,521 --> 02:24:26,980
Launceston market and had been left by the
man of her choice to find her way home alone.

1863
02:24:26,980 --> 02:24:36,570
'What was the name of your companion?' he
asked quietly; and she paused, awkward and

1864
02:24:36,570 --> 02:24:40,601
uncomfortable, her sense of guilt stronger
than ever.

1865
02:24:40,601 --> 02:24:44,820
'He was my uncle s brother.'

1866
02:24:44,820 --> 02:24:52,330
'You mean the brother knows nothing of the
landlord's trade by night?'

1867
02:24:52,330 --> 02:24:54,400
continued the gentle voice beside her.

1868
02:24:54,400 --> 02:25:00,600
'He is not of the company who bring the wagons
to Jamaica Inn?'

1869
02:25:00,600 --> 02:25:03,800
'I don't know,' she said.

1870
02:25:03,800 --> 02:25:06,040
'I have no proof.

1871
02:25:06,040 --> 02:25:07,760
He admits nothing.

1872
02:25:07,760 --> 02:25:13,340
But he told me one thing: that he had never
killed a man.

1873
02:25:13,340 --> 02:25:14,630
And I believe him.

1874
02:25:14,630 --> 02:25:20,420
He also said that my uncle was running straight
into the hands of the law, and that they would

1875
02:25:20,420 --> 02:25:23,080
catch him before long.

1876
02:25:23,080 --> 02:25:27,790
He surely would not say that if he were one
of the company.

1877
02:25:27,790 --> 02:25:30,630
You told me before that you knew Mr Bassat.

1878
02:25:30,630 --> 02:25:33,350
Perhaps you have some influence with him.

1879
02:25:33,350 --> 02:25:38,561
Could you persuade him to deal kindly with
Jem Merlyn, when the time comes?

1880
02:25:38,561 --> 02:25:42,960
After all, he is young; he could start life
again.

1881
02:25:42,960 --> 02:25:45,870
It would be easy for a man in your position.'

1882
02:25:45,870 --> 02:25:53,720
'I know Mr Bassat only very slightly,' he
told her gently.

1883
02:25:53,720 --> 02:25:59,440
'Once or twice we have spoken of matters which
concern our two villages.

1884
02:25:59,440 --> 02:26:07,710
It is hardly likely that he would pardon a
thief because of me, especially if the thief

1885
02:26:07,710 --> 02:26:12,470
is guilty and happens to be the brother of
the landlord of Jamaica Inn.

1886
02:26:12,470 --> 02:26:15,490
How old are you?'

1887
02:26:15,490 --> 02:26:16,490
'Twenty-three.'

1888
02:26:16,490 --> 02:26:24,850
'You are very young, Mary Yellan,' he said
softly; 'you are nothing but a chicken with

1889
02:26:24,850 --> 02:26:27,590
the broken shell still around you.

1890
02:26:27,590 --> 02:26:35,961
Women like you have no need to cry over a
man met once or twice; and a first kiss is

1891
02:26:35,961 --> 02:26:39,050
not a thing to be remembered.

1892
02:26:39,050 --> 02:26:44,570
You will forget your friend with his stolen
horse very soon.

1893
02:26:44,570 --> 02:26:51,990
Come now, dry your eyes; you are not the first
to cry over a lost lover.'

1894
02:26:51,990 --> 02:26:55,011
He treated her problem lightly.

1895
02:26:55,011 --> 02:26:59,891
She wondered why he had not used the words
of comfort expected from a priest.

1896
02:26:59,891 --> 02:27:06,150
She remembered that last ride with him, when
he had whipped his horse into a fever of speed,

1897
02:27:06,150 --> 02:27:10,970
and how he had bent forward in his seat and
had whispered under his breath words she had

1898
02:27:10,970 --> 02:27:12,470
not understood.

1899
02:27:12,470 --> 02:27:18,490
Again, she felt something of the same discomfort,
which she connected with his strange hair

1900
02:27:18,490 --> 02:27:24,360
and eyes, as though his unusual appearance
cut him off from the rest of the world.

1901
02:27:24,360 --> 02:27:34,120
'So I was right in my guess, and all has been
quiet at Jamaica Inn?' he said after a while.

1902
02:27:34,120 --> 02:27:39,760
Immediately she remembered the full story
of the past week, and the new knowledge that

1903
02:27:39,760 --> 02:27:41,590
had come to her.

1904
02:27:41,590 --> 02:27:47,760
'Mr Davey she whispered, 'have you ever heard
of wreckers?

1905
02:27:47,760 --> 02:27:53,870
It was too dark to see his face, but she heard
him swallow.

1906
02:27:53,870 --> 02:27:57,971
'My uncle is one of them.

1907
02:27:57,971 --> 02:28:01,250
He told me so himself.'

1908
02:28:01,250 --> 02:28:05,870
Still her companion made no reply, and she
went on in a whisper.

1909
02:28:05,870 --> 02:28:13,280
'They are in it, every one of them, from the
coast to the river bank, all those men I saw

1910
02:28:13,280 --> 02:28:19,490
that first Saturday in the bar at the inn
- the sailors, the thieves, the pedlar with

1911
02:28:19,490 --> 02:28:21,010
the broken teeth.

1912
02:28:21,010 --> 02:28:27,721
They've murdered women and children with their
own hands; they've held them under water;

1913
02:28:27,721 --> 02:28:30,740
they've killed them with rocks and stones.

1914
02:28:30,740 --> 02:28:37,350
Those are death wagons that travel the road
by night, and the goods they carry are from

1915
02:28:37,350 --> 02:28:41,011
wrecked ships, bought at the price of blood.

1916
02:28:41,011 --> 02:28:47,471
And that's why my uncle is feared and hated
by the people in the houses and farms, and

1917
02:28:47,471 --> 02:28:53,461
why all doors are barred against him, and
why the coaches drive past the inn in a cloud

1918
02:28:53,461 --> 02:28:54,840
of dust.

1919
02:28:54,840 --> 02:28:58,391
They suspect what they cannot prove.

1920
02:28:58,391 --> 02:29:05,170
There, Mr Davey; now you know the truth about
Jamaica Inn.'

1921
02:29:05,170 --> 02:29:13,010
'So the landlord talks when he has had too
much drink?' he said, and it seemed to Mary

1922
02:29:13,010 --> 02:29:19,420
that his voice lacked something of its usual
gentle quality; but when she looked up at

1923
02:29:19,420 --> 02:29:24,860
him his eyes looking back at her were as cold
and expressionless as always.

1924
02:29:24,860 --> 02:29:27,710
'He talks, yes.

1925
02:29:27,710 --> 02:29:29,470
That's how I know.

1926
02:29:29,470 --> 02:29:35,830
And perhaps that's why I've stopped trusting
people, God and even myself; and why I acted

1927
02:29:35,830 --> 02:29:37,420
like a fool today in Launceston.'

1928
02:29:37,420 --> 02:29:43,460
The wind had increased in force.

1929
02:29:43,460 --> 02:29:45,890
The carriage shook.

1930
02:29:45,890 --> 02:29:52,210
There was no shelter now; the moor on either
side was empty, and the clouds flew fast over

1931
02:29:52,210 --> 02:29:53,340
the land.

1932
02:29:53,340 --> 02:30:00,660
There was a salty wet smell to the wind that
had come from the sea 15 miles away.

1933
02:30:00,660 --> 02:30:03,200
Francis Davey leant forward in his seat.

1934
02:30:03,200 --> 02:30:07,090
'We are coming to the turning that leads to
Altarnun.

1935
02:30:07,090 --> 02:30:13,460
The driver is going on to Bodmin and will
take you to Jamaica Inn.

1936
02:30:13,460 --> 02:30:17,440
I shall leave you at the turning and walk
down to the village.

1937
02:30:17,440 --> 02:30:25,360
Am I the only man to know your secret, or
do I share it with the landlords brother?'

1938
02:30:25,360 --> 02:30:28,590
'Jem Merlyn knows,' she said.

1939
02:30:28,590 --> 02:30:31,521
'We spoke of it this morning.

1940
02:30:31,521 --> 02:30:36,120
He said little, though, and I know that he
is not friendly with my uncle.

1941
02:30:36,120 --> 02:30:39,561
Anyway, it doesn't matter now.

1942
02:30:39,561 --> 02:30:41,570
Jem is going to prison for another crime.'

1943
02:30:41,570 --> 02:30:50,740
'And suppose he could save himself by telling
about his brother, what then, Mary Yellan?

1944
02:30:50,740 --> 02:30:54,761
There's a thought for you.'

1945
02:30:54,761 --> 02:30:57,040
Mary was surprised by this new idea.

1946
02:30:57,040 --> 02:31:00,261
But the Vicar of Altarnun must have read her
thoughts.

1947
02:31:00,261 --> 02:31:06,380
'That would be a relief to you and to him,
no doubt, if he had never helped with the

1948
02:31:06,380 --> 02:31:07,380
wrecking.

1949
02:31:07,380 --> 02:31:11,660
But there is always the doubt, isn't there?

1950
02:31:11,660 --> 02:31:15,300
And neither you nor I knows the answer.

1951
02:31:15,300 --> 02:31:22,590
A guilty man does not usually tie the rope
round his own neck.'

1952
02:31:22,590 --> 02:31:27,490
Mary made a helpless movement with her hands,
and he laid his hand on her knee.

1953
02:31:27,490 --> 02:31:31,291
'I will tell you one thing to comfort you.

1954
02:31:31,291 --> 02:31:35,021
A week from now will bring the New Year.

1955
02:31:35,021 --> 02:31:42,100
The false lights have burnt for the last time,
and there will be no more wrecks.'

1956
02:31:42,100 --> 02:31:43,510
'I don t understand you.

1957
02:31:43,510 --> 02:31:49,601
How do you know this, and what has the New
Year to do with it?'

1958
02:31:49,601 --> 02:31:52,980
He called the driver to stop the horse.

1959
02:31:52,980 --> 02:31:56,040
'I am returning tonight from a meeting in
Launceston.

1960
02:31:56,040 --> 02:32:02,851
Those of us present were informed that at
last the Government is prepared to guard the

1961
02:32:02,851 --> 02:32:03,851
coast.

1962
02:32:03,851 --> 02:32:09,710
There will be watchers on the cliffs, and
the paths now known only to men like your

1963
02:32:09,710 --> 02:32:13,860
uncle and his companions will be followed
by officers of the law.

1964
02:32:13,860 --> 02:32:21,530
There will be a chain across England, Mary,
that will be very hard to break.

1965
02:32:21,530 --> 02:32:24,760
Now do you understand?'

1966
02:32:24,760 --> 02:32:29,130
He opened the door of the carriage and stepped
out into the road.

1967
02:32:29,130 --> 02:32:31,320
'Your troubles are over.

1968
02:32:31,320 --> 02:32:37,630
Tomorrow is Christmas Day, and the bells at
Altarnun will be ringing for peace.

1969
02:32:37,630 --> 02:32:41,311
I shall think of you.'

1970
02:32:41,311 --> 02:32:49,750
He waved his hand to the driver, and the carriage
went on without him.

1971
02:32:49,750 --> 02:32:55,820
There were still 3 miles to go, and those
miles were the wildest of all.

1972
02:32:55,820 --> 02:32:58,550
She sat in the corner of the carriage.

1973
02:32:58,550 --> 02:33:04,370
Through the open window, travelling down on
the wind, she heard a shot, and a distant

1974
02:33:04,370 --> 02:33:06,010
shout and a cry.

1975
02:33:06,010 --> 02:33:10,490
The voices of men came out of the darkness.

1976
02:33:10,490 --> 02:33:13,010
She leant out of the window.

1977
02:33:13,010 --> 02:33:18,580
The road rose steeply from the valley, and
there in the distance were the tall chimneys

1978
02:33:18,580 --> 02:33:21,510
of Jamaica Inn.

1979
02:33:21,510 --> 02:33:28,220
Down the road came a company of men, led by
one who carried a light before him as he ran.

1980
02:33:28,220 --> 02:33:35,180
Another shot sounded, and the driver of the
carriage slipped over in his seat and fell.

1981
02:33:35,180 --> 02:33:40,120
The horse went towards the edge of the road
like a blind thing.

1982
02:33:40,120 --> 02:33:44,300
The carriage swung wildly, then was still.

1983
02:33:44,300 --> 02:33:49,501
Somebody laughed; there was a whistle and
a cry.

1984
02:33:49,501 --> 02:33:55,521
A face appeared at the carriage window, wild
hair above the reddened eyes.

1985
02:33:55,521 --> 02:34:00,200
The lips were parted to show white teeth.

1986
02:34:00,200 --> 02:34:09,250
One hand held a light, the other a smoking
gun; they were long, thin hands, things of

1987
02:34:09,250 --> 02:34:15,420
beauty and sensitivity, though the rounded
nails were dirty.

1988
02:34:15,420 --> 02:34:21,210
Joss Merlyn laughed; then he pulled her out
beside him on the road, holding the light

1989
02:34:21,210 --> 02:34:25,670
above his head so that all could see her.

1990
02:34:25,670 --> 02:34:30,880
There were ten or twelve of them standing
in the road, with torn and dirty clothes,

1991
02:34:30,880 --> 02:34:38,771
half of them as much the worse for drink as
their leader, wild eyes rolling in their bearded

1992
02:34:38,771 --> 02:34:44,681
faces; one or two hand guns in their hands,
or were armed with broken bottles, knives

1993
02:34:44,681 --> 02:34:47,180
and stones.

1994
02:34:47,180 --> 02:34:53,000
Harry the pedlar stood holding the horses
head, while face-down on the road lay the

1995
02:34:53,000 --> 02:34:59,480
driver of the carriage, his arm bent under
him, his body still.

1996
02:34:59,480 --> 02:35:05,790
When they saw who she was, a shout of laughter
broke from the men, and the pedlar put two

1997
02:35:05,790 --> 02:35:08,870
fingers to his mouth and whistled.

1998
02:35:08,870 --> 02:35:15,170
The landlord seized her loose hair in his
hand and twisted it like a rope.

1999
02:35:15,170 --> 02:35:18,760
'So its you, is it?

2000
02:35:18,760 --> 02:35:24,440
You've chosen to come back again?'

2001
02:35:24,440 --> 02:35:26,040
Mary said nothing.

2002
02:35:26,040 --> 02:35:31,681
She looked from one to the other of the men
in the crowd and they pushed in on her, laughing,

2003
02:35:31,681 --> 02:35:35,261
pointing to her wet clothes and shouting insults.

2004
02:35:35,261 --> 02:35:39,900
'So you can't talk?'

2005
02:35:39,900 --> 02:35:46,271
cried her uncle, and hit her across the face
with the back of his hand.

2006
02:35:46,271 --> 02:35:52,740
She put up an arm to protect herself, but
