2219
02:52:08,920 --> 02:52:12,760
might yet carry them away to safety.

2220
02:52:12,760 --> 02:52:18,580
Those who carried guns now had the advantage,
and the landlord, with his remaining supporter

2221
02:52:18,580 --> 02:52:25,840
Harry the pedlar by his side, stood with his
back to the wagon and shot into the crowd.

2222
02:52:25,840 --> 02:52:29,260
This won the wagon for the landlord.

2223
02:52:29,260 --> 02:52:34,500
The remaining men, frightened at the sight
of the blood and the dying men, turned all

2224
02:52:34,500 --> 02:52:40,630
at the same moment and scattered up the twisting
track, anxious now to put a safe distance

2225
02:52:40,630 --> 02:52:44,670
between themselves and their former leader.

2226
02:52:44,670 --> 02:52:50,820
The landlord, leant against the wagon holding
the smoking, murderous gun, blood running

2227
02:52:50,820 --> 02:52:53,510
freely from a cut beside his eye.

2228
02:52:53,510 --> 02:52:58,360
Now that they were alone, he and the pedlar
wasted little time.

2229
02:52:58,360 --> 02:53:03,530
The goods that had been brought up the valley
they threw on the wagon with Mary next to

2230
02:53:03,530 --> 02:53:04,820
them.

2231
02:53:04,820 --> 02:53:08,760
The main store was still down on the sand
and washed by the tide.

2232
02:53:08,760 --> 02:53:13,570
They dared not risk collecting it; there was
simply no time.

2233
02:53:13,570 --> 02:53:18,920
The two men who had been shot lay in the road
beside the wagon.

2234
02:53:18,920 --> 02:53:24,160
Their bodies bore witness, and must be destroyed.

2235
02:53:24,160 --> 02:53:28,841
It was Harry the pedlar who dragged them to
the fire.

2236
02:53:28,841 --> 02:53:33,420
It was burning well; much of the carriage
had disappeared already, though one red wheel

2237
02:53:33,420 --> 02:53:38,510
stuck up above the blackened and broken wood.

2238
02:53:38,510 --> 02:53:43,870
Joss Merlyn led the remaining horses to the
wagon, and without a word, the two men climbed

2239
02:53:43,870 --> 02:53:47,780
in and whipped them into action.

2240
02:53:47,780 --> 02:53:52,360
Lying on her back, Mary watched the low clouds
pass across the sky.

2241
02:53:52,360 --> 02:53:58,460
Darkness had gone; the morning was wet and
grey.

2242
02:53:58,460 --> 02:54:03,640
From far away across the fields came the sound
of church bells.

2243
02:54:03,640 --> 02:54:10,261
She remembered suddenly that it was Christmas
Day.

2244
02:54:10,261 --> 02:54:13,710
CHAPTER ELEVEN
Joss Plans to Escape

2245
02:54:13,710 --> 02:54:19,440
The square of glass was familiar to her.

2246
02:54:19,440 --> 02:54:24,470
It was larger than the carriage window, and
there was a crack across it that she remembered

2247
02:54:24,470 --> 02:54:25,970
well.

2248
02:54:25,970 --> 02:54:31,660
She kept her eyes on it, struggling with memory,
and she wondered why she no longer felt the

2249
02:54:31,660 --> 02:54:36,570
rain on her face and the steady current of
wind.

2250
02:54:36,570 --> 02:54:42,440
Mary cried, and turned her head restlessly
from side to side; out of the corner of her

2251
02:54:42,440 --> 02:54:48,890
eye, she saw the brown, discoloured wall beside
her and the old nail- head where a picture

2252
02:54:48,890 --> 02:54:51,360
had once hung.

2253
02:54:51,360 --> 02:54:55,730
She was lying in her bedroom at Jamaica Inn.

2254
02:54:55,730 --> 02:55:02,310
Now there was a face bending down to her,
and she drew back, her hands in front of her,

2255
02:55:02,310 --> 02:55:06,230
because the ugly mouth and broken teeth of
the pedlar were still in her mind.

2256
02:55:06,230 --> 02:55:12,741
Her hands were held gently, though, and the
eyes that looked down at her, reddened like

2257
02:55:12,741 --> 02:55:17,761
her own from crying, were watery and blue.

2258
02:55:17,761 --> 02:55:18,990
It was Aunt Patience.

2259
02:55:18,990 --> 02:55:24,131
'How long have I been lying here?'

2260
02:55:24,131 --> 02:55:28,980
Mary asked, and she was told that this was
the second day.

2261
02:55:28,980 --> 02:55:33,580
For a moment, she was silent, considering
this information.

2262
02:55:33,580 --> 02:55:39,780
Then she sat up in bed and swung her legs
to the floor, her head aching with the effort.

2263
02:55:39,780 --> 02:55:44,100
'What are you going to do?'

2264
02:55:44,100 --> 02:55:50,410
Aunt Patience pulled at her nervously, but
the young woman shook her off and began, slowly

2265
02:55:50,410 --> 02:55:53,340
and painfully, to put on her clothes.

2266
02:55:53,340 --> 02:55:59,610
'Aunt Patience, I have gone through enough
out of loyalty to you.

2267
02:55:59,610 --> 02:56:03,811
You can't expect me to stand any more.

2268
02:56:03,811 --> 02:56:09,851
Whatever Uncle Joss may have been to you once,
he isn't human now.

2269
02:56:09,851 --> 02:56:13,771
He's an animal, half-crazy with drink and
blood.

2270
02:56:13,771 --> 02:56:19,940
Men were murdered by him on the coast; don't
you understand?

2271
02:56:19,940 --> 02:56:22,771
Men were drowned in the sea.

2272
02:56:22,771 --> 02:56:24,980
I can see nothing else.

2273
02:56:24,980 --> 02:56:29,700
I shall think of nothing else until my dying
day.'

2274
02:56:29,700 --> 02:56:39,100
The door opened; the landlord of Jamaica Inn
stood in the doorway.

2275
02:56:39,100 --> 02:56:45,170
He looked tired and grey; the cut above his
eye was still bright red.

2276
02:56:45,170 --> 02:56:49,790
He was dirty and unwashed, and there were
black shadows under his eyes.

2277
02:56:49,790 --> 02:56:56,060
'I thought I heard voices in the yard, but
I saw no one.

2278
02:56:56,060 --> 02:56:58,120
Did you hear anything?'

2279
02:56:58,120 --> 02:57:00,790
Nobody answered.

2280
02:57:00,790 --> 02:57:06,180
He sat down on the bed, his hands picking
at the bedclothes, his eyes wandering from

2281
02:57:06,180 --> 02:57:07,990
the window to the door.

2282
02:57:07,990 --> 02:57:09,850
'He'll come.

2283
02:57:09,850 --> 02:57:12,650
He's sure to come.

2284
02:57:12,650 --> 02:57:17,021
I've cut my own throat; I've disobeyed him.

2285
02:57:17,021 --> 02:57:22,681
He warned me once, and I laughed at him; I
didn't listen.

2286
02:57:22,681 --> 02:57:26,040
I wanted to play the game on my own.

2287
02:57:26,040 --> 02:57:30,320
It means death for us, for all three of us
sitting here.

2288
02:57:30,320 --> 02:57:33,380
We're finished, I tell you.

2289
02:57:33,380 --> 02:57:36,090
Why did you let me drink?

2290
02:57:36,090 --> 02:57:41,840
Why didn't you break every bottle in the house,
and turn the key on me?

2291
02:57:41,840 --> 02:57:44,021
I'd not have hurt you.

2292
02:57:44,021 --> 02:57:49,710
Now it's too late; the end has come.'

2293
02:57:49,710 --> 02:57:55,630
He looked from one to the other of them, his
reddened eyes hollow; the women looked back

2294
02:57:55,630 --> 02:57:58,971
without understanding.

2295
02:57:58,971 --> 02:58:02,100
'What do you mean?' said Mary at last.

2296
02:58:02,100 --> 02:58:04,830
'Who are you afraid of?

2297
02:58:04,830 --> 02:58:07,100
Who warned you?'

2298
02:58:07,100 --> 02:58:13,310
He shook his head, and his hands wandered
to his mouth, the fingers restless.

2299
02:58:13,310 --> 02:58:19,030
'No,' he said slowly, 'my secrets are still
my own.

2300
02:58:19,030 --> 02:58:27,561
But I tell you one thing - and you're in it
now as much as Patience there - we have enemies

2301
02:58:27,561 --> 02:58:30,530
on either side of us now.

2302
02:58:30,530 --> 02:58:36,460
We have the law on one hand, and on the other...'

2303
02:58:36,460 --> 02:58:41,830
He stopped himself, the old look beginning
to return to his eyes once more.

2304
02:58:41,830 --> 02:58:46,030
'You'd like to know, wouldn't you?

2305
02:58:46,030 --> 02:58:50,591
You'd like to run out of the house with the
name on your lips.

2306
02:58:50,591 --> 02:58:53,320
You'd like to see me hanged.

2307
02:58:53,320 --> 02:58:58,010
All right, I don't blame you for it.

2308
02:58:58,010 --> 02:59:02,320
But I saved you too, didn't I?

2309
02:59:02,320 --> 02:59:08,800
Nobody touched you last night except myself,
and I've not spoilt your pretty face.

2310
02:59:08,800 --> 02:59:11,330
Let's get out of here.

2311
02:59:11,330 --> 02:59:17,590
This room smells of decay.

2312
02:59:17,590 --> 02:59:19,721
They followed him without a word.

2313
02:59:19,721 --> 02:59:24,910
He led the way to the kitchen, where the door
was locked and the window barred.

2314
02:59:24,910 --> 02:59:28,810
The landlord pulled the wooden shutters closed
too.

2315
02:59:28,810 --> 02:59:31,771
Then he turned and faced the women.

2316
02:59:31,771 --> 02:59:34,811
'We've got to think out a plan.

2317
02:59:34,811 --> 02:59:42,400
We've been sitting here for nearly two days
now, like rats in a trap.

2318
02:59:42,400 --> 02:59:44,190
And I've had enough, I tell you.

2319
02:59:44,190 --> 02:59:48,771
I never could play that sort of game.'

2320
02:59:48,771 --> 02:59:56,200
His wife crept over to him and touched him
on the arm, passing her tongue over her lips.

2321
02:59:56,200 --> 03:00:00,280
'Well, what is it?' he said wildly.

2322
03:00:00,280 --> 03:00:06,610
'Why can't we creep away now, before it's
too late?

2323
03:00:06,610 --> 03:00:12,240
We'd be in Launceston and then out of the
area in a few hours.

2324
03:00:12,240 --> 03:00:14,660
We could travel by night.

2325
03:00:14,660 --> 03:00:20,580
We could head east where we'd be safe.'

2326
03:00:20,580 --> 03:00:23,200
'You fool!' he shouted.

2327
03:00:23,200 --> 03:00:30,070
'Don't you realize that there are people on
the road between here and Launceston who think

2328
03:00:30,070 --> 03:00:37,250
I'm the devil himself - who are only waiting
for their chance to charge me with every crime

2329
03:00:37,250 --> 03:00:38,750
in Cornwall?

2330
03:00:38,750 --> 03:00:45,561
Everybody round here knows by now what happened
on the coast on Christmas Eve, and if they

2331
03:00:45,561 --> 03:00:49,950
see us running away they'll have the proof.

2332
03:00:49,950 --> 03:00:55,050
Don't you think I've wanted to get away and
save myself?

2333
03:00:55,050 --> 03:01:01,790
No, we've got one chance - one single chance
in a million.

2334
03:01:01,790 --> 03:01:04,660
We've got to lie quiet.

2335
03:01:04,660 --> 03:01:09,920
If we stay here at Jamaica Inn it may confuse
them.

2336
03:01:09,920 --> 03:01:12,830
They've got to look for proof.

2337
03:01:12,830 --> 03:01:18,360
They've got to get sworn proof before they
lay hands on us.

2338
03:01:18,360 --> 03:01:26,920
Oh, yes, the ship's there with her back broken
on the rocks, and piles of things lying on

2339
03:01:26,920 --> 03:01:29,510
the sand ready to take away.

2340
03:01:29,510 --> 03:01:34,550
They'll find two burnt bodies, and a pile
of ashes.

2341
03:01:34,550 --> 03:01:40,280
Many of us will be suspected, but where's
the proof?

2342
03:01:40,280 --> 03:01:42,681
Answer me that.

2343
03:01:42,681 --> 03:01:47,040
I was here that night with my family!'

2344
03:01:47,040 --> 03:01:51,530
'You've forgotten one thing, haven't you?'
said Mary.

2345
03:01:51,530 --> 03:01:54,790
'No, my dear, I have not.

2346
03:01:54,790 --> 03:02:03,740
The driver of that carriage was shot not a
quarter of a mile down the road outside.

2347
03:02:03,740 --> 03:02:09,001
You were hoping we'd left the body there,
weren't you?

2348
03:02:09,001 --> 03:02:15,710
The body travelled with us to the coast and
it lies now, if I remember rightly, beneath

2349
03:02:15,710 --> 03:02:20,591
a 10- foot bank of sand.

2350
03:02:20,591 --> 03:02:24,670
Of course, someone is going to miss him.

2351
03:02:24,670 --> 03:02:32,061
I'm prepared for that; but as they'll never
find his carriage it does not matter much.

2352
03:02:32,061 --> 03:02:37,110
Perhaps he was tired of his wife and has driven
to Penzance.

2353
03:02:37,110 --> 03:02:40,931
They can look for him there.'

2354
03:02:40,931 --> 03:02:47,130
He threw back his head and laughed; but his
laugh was cut short in the middle, his mouth

2355
03:02:47,130 --> 03:02:52,310
shut like a trap, his face as white as a sheet.

2356
03:02:52,310 --> 03:02:56,690
'Listen,' he whispered, 'listen...'

2357
03:02:56,690 --> 03:03:02,430
They followed the direction of his eyes, which
were fixed on the crack of light that came

2358
03:03:02,430 --> 03:03:04,930
through the shutters.

2359
03:03:04,930 --> 03:03:11,830
Something was knocking gently at the kitchen
window... knocking lightly, softly at the

2360
03:03:11,830 --> 03:03:12,930
glass.

2361
03:03:12,930 --> 03:03:17,940
There was no other sound in the kitchen except
for the frightened breathing of Aunt Patience,

2362
03:03:17,940 --> 03:03:23,280
whose hand crept along the table towards Mary.

2363
03:03:23,280 --> 03:03:26,530
The landlord stood completely still for a
moment.

2364
03:03:26,530 --> 03:03:32,150
Then he bent forward until his fingers reached
the gun that stood against the chair, never

2365
03:03:32,150 --> 03:03:34,761
once taking his eyes from the shutters.

2366
03:03:34,761 --> 03:03:39,391
He jumped forward, tearing the shutters open.

2367
03:03:39,391 --> 03:03:46,640
A man stood outside the window, his face pressed
against the glass, his broken teeth showing

2368
03:03:46,640 --> 03:03:49,440
in a twisted smile.

2369
03:03:49,440 --> 03:03:52,200
It was Harry the pedlar.

2370
03:03:52,200 --> 03:03:55,350
Joss Merlyn swore, and threw open the window.

2371
03:03:55,350 --> 03:03:57,230
'Come inside, can't you?

2372
03:03:57,230 --> 03:04:01,850
Do you want to be shot, you fool?

2373
03:04:01,850 --> 03:04:04,890
Unlock the door, Mary.'

2374
03:04:04,890 --> 03:04:07,550
She did so without a word.

2375
03:04:07,550 --> 03:04:14,570
'Well, have you brought news?' asked the landlord.

2376
03:04:14,570 --> 03:04:17,431
The pedlar pointed over his shoulder.

2377
03:04:17,431 --> 03:04:23,960
'The country's wild with anger; they're crazy
for blood and justice.

2378
03:04:23,960 --> 03:04:29,980
There'll only be one end to this storm, Joss,
and you know the name for it, don't you?'

2379
03:04:29,980 --> 03:04:32,780
He made a sign with his hands across his throat.

2380
03:04:32,780 --> 03:04:36,150
'We've got to run,' he said.

2381
03:04:36,150 --> 03:04:38,400
'It's our only chance.

2382
03:04:38,400 --> 03:04:43,840
The roads are poison, and Bodmin and Launceston
worst of all.

2383
03:04:43,840 --> 03:04:49,250
I'll keep to the moors; it'll take me longer,
I know that, but what does that matter if

2384
03:04:49,250 --> 03:04:51,010
you save yourself from hanging?'

2385
03:04:51,010 --> 03:04:55,551
'So you'll give up, Harry, will you?

2386
03:04:55,551 --> 03:04:58,780
Run like a beaten dog?

2387
03:04:58,780 --> 03:05:02,350
Have they proved it was us?

2388
03:05:02,350 --> 03:05:03,430
Tell me that.

2389
03:05:03,430 --> 03:05:07,521
Or are you worried about your soul?'

2390
03:05:07,521 --> 03:05:11,700
'Curse my soul, Joss; it's common sense I'm
thinking of.

2391
03:05:11,700 --> 03:05:17,521
This part of the country is dangerous, and
I'll leave while I can.

2392
03:05:17,521 --> 03:05:20,521
I've stayed by you, haven't I?

2393
03:05:20,521 --> 03:05:25,910
I've come out here today, risking death, to
give you warning.

2394
03:05:25,910 --> 03:05:32,360
I'm not saying anything against you, Joss,
but it was your stupidity that brought us

2395
03:05:32,360 --> 03:05:33,860
to this, wasn't it?

2396
03:05:33,860 --> 03:05:39,521
You made us crazy like yourself, and led us
to the coast on an adventure that none of

2397
03:05:39,521 --> 03:05:41,440
us had planned.

2398
03:05:41,440 --> 03:05:45,050
We took a chance in a million - and succeeded.

2399
03:05:45,050 --> 03:05:47,230
Too well.

2400
03:05:47,230 --> 03:05:53,760
We became stupid with excitement, left a hundred
tracks scattered on the sand.

2401
03:05:53,760 --> 03:05:55,530
And whose fault was it?

2402
03:05:55,530 --> 03:05:57,080
Why, yours, I say!'

2403
03:05:57,080 --> 03:06:04,891
He banged the table, his yellow face pushed
close to the landlord's.

2404
03:06:04,891 --> 03:06:10,690
Joss Merlyn considered him for a moment, and
when he spoke, his voice was dangerous and

2405
03:06:10,690 --> 03:06:12,440
low.

2406
03:06:12,440 --> 03:06:17,710
'So you blame me, do you, Harry?

2407
03:06:17,710 --> 03:06:22,710
You're like the rest of your kind when the
luck of the game turns against you.

2408
03:06:22,710 --> 03:06:29,870
Run, then, if you like; run to the riverbank
like a beaten dog.

2409
03:06:29,870 --> 03:06:33,910
I'll fight the world alone!'

2410
03:06:33,910 --> 03:06:36,440
The pedlar forced a laugh.

2411
03:06:36,440 --> 03:06:41,500
'We can talk, can't we, without cutting each
other's throats?

2412
03:06:41,500 --> 03:06:47,110
I've not gone against you; I'm on your side
still.

2413
03:06:47,110 --> 03:06:49,510
We were all crazy that night, I know that.

2414
03:06:49,510 --> 03:06:55,140
Let's leave it alone, then; what's done is
done.

2415
03:06:55,140 --> 03:06:59,860
Our men are scattered, and we needn't worry
about them.

2416
03:06:59,860 --> 03:07:03,171
They'll be too frightened to show their heads.

2417
03:07:03,171 --> 03:07:06,410
That leaves you and me, Joss.

2418
03:07:06,410 --> 03:07:13,310
We've been in this business, the pair of us,
deeper than most, and the more we help each

2419
03:07:13,310 --> 03:07:17,221
other, the better it'll be for us both.

2420
03:07:17,221 --> 03:07:25,180
Now then, that's why I'm here, to talk and
see what we ought to do.'

2421
03:07:25,180 --> 03:07:27,110
The landlord watched him calmly.

2422
03:07:27,110 --> 03:07:34,490
'Just what are you aiming at, Harry?' he said,
filling his pipe.

2423
03:07:34,490 --> 03:07:37,900
'I'm not aiming at anything.

2424
03:07:37,900 --> 03:07:42,601
I want to make things easier for all of us.

2425
03:07:42,601 --> 03:07:46,280
We've got to go, unless we want to hang.

2426
03:07:46,280 --> 03:07:53,850
But it's like this, Joss; I don't see the
fun of going empty-handed.

2427
03:07:53,850 --> 03:07:58,000
There are a lot of things we put in the store
room two days ago.

2428
03:07:58,000 --> 03:07:59,771
That's right, isn't it?

2429
03:07:59,771 --> 03:08:04,271
It belongs to all of us who worked for it
on that night.

2430
03:08:04,271 --> 03:08:11,650
But there's none of them left to claim it
except you and me.

2431
03:08:11,650 --> 03:08:17,160
I'm not saying that there's much of value
there, but I don't see why some of it shouldn't

2432
03:08:17,160 --> 03:08:22,970
help us out of the area, do you?'

2433
03:08:22,970 --> 03:08:27,790
The landlord blew a cloud of smoke into his
face.

2434
03:08:27,790 --> 03:08:34,670
'So you didn't come back to Jamaica Inn because
of my sweet smile alone, then?

2435
03:08:34,670 --> 03:08:41,670
I was thinking you were fond of me, and wanted
to hold my hand.'

2436
03:08:41,670 --> 03:08:45,490
The pedlar smiled, and changed his position
on his chair.

2437
03:08:45,490 --> 03:08:49,181
'All right - we're friends, aren't we?

2438
03:08:49,181 --> 03:08:52,051
There's no harm in plain speaking.

2439
03:08:52,051 --> 03:08:56,812
The things are here, and it'll take two men
to move it.

2440
03:08:56,812 --> 03:08:59,930
The women can't do it.

2441
03:08:59,930 --> 03:09:04,490
What's against you and me making a deal?'

2442
03:09:04,490 --> 03:09:09,011
The landlord thoughtfully smoked his pipe.

2443
03:09:09,011 --> 03:09:14,290
'And supposing there's nothing here, after
all?

2444
03:09:14,290 --> 03:09:18,280
Supposing I've got rid of it already?

2445
03:09:18,280 --> 03:09:25,271
I've been sitting here for two days, you know,
and the coaches pass my door.

2446
03:09:25,271 --> 03:09:29,440
What then, Harry boy?'

2447
03:09:29,440 --> 03:09:32,631
The smile went from the face of the pedlar.

2448
03:09:32,631 --> 03:09:33,970
'What's the joke?

2449
03:09:33,970 --> 03:09:39,100
Do you play a double game up here at Jamaica
Inn?

2450
03:09:39,100 --> 03:09:42,140
You'll find it hasn't paid you, if you have.

2451
03:09:42,140 --> 03:09:49,570
You've been clever at this trade, month in,
month out; too clever, some of us thought,

2452
03:09:49,570 --> 03:09:55,480
for the small profit we made out of it - we,
who took most of the risks.

2453
03:09:55,480 --> 03:09:59,570
And we didn't ask you how you did it.

2454
03:09:59,570 --> 03:10:07,020
Listen here, Joss Merlyn; do you take your
orders from someone above you?'

2455
03:10:07,020 --> 03:10:10,120
The landlord was on him like a flash.

2456
03:10:10,120 --> 03:10:15,270
He hit him on the chin, and the man went over
backwards onto his head.

2457
03:10:15,270 --> 03:10:21,300
He rolled over onto his knees, but the landlord
towered above him, his gun pointing at his

2458
03:10:21,300 --> 03:10:22,300
throat.

2459
03:10:22,300 --> 03:10:33,471
'Move, and you're a dead man,' he said softly,
as Harry looked up at his attacker, his little

2460
03:10:33,471 --> 03:10:35,190
eyes half closed.

2461
03:10:35,190 --> 03:10:44,970
'Now we can talk, you and I.' He leant once
more against the table, while the pedlar continued

2462
03:10:44,970 --> 03:10:47,050
to kneel on the floor.

2463
03:10:47,050 --> 03:10:55,520
'You didn't come here tonight to warn me;
you came to see what you could get out of

2464
03:10:55,520 --> 03:10:56,950
the wreck.

2465
03:10:56,950 --> 03:11:01,390
You didn't expect to find me here, did you?

2466
03:11:01,390 --> 03:11:09,940
You thought it would be Patience here, or
Mary; and you would frighten them easily,

2467
03:11:09,940 --> 03:11:17,540
wouldn't you, and reach for my gun where it
hangs on the wall, as you've often seen?

2468
03:11:17,540 --> 03:11:24,600
You little rat, Harry, do you think I didn't
see it in your eyes when I threw back the

2469
03:11:24,600 --> 03:11:28,090
shutters and saw your face at the window?

2470
03:11:28,090 --> 03:11:31,730
Do you think I didn't see your surprise?

2471
03:11:31,730 --> 03:11:34,010
Very well, then.

2472
03:11:34,010 --> 03:11:38,510
We'll make a deal, as you suggest.

2473
03:11:38,510 --> 03:11:46,520
I've changed my mind, my loving friend, and
with your help we'll take the road.

2474
03:11:46,520 --> 03:11:52,340
There are things in this place worth taking,
and I can't load them alone.

2475
03:11:52,340 --> 03:11:58,490
Tomorrow is Sunday, and a day of rest.

2476
03:11:58,490 --> 03:12:06,180
Not even the wrecking of 50 ships will drag
the people around here from their knees.

2477
03:12:06,180 --> 03:12:12,540
There'll be prayers offered for poor sailors
who suffer because of the devil's work, but

2478
03:12:12,540 --> 03:12:18,630
they'll not go looking for the devil on a
Sunday.

2479
03:12:18,630 --> 03:12:25,970
'Twenty-four hours we have, Harry my boy,
and tomorrow night when you've broken your

2480
03:12:25,970 --> 03:12:36,110
back loading my property into the farm wagon
and kissed me goodbye - why, then you can

2481
03:12:36,110 --> 03:12:43,590
go down on your knees and thank Joss Merlyn
for letting you go free with your life.'

2482
03:12:43,590 --> 03:12:50,350
He raised his gun again, bringing it close
to the man's throat.

2483
03:12:50,350 --> 03:12:54,020
The pedlar cried out, showing the whites of
his eyes.

2484
03:12:54,020 --> 03:12:56,660
The landlord laughed.

2485
03:12:56,660 --> 03:13:05,600
'Come on,' he said, 'do you think I'm going
to play with you all night?

2486
03:13:05,600 --> 03:13:11,021
Open the kitchen door, and turn to the right,
and walk down the passage until I tell you

2487
03:13:11,021 --> 03:13:12,970
to stop.

2488
03:13:12,970 --> 03:13:18,850
Your hands have been waiting to explore the
goods brought from the shore, haven't they,

2489
03:13:18,850 --> 03:13:19,850
Harry?

2490
03:13:19,850 --> 03:13:24,190
You shall spend the night in the store room
among them all.'

2491
03:13:24,190 --> 03:13:31,681
Pressing his gun into the pedlar's back, he
pushed him out of the kitchen and down the

2492
03:13:31,681 --> 03:13:33,870
dark passage to the store.

2493
03:13:33,870 --> 03:13:39,600
The door had been mended with new wood and
was stronger than before.

2494
03:13:39,600 --> 03:13:46,681
After he had turned the key on his friend,
the landlord returned to the kitchen.

2495
03:13:46,681 --> 03:13:54,190
'I thought Harry would turn soon,' he said.

2496
03:13:54,190 --> 03:13:58,810
'I've seen it coming in his eyes for weeks.

2497
03:13:58,810 --> 03:14:04,380
He'll fight on the winning side, but he'll
turn against you when your luck changes.

2498
03:14:04,380 --> 03:14:07,030
He's jealous of me.

2499
03:14:07,030 --> 03:14:10,340
They're all jealous of me.

2500
03:14:10,340 --> 03:14:15,890
They knew I had brains, and they hated me
for it.

2501
03:14:15,890 --> 03:14:18,590
You'd better get your supper and go to bed.

2502
03:14:18,590 --> 03:14:28,450
You've a long journey to make tomorrow night,
and I warn you here and now it won't be an

2503
03:14:28,450 --> 03:14:31,370
easy one.'

2504
03:14:31,370 --> 03:14:33,100
Mary looked at him across the table.

2505
03:14:33,100 --> 03:14:39,760
Tired as she was, because all that she had
seen and done weighed heavily on her, her

2506
03:14:39,760 --> 03:14:42,400
mind was full of plans.

2507
03:14:42,400 --> 03:14:48,660
Some time, somehow, before tomorrow night,
she must go to Altarnun.

2508
03:14:48,660 --> 03:14:51,750
Once there, her responsibility was over.

2509
03:14:51,750 --> 03:14:55,051
Action would be taken by others.

2510
03:14:55,051 --> 03:15:01,270
It would be hard for Aunt Patience, hard for
herself at first, perhaps, but at least justice

2511
03:15:01,270 --> 03:15:02,740
would win.

2512
03:15:02,740 --> 03:15:07,210
It would be easy enough to clear her own name,
and her aunt's.

2513
03:15:07,210 --> 03:15:13,330
The thought of her uncle standing as he would
with his hands tied behind him, powerless

2514
03:15:13,330 --> 03:15:19,561
for the first time and forever, was something
that gave her great pleasure.

2515
03:15:19,561 --> 03:15:21,930
She dragged her eyes away from him.

2516
03:15:21,930 --> 03:15:26,250
'I'll have no supper tonight,' she said.

2517
03:15:26,250 --> 03:15:32,270
He crossed into the hall as she climbed the
stairs, and he followed her to the room over

2518
03:15:32,270 --> 03:15:33,480
the front door.

2519
03:15:33,480 --> 03:15:41,570
'Give me your key,' he said, and she handed
it to him without a word.

2520
03:15:41,570 --> 03:15:46,970
He stayed for a moment, looking down at her,
and then he bent low and laid his fingers

2521
03:15:46,970 --> 03:15:48,280
on her mouth.

2522
03:15:48,280 --> 03:15:52,140
'I like you, Mary.

2523
03:15:52,140 --> 03:15:59,150
You've got spirit still, and courage, in spite
of all the rough treatment I've given you.

2524
03:15:59,150 --> 03:16:02,590
I've seen it in your eyes tonight.

2525
03:16:02,590 --> 03:16:11,830
If I'd been a younger man I'd have fallen
in love with you - and won you too, and ridden

2526
03:16:11,830 --> 03:16:12,830
away with you.

2527
03:16:12,830 --> 03:16:16,550
You know that, don't you?'

2528
03:16:16,550 --> 03:16:20,150
He lowered his voice to a whisper.

2529
03:16:20,150 --> 03:16:24,200
'There's danger for me ahead.

2530
03:16:24,200 --> 03:16:26,240
Never mind the law.

2531
03:16:26,240 --> 03:16:31,140
The whole of Cornwall can come running at
my heels and I shall not care.

2532
03:16:31,140 --> 03:16:40,760
It's other things I have to watch for - footsteps,
Mary, that come in the night and go again,

2533
03:16:40,760 --> 03:16:44,180
and a hand that is waiting to strike me down.

2534
03:16:44,180 --> 03:16:53,090
We'll put the river between us and Jamaica
Inn,' he said; and then he smiled, the curve

2535
03:16:53,090 --> 03:16:59,170
of his mouth painfully familiar to her like
something from her past.

2536
03:16:59,170 --> 03:17:03,431
He shut the door on her, and turned the key.

2537
03:17:03,431 --> 03:17:07,210
She went then to her bed, and sat on it.

2538
03:17:07,210 --> 03:17:15,350
And she began to cry, softly and secretly,
the tears tasting bitter as they fell on her

2539
03:17:15,350 --> 03:17:18,250
hand.

2540
03:17:18,250 --> 03:17:23,160
CHAPTER TWELVE
To Altarnun

2541
03:17:23,160 --> 03:17:29,000
She had fallen asleep where she lay, without
undressing, and her first conscious thought

2542
03:17:29,000 --> 03:17:32,200
was that the storm had returned.

2543
03:17:32,200 --> 03:17:38,100
She was awake immediately, and she waited
for the sound that had woken her to come again.

2544
03:17:38,100 --> 03:17:43,780
It came in a moment, a handful of earth thrown
against the window from the yard outside.

2545
03:17:43,780 --> 03:17:48,750
It was Jem Merlyn standing below in the yard.

2546
03:17:48,750 --> 03:17:55,771
He whispered up to her, 'Come down to the
door here, and open it for me.'

2547
03:17:55,771 --> 03:17:56,870
She shook her head.

2548
03:17:56,870 --> 03:18:00,450
'I can't - I'm locked in my room.'

2549
03:18:00,450 --> 03:18:07,650
He looked back at her, confused, and examined
the house as if it might offer some solution

2550
03:18:07,650 --> 03:18:09,521
of its own.

2551
03:18:09,521 --> 03:18:14,390
He ran his hand along the wall, feeling for
old nails that might once have been used for

2552
03:18:14,390 --> 03:18:19,120
training climbing plants, and would now give
him a foothold of a sort.

2553
03:18:19,120 --> 03:18:24,820
Swinging himself up to the low roof over the
front door, he was able to pull himself up

2554
03:18:24,820 --> 03:18:26,990
to the level of her window.

2555
03:18:26,990 --> 03:18:31,970
'I shall have to talk to you here,' he said.

2556
03:18:31,970 --> 03:18:35,140
'Come closer where I can see you.'

2557
03:18:35,140 --> 03:18:40,190
She knelt on the floor of her room, her face
at the window, and they looked at each other

2558
03:18:40,190 --> 03:18:42,660
without speaking.

2559
03:18:42,660 --> 03:18:47,710
He looked tired, and his eyes were hollow
like those of one who has not slept.

2560
03:18:47,710 --> 03:18:54,190
There were lines around his mouth that she
had not noticed before, and he did not smile.

2561
03:18:54,190 --> 03:18:57,590
'I'm sorry,' he said at last.

2562
03:18:57,590 --> 03:19:02,250
'I left you alone without excuse at Launceston
on Christmas Eve.

2563
03:19:02,250 --> 03:19:04,720
You can forgive me or not.

2564
03:19:04,720 --> 03:19:10,210
But the reason for it - that I can't give
you.

2565
03:19:10,210 --> 03:19:11,760
I'm sorry.'

2566
03:19:11,760 --> 03:19:14,240
She was hurt by his manner.

2567
03:19:14,240 --> 03:19:18,860
His coldness upset her, and she hoped that
he could not see the disappointment in her

2568
03:19:18,860 --> 03:19:20,620
face.

2569
03:19:20,620 --> 03:19:23,540
He did not even ask how she had returned that
night.

2570
03:19:23,540 --> 03:19:28,200
'Why are you locked in your room?'

2571
03:19:28,200 --> 03:19:30,830
Her voice was flat and dull when she replied.

2572
03:19:30,830 --> 03:19:36,780
'My uncle fears that I may wander in the passage
and discover his secrets.'

2573
03:19:36,780 --> 03:19:40,360
'Where is he?'

2574
03:19:40,360 --> 03:19:42,760
'He's going to spend the night in the kitchen.

2575
03:19:42,760 --> 03:19:50,070
He's afraid of something, or someone; the
windows and doors are barred, and he has his

2576
03:19:50,070 --> 03:19:51,950
gun.'

2577
03:19:51,950 --> 03:19:53,310
Jem laughed bitterly.

2578
03:19:53,310 --> 03:19:56,650
'I don't doubt he's afraid.

2579
03:19:56,650 --> 03:20:00,900
He'll be even more frightened before many
hours have passed, I can tell you that.

2580
03:20:00,900 --> 03:20:07,640
I came here to see him, but if he is sitting
there with a gun across his knee I shall come

2581
03:20:07,640 --> 03:20:12,380
again tomorrow, when the shadows have gone.'

2582
03:20:12,380 --> 03:20:13,761
'Tomorrow may be too late.'

2583
03:20:13,761 --> 03:20:16,061
'What do you mean?'

2584
03:20:16,061 --> 03:20:19,290
'He intends to leave Jamaica Inn tonight.'

2585
03:20:19,290 --> 03:20:22,771
'Are you telling me the truth?'

2586
03:20:22,771 --> 03:20:28,250
'Why should I lie to you now?'

2587
03:20:28,250 --> 03:20:29,350
Jem was silent.

2588
03:20:29,350 --> 03:20:33,760
The news had clearly come as a surprise to
him.

2589
03:20:33,760 --> 03:20:38,110
She was thrown back now on her old suspicion
of him.

2590
03:20:38,110 --> 03:20:44,600
He was the visitor expected by her uncle,
and therefore hated by him and feared.

2591
03:20:44,600 --> 03:20:51,051
The face of the pedlar returned to her, and
his words, that had stung Joss Merlyn to anger:

2592
03:20:51,051 --> 03:20:58,410
'Listen here, Joss Merlyn, do you take your
orders from someone above you?'

2593
03:20:58,410 --> 03:21:06,040
The man whose brains made use of the landlord's
strength, the man who had hidden in the empty

2594
03:21:06,040 --> 03:21:07,040
room...

2595
03:21:07,040 --> 03:21:14,040
Leaning forward suddenly, he looked into her
face and touched the long cut that ran from

2596
03:21:14,040 --> 03:21:16,610
her forehead to her chin.

2597
03:21:16,610 --> 03:21:22,390
'Who did these?' he said, turning now to the
mark on her cheek.

2598
03:21:22,390 --> 03:21:26,590
She paused a moment, and then answered him.

2599
03:21:26,590 --> 03:21:28,960
'I got them on Christmas Eve.'

2600
03:21:28,960 --> 03:21:35,461
The look in his eye told her that he understood,
and had knowledge of the evening, and because

2601
03:21:35,461 --> 03:21:38,330
of it was here now at Jamaica Inn.

2602
03:21:38,330 --> 03:21:42,540
'You were with them, on the shore?' he whispered.

2603
03:21:42,540 --> 03:21:45,830
'Why did you go with them?'

2604
03:21:45,830 --> 03:21:48,850
'They were crazy with drink.

2605
03:21:48,850 --> 03:21:50,610
I don't think they knew what they were doing.

2606
03:21:50,610 --> 03:21:53,860
I could no more have stood against them than
a child.

2607
03:21:53,860 --> 03:21:59,010
There were ten of them or more, and my uncle...
he led them.

2608
03:21:59,010 --> 03:22:02,110
He and the pedlar.

2609
03:22:02,110 --> 03:22:05,800
If you know about it, why do you ask me?

2610
03:22:05,800 --> 03:22:08,020
Don't make me remember.

2611
03:22:08,020 --> 03:22:10,700
I don't want to remember.'

2612
03:22:10,700 --> 03:22:13,800
'How much did they hurt you?'

2613
03:22:13,800 --> 03:22:16,490
'You can see for yourself.

2614
03:22:16,490 --> 03:22:20,520
I tried to escape and I hurt my side.

2615
03:22:20,520 --> 03:22:23,060
They caught me again, of course.

2616
03:22:23,060 --> 03:22:28,970
They tied my hands and feet, and tied a cloth
over my mouth so that I could not cry out.

2617
03:22:28,970 --> 03:22:35,440
I saw the ship come through the darkness,
and I could do nothing - alone there in the

2618
03:22:35,440 --> 03:22:36,650
wind and the rain.

2619
03:22:36,650 --> 03:22:40,470
I had to watch them die.'

2620
03:22:40,470 --> 03:22:46,210
She stopped, her voice trembling, her face
in her hands.

2621
03:22:46,210 --> 03:22:52,880
He made no move towards her; and she felt
him far from her, wrapped in secrecy.

2622
03:22:52,880 --> 03:22:55,420
She felt lonelier than ever.

2623
03:22:55,420 --> 03:23:04,960
'Was it my brother who hurt you most?' he
said after a while.

2624
03:23:04,960 --> 03:23:08,350
It was too late; it did not matter now.

2625
03:23:08,350 --> 03:23:11,610
'I've told you he was very drunk.

2626
03:23:11,610 --> 03:23:15,271
You know, better than I perhaps, what he can
do 'then.'

2627
03:23:15,271 --> 03:23:19,140
'Yes, I know.'

2628
03:23:19,140 --> 03:23:23,230
He paused for a moment, and then he took her
hand.

2629
03:23:23,230 --> 03:23:25,351
'He shall die for this.'

2630
03:23:25,351 --> 03:23:29,550
'His death will not bring back the men he
has killed.'

2631
03:23:29,550 --> 03:23:32,260
'I'm not thinking of them now.'

2632
03:23:32,260 --> 03:23:37,030
'If you're thinking of me, don't waste your
sympathy.

2633
03:23:37,030 --> 03:23:39,811
I can deal with it in my own way.

2634
03:23:39,811 --> 03:23:44,440
I've learnt one thing - to depend on myself.'

2635
03:23:44,440 --> 03:23:47,680
'What do you intend to do?'

2636
03:23:47,680 --> 03:23:52,630
'He expects me to go with him, and Aunt Patience
as well.

2637
03:23:52,630 --> 03:23:57,721
If I asked you to do something, how would
you answer me?'

2638
03:23:57,721 --> 03:24:04,220
He smiled then, for the first time, as he
had done in Launceston, and her heart warmed,

2639
03:24:04,220 --> 03:24:06,650
encouraged at the change.

2640
03:24:06,650 --> 03:24:10,180
'How can I tell?' he said.

2641
03:24:10,180 --> 03:24:13,521
'I want you to go away from here.'

2642
03:24:13,521 --> 03:24:15,890
'I'm going now.'

2643
03:24:15,890 --> 03:24:21,700
'No, I mean away from the moors - away from
Jamaica Inn.

2644
03:24:21,700 --> 03:24:25,220
I want you to tell me you won't return here.

2645
03:24:25,220 --> 03:24:30,230
I can stand up against your brother; I'm in
no danger from him now.

2646
03:24:30,230 --> 03:24:32,700
I don't want you to come here tomorrow.

2647
03:24:32,700 --> 03:24:34,890
Please promise me you'll go away.'

2648
03:24:34,890 --> 03:24:38,551
'What have you got in mind?'

2649
03:24:38,551 --> 03:24:42,750
'Something which does not concern you, but
might bring you into danger.

2650
03:24:42,750 --> 03:24:45,030
I can't say any more.

2651
03:24:45,030 --> 03:24:47,260
I would rather you trusted me.'

2652
03:24:47,260 --> 03:24:49,120
'Trust you?

2653
03:24:49,120 --> 03:24:51,060
Of course, I trust you.

2654
03:24:51,060 --> 03:24:54,971
It's you who won't trust me, you little fool.'

2655
03:24:54,971 --> 03:25:01,610
He laughed silently, and bent down to her,
putting his arms round her, and kissed her

2656
03:25:01,610 --> 03:25:06,330
then as he had kissed her in Launceston, but
with anger.

2657
03:25:06,330 --> 03:25:10,650
'Play your own game by yourself, then, and
leave me to play mine.

2658
03:25:10,650 --> 03:25:17,790
If you must be a boy, I can't stop you, but
keep that face, which I have kissed and shall

2659
03:25:17,790 --> 03:25:20,561
kiss again, away from danger.

2660
03:25:20,561 --> 03:25:23,530
You don't want to kill yourself, do you?

2661
03:25:23,530 --> 03:25:29,320
I have to leave you now; it will be light
in less than an hour.

2662
03:25:29,320 --> 03:25:31,380
And if both our plans go wrong, what then?

2663
03:25:31,380 --> 03:25:34,590
Would you mind if you never saw me again?

2664
03:25:34,590 --> 03:25:38,720
No, of course you wouldn't care.

2665
03:25:38,720 --> 03:25:46,660
You'll marry a farmer one day, or a small
tradesman, and live quietly among your neighbours.

2666
03:25:46,660 --> 03:25:51,400
Don't tell them you once lived at Jamaica
Inn, or had a horse thief make love to you.

2667
03:25:51,400 --> 03:25:54,180
They'd shut their doors against you.

2668
03:25:54,180 --> 03:25:58,510
Goodbye - and good luck to you.'

2669
03:25:58,510 --> 03:26:01,210
He lowered himself to the ground.

2670
03:26:01,210 --> 03:26:06,530
She watched him from the window, waving to
him, but he had turned and gone without looking

2671
03:26:06,530 --> 03:26:11,360
back at her, crossing the yard like a shadow.

2672
03:26:11,360 --> 03:26:16,360
Morning would soon be here; she would not
sleep again.

2673
03:26:16,360 --> 03:26:21,800
She sat on her bed, waiting for her door to
be unlocked; and she made her plans for the

2674
03:26:21,800 --> 03:26:24,060
evening to come.

2675
03:26:24,060 --> 03:26:28,190
She must act as if she were prepared to make
the planned journey with the landlord and

2676
03:26:28,190 --> 03:26:29,190
Aunt Patience.

2677
03:26:29,190 --> 03:26:36,011
Later, she would make some excuse - a desire
to rest in her room before the journey, perhaps

2678
03:26:36,011 --> 03:26:41,230
- and then would come the most dangerous moment
of her day.

2679
03:26:41,230 --> 03:26:47,070
She would have to leave Jamaica Inn secretly
and run to Altarnun.

2680
03:26:47,070 --> 03:26:52,930
Francis Davey would understand; time would
be against them, and he would have to act

2681
03:26:52,930 --> 03:26:54,850
quickly.

2682
03:26:54,850 --> 03:27:00,610
She would then return to the inn, and hope
that her absence had remained unnoticed.

2683
03:27:00,610 --> 03:27:02,480
That was the risk.

2684
03:27:02,480 --> 03:27:09,770
If the landlord went to her room and found
her gone, her life would be worth nothing.

2685
03:27:09,770 --> 03:27:11,841
She must be prepared for that.

2686
03:27:11,841 --> 03:27:14,670
No excuse would save her then.

2687
03:27:14,670 --> 03:27:20,780
But if he believed her to be sleeping, the
game would continue.

2688
03:27:20,780 --> 03:27:26,051
They would make preparations for the journey;
they might even climb into the wagon and come

2689
03:27:26,051 --> 03:27:28,030
out on the road.

2690
03:27:28,030 --> 03:27:31,190
After that, her responsibility would end.

2691
03:27:31,190 --> 03:27:37,021
Whatever happened next would be in the hands
of the Vicar of Altarnun.

2692
03:27:37,021 --> 03:27:49,680
Beyond this she could not think, nor had she
any great desire to look ahead.

2693
03:27:49,680 --> 03:27:53,771
When she had helped them clear the midday
meal away and had persuaded her aunt to pack

2694
03:27:53,771 --> 03:27:59,440
a basket of food for the journey, she turned
to her uncle and spoke to him.

2695
03:27:59,440 --> 03:28:05,380
'If we are to travel tonight, would it not
be better if Aunt Patience and I rested now

2696
03:28:05,380 --> 03:28:09,690
during the afternoon, so we could start out
fresh on the journey?

2697
03:28:09,690 --> 03:28:14,410
There will be no sleep for any of us tonight.'

2698
03:28:14,410 --> 03:28:16,230
'You may rest if you like.

2699
03:28:16,230 --> 03:28:19,000
There'll be work for both of you later.

2700
03:28:19,000 --> 03:28:23,930
You're right when you say there will be no
sleep for you tonight.

2701
03:28:23,930 --> 03:28:30,350
Go, then; I shall be glad to get rid of you
for a time.'

2702
03:28:30,350 --> 03:28:35,220
Mary entered her own little room and closed
the door, turning the key.

2703
03:28:35,220 --> 03:28:38,750
Her heart beat fast at the thought of adventure.

2704
03:28:38,750 --> 03:28:45,980
It was nearly 4 miles to Altarnun by road,
but she could walk the distance in an hour.

2705
03:28:45,980 --> 03:28:51,530
If she left Jamaica Inn at four o'clock, when
the light was failing, she would be back again

2706
03:28:51,530 --> 03:28:58,470
soon after six; and the landlord would be
unlikely to come to wake her up before seven.

2707
03:28:58,470 --> 03:29:03,540
She had three hours, then, in which to play
her part.

2708
03:29:03,540 --> 03:29:08,420
She would climb out of the window and drop
to the ground, as Jem had done.

2709
03:29:08,420 --> 03:29:14,021
She sat by the window, looking out on the
empty yard and the high road where no one

2710
03:29:14,021 --> 03:29:20,810
ever passed, waiting for the clock in the
hall to strike four.

2711
03:29:20,810 --> 03:29:24,640
When it struck at last, the sound rang out
in the silence.

2712
03:29:24,640 --> 03:29:31,150
Every second was important to her now, and
she must waste no time in going.

2713
03:29:31,150 --> 03:29:33,030
She climbed through the window.

2714
03:29:33,030 --> 03:29:36,460
The jump was nothing, as she had thought.

2715
03:29:36,460 --> 03:29:38,160
She looked up at Jamaica Inn.

2716
03:29:38,160 --> 03:29:45,690
It looked evil in the half-darkness, the windows
barred; she thought of the terrible things

2717
03:29:45,690 --> 03:29:52,440
the house had witnessed, the secrets now shut
up behind its walls; and she turned away from

2718
03:29:52,440 --> 03:29:58,471
it as from a house of the dead, and went out
on the road.

2719
03:29:58,471 --> 03:30:00,811
Darkness fell as she walked.

2720
03:30:00,811 --> 03:30:06,311
She came at last to where the roads divided,
and she turned to her left, down the steep

2721
03:30:06,311 --> 03:30:08,480
hill to Altarnun.

2722
03:30:08,480 --> 03:30:11,190
The vicar's house was silent.

2723
03:30:11,190 --> 03:30:14,490
There were no lights there.

2724
03:30:14,490 --> 03:30:17,380
She turned back towards the church.

2725
03:30:17,380 --> 03:30:20,370
Francis Davey would be there, of course!

2726
03:30:20,370 --> 03:30:22,851
It was Sunday.

2727
03:30:22,851 --> 03:30:26,070
She stopped for a moment, uncertain what to
do.

2728
03:30:26,070 --> 03:30:32,710
Then the gate opened and a woman came out
into the road, carrying flowers.

2729
03:30:32,710 --> 03:30:38,061
She looked hard at Mary, knowing her to be
a stranger, and would have passed her by with

2730
03:30:38,061 --> 03:30:41,101
a 'good night', but Mary turned.

2731
03:30:41,101 --> 03:30:43,750
'Forgive me,' she said.

2732
03:30:43,750 --> 03:30:47,230
'I see you have come from the church.

2733
03:30:47,230 --> 03:30:50,360
Can you tell me if Mr Davey is there?'

2734
03:30:50,360 --> 03:30:59,730
'No, he is not,' said the woman; and then,
after a moment, 'Did you want to see him?'

2735
03:30:59,730 --> 03:31:04,771
'Very urgently,' said Mary 'Can you help me?'

2736
03:31:04,771 --> 03:31:10,760
The woman looked at her strangely, and then
she shook her head firmly

2737
03:31:10,760 --> 03:31:13,580
'I'm sorry,' she said.

2738
03:31:13,580 --> 03:31:20,150
'The vicar's away He went to hold a service
in another village, many miles from here.

2739
03:31:20,150 --> 03:31:26,021
He is not expected back in Altarnun tonight.'

2740
03:31:26,021 --> 03:31:32,230
CHAPTER THIRTEEN
Murder at Jamaica Inn

2741
03:31:32,230 --> 03:31:35,140
At first, Mary looked at the woman in disbelief.

2742
03:31:35,140 --> 03:31:36,851
'But that's impossible.

2743
03:31:36,851 --> 03:31:38,561
Surely you're mistaken?'

2744
03:31:38,561 --> 03:31:40,840
'The vicar has left.

2745
03:31:40,840 --> 03:31:43,690
He rode away after dinner.

2746
03:31:43,690 --> 03:31:49,390
I ought to know: I am his housekeeper.'

2747
03:31:49,390 --> 03:31:53,400
Mary wondered hopelessly what she could do
now.

2748
03:31:53,400 --> 03:31:59,771
To come to Altarnun and then return without
help to Jamaica Inn was impossible.

2749
03:31:59,771 --> 03:32:05,931
She could not place confidence in the village
people, nor would they believe her story.

2750
03:32:05,931 --> 03:32:11,950
She must find someone with power - someone
who knew something of Joss Merlyn and Jamaica

2751
03:32:11,950 --> 03:32:12,950
Inn.

2752
03:32:12,950 --> 03:32:16,880
'Who is the nearest magistrate?'

2753
03:32:16,880 --> 03:32:18,570
she said at last.

2754
03:32:18,570 --> 03:32:21,330
The woman considered the question.

2755
03:32:21,330 --> 03:32:28,900
'Well, the nearest would be Mr Bassat over
at North Hill, and that must be over 4 miles

2756
03:32:28,900 --> 03:32:32,370
from here - perhaps more, perhaps less.

2757
03:32:32,370 --> 03:32:36,271
I can't say for certain, for I've never been
there.

2758
03:32:36,271 --> 03:32:40,400
You surely don't intend to walk out there
tonight?'

2759
03:32:40,400 --> 03:32:42,360
'I must.

2760
03:32:42,360 --> 03:32:44,000
There is nothing else for me to do.

2761
03:32:44,000 --> 03:32:46,650
I must waste no time, either.

2762
03:32:46,650 --> 03:32:52,970
I'm in great trouble now, and only your vicar
or a magistrate can help me.'

2763
03:32:52,970 --> 03:32:57,890
'You'd better stay here and wait for the vicar,
if you can.'

2764
03:32:57,890 --> 03:33:04,931
'That's impossible,' said Mary, 'but when
he does return, could you tell him perhaps

2765
03:33:04,931 --> 03:33:05,931
that...

2766
03:33:05,931 --> 03:33:11,240
But wait; if you have pen and paper, I'll
write him a note of explanation.

2767
03:33:11,240 --> 03:33:13,170
That would be better still.'

2768
03:33:13,170 --> 03:33:17,680
'Come into my house here, and you may write
what you like.

2769
03:33:17,680 --> 03:33:22,020
I can take the note to his house.'

2770
03:33:22,020 --> 03:33:24,890
Mary followed the woman to her house.

2771
03:33:24,890 --> 03:33:27,700
Time was slipping away fast.

2772
03:33:27,700 --> 03:33:32,760
Her uncle would take warning from the fact
that she had run away, and leave the inn before

2773
03:33:32,760 --> 03:33:34,820
the intended time.

2774
03:33:34,820 --> 03:33:39,280
And then her effort would have been for nothing.

2775
03:33:39,280 --> 03:33:42,370
Mary wrote with the speed of hopelessness.

2776
03:33:42,370 --> 03:33:47,310
Then she folded the note and gave it to the
woman by her side.

2777
03:33:47,310 --> 03:33:51,980
So she set out on a walk of 4 miles or more
to North Hill.

2778
03:33:51,980 --> 03:33:59,650
She had placed such trust in Francis Davey
that it was hard to realize that he had failed

2779
03:33:59,650 --> 03:34:00,650
her.

2780
03:34:00,650 --> 03:34:04,170
He had not known, of course, that she needed
him.

2781
03:34:04,170 --> 03:34:08,680
She was anxious about Aunt Patience, and the
thought of her setting out on the journey

2782
03:34:08,680 --> 03:34:15,750
like a trembling dog tied to its master made
Mary run along the empty road.

2783
03:34:15,750 --> 03:34:20,540
She came at last to big gates and the entrance
to a driveway.

2784
03:34:20,540 --> 03:34:27,090
This must be North Hill, and this house must
belong to the magistrate.

2785
03:34:27,090 --> 03:34:31,190
In the distance, a church clock struck seven.

2786
03:34:31,190 --> 03:34:35,860
She had been away from Jamaica Inn for about
three hours already.

2787
03:34:35,860 --> 03:34:39,771
Her fear returned as she came to the house.

2788
03:34:39,771 --> 03:34:43,670
She swung the great bell and waited.

2789
03:34:43,670 --> 03:34:49,490
After some time she heard footsteps inside,
and the door was opened by a servant.

2790
03:34:49,490 --> 03:34:56,280
'I have come to see Mr Bassat on very urgent
business,' she told him.

2791
03:34:56,280 --> 03:35:01,791
'The matter is of the greatest importance,
or I would not come at such an hour, and on

2792
03:35:01,791 --> 03:35:03,830
a Sunday night.'

2793
03:35:03,830 --> 03:35:09,420
'Mr Bassat left for Launceston this morning,'
answered the man.

2794
03:35:09,420 --> 03:35:13,700
'He was called away at short notice, and he
has not yet returned.'

2795
03:35:13,700 --> 03:35:20,610
This time Mary could not control herself,
and a cry of hopelessness escaped her.

2796
03:35:20,610 --> 03:35:28,221
'I have come a long way,' she said, with great
feeling, as if by the strength of her need

2797
03:35:28,221 --> 03:35:31,551
for him she could bring the magistrate to
her side.

2798
03:35:31,551 --> 03:35:38,240
'If I do not see him, something terrible will
happen, and a great criminal will escape the

2799
03:35:38,240 --> 03:35:40,330
hands of the law.

2800
03:35:40,330 --> 03:35:44,880
You are looking at me strangely, but I am
speaking the truth.

2801
03:35:44,880 --> 03:35:47,980
If only there were someone I could turn to...'

2802
03:35:47,980 --> 03:35:53,630
'Mrs Bassat is at home,' said the man with
interest.

2803
03:35:53,630 --> 03:35:58,800
'Perhaps she will see you, if your business
is as urgent as you say.

2804
03:35:58,800 --> 03:36:03,000
Follow me, will you, to the library?'

2805
03:36:03,000 --> 03:36:08,570
Mary crossed the hall in a dream, knowing
only that her plan had failed again, through

2806
03:36:08,570 --> 03:36:13,460
chance alone, and that she was now powerless
to help herself.

2807
03:36:13,460 --> 03:36:19,300
The library, with its bright fire, seemed
unreal to her, and her eyes were not used

2808
03:36:19,300 --> 03:36:20,970
to the light that met them.

2809
03:36:20,970 --> 03:36:28,120
A woman, whom she recognized immediately as
the lady who had bought the horse in Launceston

2810
03:36:28,120 --> 03:36:33,170
market square, was sitting in a chair in front
of the fire.

2811
03:36:33,170 --> 03:36:37,340
She looked up in surprise when Mary was shown
into the room.

2812
03:36:37,340 --> 03:36:40,510
Mrs Bassat rose to her feet.

2813
03:36:40,510 --> 03:36:43,750
'What can I do for you?'

2814
03:36:43,750 --> 03:36:45,020
she said kindly.

2815
03:36:45,020 --> 03:36:48,600
'You look pale and tired.

2816
03:36:48,600 --> 03:36:51,450
Won't you sit down?'

2817
03:36:51,450 --> 03:36:52,910
Mary shook her head impatiently.

2818
03:36:52,910 --> 03:36:58,730
'Thank you, but I must know when Mr Bassat
is returning home.'

2819
03:36:58,730 --> 03:37:02,710
'I have no idea,' replied his wife.

2820
03:37:02,710 --> 03:37:10,021
'He had to leave this morning at a moment's
notice, and, to tell you the truth, I am really

2821
03:37:10,021 --> 03:37:11,650
anxious about him.

2822
03:37:11,650 --> 03:37:18,760
If this innkeeper decides to fight, as he
is certain to do, Mr Bassat may be wounded,

2823
03:37:18,760 --> 03:37:20,891
in spite of the soldiers.'

2824
03:37:20,891 --> 03:37:24,700
'What do you mean?' said Mary quickly.

2825
03:37:24,700 --> 03:37:29,320
'He has set out on a highly dangerous piece
of work.

2826
03:37:29,320 --> 03:37:36,760
Your face is new to me, and I suppose you
are not from North Hill, or you would have

2827
03:37:36,760 --> 03:37:42,240
heard of the man Merlyn who keeps an inn on
the Bodmin road.

2828
03:37:42,240 --> 03:37:48,021
Mr Bassat has suspected him for some time
of terrible crimes, but it was not until this

2829
03:37:48,021 --> 03:37:51,870
morning that the full proof came into his
hands.

2830
03:37:51,870 --> 03:37:58,710
He left immediately for Launceston to get
help, and he intends to surround the inn tonight,

2831
03:37:58,710 --> 03:38:01,690
and seize the people inside.

2832
03:38:01,690 --> 03:38:07,381
He will go well armed, of course, and with
a large body of men, but I shall not rest

2833
03:38:07,381 --> 03:38:09,550
until he returns.'

2834
03:38:09,550 --> 03:38:17,580
'I came here to warn Mr Bassat that the landlord
intends to leave the inn tonight, and so escape

2835
03:38:17,580 --> 03:38:18,580
justice.

2836
03:38:18,580 --> 03:38:23,830
I have proof of his guilt, which I did not
believe Mr Bassat to possess.

2837
03:38:23,830 --> 03:38:29,011
You tell me that he has already gone, and
perhaps even now is at Jamaica Inn.

2838
03:38:29,011 --> 03:38:33,500
Therefore I have wasted my time in coming
here.'

2839
03:38:33,500 --> 03:38:40,801
Mary sat down then, her hands folded, and
looked unseeing into the fire.

2840
03:38:40,801 --> 03:38:45,710
She had come to the end of her strength and
for the moment, she could not look into the

2841
03:38:45,710 --> 03:38:46,710
future.

2842
03:38:46,710 --> 03:38:52,790
All that her tired mind could tell her was
that her journey this evening had been for

2843
03:38:52,790 --> 03:38:53,790
nothing.

2844
03:38:53,790 --> 03:38:59,040
'I have done a very stupid thing in coming
here,' she said miserably.

2845
03:38:59,040 --> 03:39:06,420
T thought it clever, but I have only succeeded
in making a fool of myself and of everyone

2846
03:39:06,420 --> 03:39:07,910
else.

2847
03:39:07,910 --> 03:39:13,480
My uncle will discover that my room is empty,
and guess that I have informed against him.

2848
03:39:13,480 --> 03:39:18,650
He will leave Jamaica Inn before Mr Bassat
arrives.'

2849
03:39:18,650 --> 03:39:21,500
Mrs Bassat came towards her.

2850
03:39:21,500 --> 03:39:29,840
'You have been placed in a terrible position,'
she said kindly, 'and I think you are very

2851
03:39:29,840 --> 03:39:35,061
brave to come here tonight, all those lonely
miles, to warn my husband.

2852
03:39:35,061 --> 03:39:39,630
The question is: what do you want me to do
now?

2853
03:39:39,630 --> 03:39:43,520
I will help you in any way you think best.'

2854
03:39:43,520 --> 03:39:50,460
'I can think of nothing but my poor aunt,
who at this moment may be suffering terribly.

2855
03:39:50,460 --> 03:39:57,450
I must know what is happening at Jamaica Inn,
if I have to walk back there myself tonight.'

2856
03:39:57,450 --> 03:40:03,050
'But you cannot possibly walk back there now,
alone.

2857
03:40:03,050 --> 03:40:07,030
I will order the carriage, and Richards will
go with you.

2858
03:40:07,030 --> 03:40:12,080
He can be trusted completely, and will carry
guns for your protection.

2859
03:40:12,080 --> 03:40:19,950
If there is fighting in progress, you need
not go near the inn until it is over.'

2860
03:40:19,950 --> 03:40:29,521
In a quarter of an hour, the carriage drove
up to the door, with Richards in charge.

2861
03:40:29,521 --> 03:40:36,240
Mary recognized him as the servant who had
ridden with Mr Bassat to Jamaica Inn before.

2862
03:40:36,240 --> 03:40:42,130
He wanted to know everything, of course, but
she gave short answers to his questions, and

2863
03:40:42,130 --> 03:40:44,479
did not encourage him.

2864
03:40:44,479 --> 03:40:49,770
The horse and carriage quickly covered the
miles that Mary had walked alone.

2865
03:40:49,770 --> 03:40:55,150
'We shall find them there before us, as likely
as not,' Richards told Mary.

2866
03:40:55,150 --> 03:41:00,220
'It will be a good thing for the neighbourhood
when he's in prison.

2867
03:41:00,220 --> 03:41:07,120
It's a pity we were not here sooner; there'll
have been some excitement in taking him, I

2868
03:41:07,120 --> 03:41:08,120
expect.'

2869
03:41:08,120 --> 03:41:14,130
'Little excitement if Mr Bassat finds his
man has escaped,' said Mary quietly.

2870
03:41:14,130 --> 03:41:19,431
'Joss Merlyn knows these moors like the back
of his hand.'

2871
03:41:19,431 --> 03:41:25,530
'My master was born here, just as the landlord
was,' said Richards.

2872
03:41:25,530 --> 03:41:32,860
'If it comes to a run across country, I'd
expect my master to win every time.

2873
03:41:32,860 --> 03:41:38,229
He has hunted here, as man and boy, for nearly
50 years.

2874
03:41:38,229 --> 03:41:42,690
But they'll catch Merlyn before he starts
to run, if I'm not mistaken.'

2875
03:41:42,690 --> 03:41:50,210
The steep hill to Jamaica Inn rose in front
of them, white beneath the moon, and as the

2876
03:41:50,210 --> 03:41:57,510
dark chimneys rose into view, Richards became
silent, examining his guns.

2877
03:41:57,510 --> 03:42:03,030
As they came near to the top of the hill,
Richards turned, and whispered in her ear,

2878
03:42:03,030 --> 03:42:09,910
'Would it be best for you to wait here, in
the carriage, by the side of the road, while

2879
03:42:09,910 --> 03:42:13,530
I go forward to see if they are there?'

2880
03:42:13,530 --> 03:42:18,870
'I've waited long enough tonight, and gone
half-crazy with it,' said Mary.

2881
03:42:18,870 --> 03:42:26,061
'I'd rather meet my uncle face to face than
stay behind here, seeing and hearing, nothing.

2882
03:42:26,061 --> 03:42:28,650
It's my aunt I'm thinking of.

2883
03:42:28,650 --> 03:42:32,740
She's as harmless as a child, and I want to
take care of her if I can.

2884
03:42:32,740 --> 03:42:36,560
Give me a gun and let me go.

2885
03:42:36,560 --> 03:42:41,450
I won't take any risks, I promise you.'

2886
03:42:41,450 --> 03:42:47,880
She went forward, then held her gun in front
of her and looked round the corner of the

2887
03:42:47,880 --> 03:42:49,570
stonewall into the yard.

2888
03:42:49,570 --> 03:42:51,761
It was empty.

2889
03:42:51,761 --> 03:42:54,230
The stable door was shut.

2890
03:42:54,230 --> 03:43:02,440
The inn was as dark and silent as when she
had left it nearly seven hours before; the

2891
03:43:02,440 --> 03:43:04,670
windows and the door were barred.

2892
03:43:04,670 --> 03:43:11,490
There were no wheel marks in the yard, and
no preparations for escape.

2893
03:43:11,490 --> 03:43:17,229
She crept across to the stable and laid her
ear against the door.

2894
03:43:17,229 --> 03:43:23,180
She waited a moment, and then she heard the
horse move restlessly, she heard his feet

2895
03:43:23,180 --> 03:43:25,720
on the stone floor.

2896
03:43:25,720 --> 03:43:30,580
Then they had not gone, and her uncle was
still at Jamaica Inn!

2897
03:43:30,580 --> 03:43:37,840
Her heart sank, and she wondered if she should
return to Richards and wait until the magistrate

2898
03:43:37,840 --> 03:43:39,700
and his men arrived.

2899
03:43:39,700 --> 03:43:46,940
Surely, if her uncle intended to leave, he
would have gone before now?

2900
03:43:46,940 --> 03:43:53,150
He might have changed his plans and decided
to go on foot, but then Aunt Patience could

2901
03:43:53,150 --> 03:43:54,880
never go with him.

2902
03:43:54,880 --> 03:43:59,470
Mary went round the corner of the house.

2903
03:43:59,470 --> 03:44:04,750
She came to where a crack of light would show
through the kitchen window shutter.

2904
03:44:04,750 --> 03:44:07,380
There was no light.

2905
03:44:07,380 --> 03:44:10,100
She laid her hand on the handle of the door.

2906
03:44:10,100 --> 03:44:14,971
It turned, to her surprise, and the door opened.

2907
03:44:14,971 --> 03:44:21,110
This easy entrance, completely unexpected,
surprised her for the moment and she was afraid

2908
03:44:21,110 --> 03:44:23,810
to enter.

2909
03:44:23,810 --> 03:44:30,180
Supposing her uncle sat on his chair, waiting
for her, his gun across his knee?

2910
03:44:30,180 --> 03:44:35,120
She had her own gun, but it gave her no confidence.

2911
03:44:35,120 --> 03:44:40,200
Very slowly, she put her face around the door.

2912
03:44:40,200 --> 03:44:41,979
No sound came to her.

2913
03:44:41,979 --> 03:44:48,061
Out of the corner of her eye, she could see
the ashes of the fire, but they were hardly

2914
03:44:48,061 --> 03:44:49,810
red.

2915
03:44:49,810 --> 03:44:54,870
She knew then that the kitchen had been empty
for hours.

2916
03:44:54,870 --> 03:44:58,120
She pushed the door open, and went inside.

2917
03:44:58,120 --> 03:45:03,850
She lit the lamp and looked about her.

2918
03:45:03,850 --> 03:45:10,230
The door to the passage was wide open, and
the silence became more frightening than before,

2919
03:45:10,230 --> 03:45:12,870
strangely and terribly still.

2920
03:45:12,870 --> 03:45:20,510
Something was not as it had been; some sound
was missing that must account for the silence.

2921
03:45:20,510 --> 03:45:25,011
Then Mary realized that she could not hear
the clock.

2922
03:45:25,011 --> 03:45:28,229
It had stopped.

2923
03:45:28,229 --> 03:45:32,940
She stepped into the passage and listened
again.

2924
03:45:32,940 --> 03:45:39,750
She was right; the house was silent because
the clock had stopped.

2925
03:45:39,750 --> 03:45:44,750
She turned the corner, and she saw that the
clock, which always stood against the wall

2926
03:45:44,750 --> 03:45:48,990
beside the door, had fallen forward on to
its face.

2927
03:45:48,990 --> 03:45:54,431
The glass was in pieces on the stone floor,
and the wood had split.

2928
03:45:54,431 --> 03:45:59,710
The clock had fallen across the narrow hall,
and it was not until she came to the foot

2929
03:45:59,710 --> 03:46:05,190
of the stairs that Mary saw what was beyond
it.

2930
03:46:05,190 --> 03:46:12,400
The landlord of Jamaica Inn lay on his face
among the broken glass.

2931
03:46:12,400 --> 03:46:18,680
The fallen clock had hidden him at first;
he lay in the shadow, one arm thrown above

2932
03:46:18,680 --> 03:46:22,680
his head and the other holding the door.

2933
03:46:22,680 --> 03:46:27,970
There was blood on the stone floor; and blood
between his shoulders, dark now and nearly

2934
03:46:27,970 --> 03:46:32,450
dry, where the knife had entered him.

2935
03:46:32,450 --> 03:46:37,030
When he was attacked from behind, he must
have stretched out his hands, and fallen,

2936
03:46:37,030 --> 03:46:42,950
dragging at the clock; and when he fell on
his face, the clock had crashed with him to

2937
03:46:42,950 --> 03:46:50,720
the ground, and he had died there, trying
to reach the door.

2938
03:46:50,720 --> 03:46:53,991
CHAPTER FOURTEEN
The Pedlar Is Found

2939
03:46:53,991 --> 03:47:00,870
It was a long time before Mary moved away
from the stairs.

2940
03:47:00,870 --> 03:47:06,560
Something of her own strength had gone, leaving
her powerless like the figure on the floor.

2941
03:47:06,560 --> 03:47:11,150
It was the silence that frightened her most.

2942
03:47:11,150 --> 03:47:15,979
Now that the clock was no longer going, her
ears missed the sound of it.

2943
03:47:15,979 --> 03:47:22,120
Her light shone on the walls, but it did not
reach to the top of the stairs, where the

2944
03:47:22,120 --> 03:47:24,690
darkness waited for her.

2945
03:47:24,690 --> 03:47:31,561
She knew that she could never climb those
stairs again, nor walk along that upper passage.

2946
03:47:31,561 --> 03:47:34,860
Whatever lay above her must stay there.

2947
03:47:34,860 --> 03:47:40,101
She backed away down the hall along the passage,
and when she came to the kitchen and saw the

2948
03:47:40,101 --> 03:47:46,590
door still open, her self-control left her,
and she ran blindly through the door to the

2949
03:47:46,590 --> 03:47:51,979
cold air outside, where the familiar figure
of Richards met her.

2950
03:47:51,979 --> 03:47:58,010
He put out his hands to save her, and she
seized him, feeling for comfort, cold now

2951
03:47:58,010 --> 03:47:59,860
from the shock.

2952
03:47:59,860 --> 03:48:05,570
'He's dead,' she said; 'he's dead there on
the floor.

2953
03:48:05,570 --> 03:48:12,780
I saw him'; and, although she tried hard,
she could not stop shaking.

2954
03:48:12,780 --> 03:48:16,130
He led her to the side of the road, back to
the carriage.

2955
03:48:16,130 --> 03:48:21,710
'Has your aunt gone?' he whispered.

2956
03:48:21,710 --> 03:48:23,101
Mary shook her head.

2957
03:48:23,101 --> 03:48:25,351
'I don't know.

2958
03:48:25,351 --> 03:48:26,430
I didn't see.

2959
03:48:26,430 --> 03:48:29,940
I had to come away.'

2960
03:48:29,940 --> 03:48:32,610
He saw by her face that her strength had gone.

2961
03:48:32,610 --> 03:48:36,610
'All right, then,' he said, 'all right.

2962
03:48:36,610 --> 03:48:38,620
Sit quiet, then.

2963
03:48:38,620 --> 03:48:40,670
No one shall hurt you.

2964
03:48:40,670 --> 03:48:42,300
There now.'

2965
03:48:42,300 --> 03:48:46,650
His rough voice helped her, and she sat close
beside him.

2966
03:48:46,650 --> 03:48:51,310
'That was no sight for a girl to see; you
should have let me go.

2967
03:48:51,310 --> 03:48:55,480
I wish now you'd stayed back here in the carriage.

2968
03:48:55,480 --> 03:49:01,350
That's terrible for you, to see him lying
there, murdered.'

2969
03:49:01,350 --> 03:49:02,570
Talking helped her.

2970
03:49:02,570 --> 03:49:05,680
'The horse was still in the stable.

2971
03:49:05,680 --> 03:49:09,690
I listened at the door and heard it moving
about.

2972
03:49:09,690 --> 03:49:13,720
They had never even finished their preparations
for going.

2973
03:49:13,720 --> 03:49:19,160
The kitchen door was not locked, and there
were packages on the floor there, ready to

2974
03:49:19,160 --> 03:49:20,681
load into the wagon.

2975
03:49:20,681 --> 03:49:23,280
It must have happened several hours ago.'

2976
03:49:23,280 --> 03:49:29,130
'I don't know what the magistrate is doing,'
said Richards.

2977
03:49:29,130 --> 03:49:32,140
'He should have been here before this.

2978
03:49:32,140 --> 03:49:35,620
You should tell your story to him.

2979
03:49:35,620 --> 03:49:38,351
There's been bad work here tonight.'

2980
03:49:38,351 --> 03:49:43,200
They fell silent, and both of them watched
the road.

2981
03:49:43,200 --> 03:49:48,280
'Who could have killed the landlord?' said
Richards confused.

2982
03:49:48,280 --> 03:49:54,590
'He can deal with most men, and should have
been able to defend himself.

2983
03:49:54,590 --> 03:50:01,290
There were plenty who might have done it,
though if ever a man was hated, he was.'

2984
03:50:01,290 --> 03:50:05,841
'There was the pedlar,' said Mary slowly.

2985
03:50:05,841 --> 03:50:08,460
'I'd forgotten about him.

2986
03:50:08,460 --> 03:50:15,670
It must have been him, breaking out from the
locked room.'

2987
03:50:15,670 --> 03:50:23,271
She seized on this idea, to escape from another;
and she retold the story, eagerly now, of

2988
03:50:23,271 --> 03:50:26,350
how the pedlar had come to the inn the night
before.

2989
03:50:26,350 --> 03:50:34,120
It seemed then that the crime was proved,
and there could be no other explanation.

2990
03:50:34,120 --> 03:50:38,940
'He'll not run far before the magistrate catches
him,' said Richards.

2991
03:50:38,940 --> 03:50:45,610
'No one can hide on these moors, unless he's
a local man, and I've never heard of Harry

2992
03:50:45,610 --> 03:50:47,190
the pedlar before.

2993
03:50:47,190 --> 03:50:55,090
But then, they came from every hole and corner
in Cornwall, Joss Merlyn's men.

2994
03:50:55,090 --> 03:50:58,480
They were the lowest of the low from the whole
area.'

2995
03:50:58,480 --> 03:51:07,320
He paused, and then: 'I'll go to the inn,
if you would like me to, and see for myself

2996
03:51:07,320 --> 03:51:10,900
whether he has left any tracks behind him.

2997
03:51:10,900 --> 03:51:14,200
There might be something

2998
03:51:14,200 --> 03:51:16,720
Mary seized hold of his arm.

2999
03:51:16,720 --> 03:51:21,391
'I don't want to be alone again,' she said
quickly.

3000
03:51:21,391 --> 03:51:25,221
'Think me a fool if you will, but I couldn't
bear it.

3001
03:51:25,221 --> 03:51:31,631
If you had been inside Jamaica Inn tonight,
you would understand...

3002
03:51:31,631 --> 03:51:33,479
Something has happened to my aunt as well.

3003
03:51:33,479 --> 03:51:34,900
I know that.

3004
03:51:34,900 --> 03:51:37,280
I know she is dead.

3005
03:51:37,280 --> 03:51:41,801
That's why I was afraid to go upstairs.

3006
03:51:41,801 --> 03:51:45,650
She's lying there in the darkness, in the
passage above.

3007
03:51:45,650 --> 03:51:50,290
Whoever killed my uncle will have killed her
too.'

3008
03:51:50,290 --> 03:51:53,230
The servant coughed.

3009
03:51:53,230 --> 03:51:56,420
'She may have run out on to the moor.

3010
03:51:56,420 --> 03:51:59,780
She may have run for help along the road.'

3011
03:51:59,780 --> 03:52:06,120
'No,' whispered Mary, 'she would never have
done that.

3012
03:52:06,120 --> 03:52:09,580
She would be with him now, by his side.

3013
03:52:09,580 --> 03:52:11,200
She's dead.

3014
03:52:11,200 --> 03:52:14,440
I know she's dead.

3015
03:52:14,440 --> 03:52:18,190
If I hadn't left her, this would never have
happened.'

3016
03:52:18,190 --> 03:52:21,430
The man was silent.

3017
03:52:21,430 --> 03:52:23,170
He could not help her.

3018
03:52:23,170 --> 03:52:30,620
After all, she was a stranger to him, and
what had happened was no concern of his.

3019
03:52:30,620 --> 03:52:34,880
Mary held up a warning hand.

3020
03:52:34,880 --> 03:52:37,100
'Listen,' she said.

3021
03:52:37,100 --> 03:52:39,620
'Can you hear something?'

3022
03:52:39,620 --> 03:52:41,900
They looked to the north.

3023
03:52:41,900 --> 03:52:45,510
The distant sound of horses was unmistakable.

3024
03:52:45,510 --> 03:52:49,570
'It's them!' said Richards excitedly.

3025
03:52:49,570 --> 03:52:54,200
'It's the magistrate; he's coming at last.'

3026
03:52:54,200 --> 03:52:55,470
They waited.

3027
03:52:55,470 --> 03:53:03,110
The noise drew near, and Richards in his relief
ran out on to the road to greet them, shouting

3028
03:53:03,110 --> 03:53:04,610
and waving his arms.

3029
03:53:04,610 --> 03:53:10,540
The leader pulled up his horse, calling out
in surprise at the sight of him.

3030
03:53:10,540 --> 03:53:12,631
'What are you doing here?' he shouted.

3031
03:53:12,631 --> 03:53:18,229
It was Mr Bassat himself.

3032
03:53:18,229 --> 03:53:21,660
He held up his hand to warn his followers
behind.

3033
03:53:21,660 --> 03:53:25,680
'The landlord is dead, murdered!'

3034
03:53:25,680 --> 03:53:27,170
cried his servant.

3035
03:53:27,170 --> 03:53:30,740
'I have a young relative of his here with
me in the carriage.

3036
03:53:30,740 --> 03:53:36,160
It was Mrs Bassat who sent me out here, sir.'

3037
03:53:36,160 --> 03:53:42,050
He held the horse for his master, answering
as well as he could the rapid questions put

3038
03:53:42,050 --> 03:53:43,050
to him.

3039
03:53:43,050 --> 03:53:49,500
'If the man has been murdered, he deserved
it, but I'd still rather have put him in chains

3040
03:53:49,500 --> 03:53:50,500
myself.

3041
03:53:50,500 --> 03:53:53,690
You cannot punish a dead man.'

3042
03:53:53,690 --> 03:53:59,900
The magistrate, whose mind worked slowly,
began to realize what Mary was doing in the

3043
03:53:59,900 --> 03:54:01,620
carriage.

3044
03:54:01,620 --> 03:54:05,690
He had thought at first that she was his servant's
prisoner.

3045
03:54:05,690 --> 03:54:11,070
'This is too difficult for me to understand,'
he said.

3046
03:54:11,070 --> 03:54:15,931
'I believed you to be working with your uncle
against the law.

3047
03:54:15,931 --> 03:54:19,729
Why did you lie to me, when I came earlier
in the month?

3048
03:54:19,729 --> 03:54:21,730
You told me you knew nothing.'

3049
03:54:21,730 --> 03:54:26,040
'I lied because of my aunt,' said Mary.

3050
03:54:26,040 --> 03:54:33,220
'Whatever I said to you then was only for
her, nor did I know as much then as I do now.'

3051
03:54:33,220 --> 03:54:40,710
'You did a brave thing in walking all that
way to Altarnun to warn me; but-all this trouble

3052
03:54:40,710 --> 03:54:46,170
could have been avoided, and the terrible
crime of that night could have been prevented

3053
03:54:46,170 --> 03:54:48,840
if you had been open with me before.

3054
03:54:48,840 --> 03:54:52,370
But we can talk about that later.

3055
03:54:52,370 --> 03:54:56,890
I must ask you to wait in the yard.'

3056
03:54:56,890 --> 03:55:03,070
He led his men round the back, and before
long, the dark and silent house seemed to

3057
03:55:03,070 --> 03:55:04,070
come to life.

3058
03:55:04,070 --> 03:55:12,070
The windows were thrown open, and some of
the men went upstairs and explored the rooms

3059
03:55:12,070 --> 03:55:13,070
above.

3060
03:55:13,070 --> 03:55:16,740
Someone called sharply from the house.

3061
03:55:16,740 --> 03:55:23,030
After a time the magistrate himself came out
into the yard and walked over to the carriage.

3062
03:55:23,030 --> 03:55:26,610
'I'm sorry,' he said.

3063
03:55:26,610 --> 03:55:28,571
'I have bad news for you.

3064
03:55:28,571 --> 03:55:33,300
Perhaps you expected it.'

3065
03:55:33,300 --> 03:55:36,630
'Yes,' said Mary.

3066
03:55:36,630 --> 03:55:40,140
'I don't think she suffered at all.

3067
03:55:40,140 --> 03:55:44,630
She was lying just inside the bedroom at the
end of the passage.

3068
03:55:44,630 --> 03:55:48,070
Killed with a knife, like your uncle.

3069
03:55:48,070 --> 03:55:49,760
She could have known nothing.

3070
03:55:49,760 --> 03:55:53,500
Believe me, I'm very sorry.

3071
03:55:53,500 --> 03:55:56,700
I wish I could have kept this from you.'

3072
03:55:56,700 --> 03:56:02,970
He stood by her awkwardly; and then, seeing
that Mary was better left alone, he walked

3073
03:56:02,970 --> 03:56:06,560
back across the yard to the inn.

3074
03:56:06,560 --> 03:56:12,110
Mary sat without moving and prayed in her
own way that Aunt Patience would understand

3075
03:56:12,110 --> 03:56:18,060
what she had tried to do, and would forgive
her and find peace now, wherever she might

3076
03:56:18,060 --> 03:56:20,590
be.

3077
03:56:20,590 --> 03:56:26,940
Once again, there was excitement in the house
- shouting and the sound of running feet.

3078
03:56:26,940 --> 03:56:31,410
There was a crash of splitting wood and the
shutters were torn away from the windows of

3079
03:56:31,410 --> 03:56:37,280
the locked room, which no one, it seemed,
had entered until now Then round the corner

3080
03:56:37,280 --> 03:56:43,561
of the yard they came, six or seven of them
led by the magistrate, holding among them

3081
03:56:43,561 --> 03:56:45,900
something that fought to escape.

3082
03:56:45,900 --> 03:56:47,450
'They've got him!

3083
03:56:47,450 --> 03:56:50,850
It's the murderer!'

3084
03:56:50,850 --> 03:56:52,180
shouted Richards.

3085
03:56:52,180 --> 03:57:00,900
The prisoner looked up at her, his face and
clothes dirty; it was Harry the pedlar.

3086
03:57:00,900 --> 03:57:05,360
'What do you know of this man?'

3087
03:57:05,360 --> 03:57:07,440
the magistrate said to Mary.

3088
03:57:07,440 --> 03:57:11,690
'We found him in the locked room there, lying
on the floor.

3089
03:57:11,690 --> 03:57:15,690
He says he knows nothing of the crime.'

3090
03:57:15,690 --> 03:57:22,681
'He was one of the company,' said Mary slowly,
'and he came to the inn last night and quarrelled

3091
03:57:22,681 --> 03:57:24,710
with my uncle.

3092
03:57:24,710 --> 03:57:30,650
My uncle aimed a gun at him, and locked him
up in the locked room, threatening him with

3093
03:57:30,650 --> 03:57:31,650
death.

3094
03:57:31,650 --> 03:57:37,229
He had every reason to kill my uncle, and
no one could have done it except him.

3095
03:57:37,229 --> 03:57:38,229
He is lying to you.'

3096
03:57:38,229 --> 03:57:45,900
'But the door was locked; it took three of
us to break it down from the outside.

3097
03:57:45,900 --> 03:57:49,630
This man had never been out of the room at
all.

3098
03:57:49,630 --> 03:57:55,320
Look at his clothes; look at his eyes, blinded
still by our light!

3099
03:57:55,320 --> 03:57:59,490
He's not your murderer.'

3100
03:57:59,490 --> 03:58:03,980
Mary knew then that what Mr Bassat had said
was the truth.

3101
03:58:03,980 --> 03:58:07,729
Harry the pedlar could not have done the murders.

3102
03:58:07,729 --> 03:58:14,320
'We'll have him in prison, in spite of that,
and hang him too, if he deserves it, which

3103
03:58:14,320 --> 03:58:16,350
I'll swear he does.

3104
03:58:16,350 --> 03:58:21,690
But first he shall give us the names of his
companions.

3105
03:58:21,690 --> 03:58:27,020
One of them has killed the landlord, you may
be sure of that, and we'll track him down

3106
03:58:27,020 --> 03:58:31,960
if we have to set every dog in Cornwall on
his heels.'

3107
03:58:31,960 --> 03:58:39,121
They dragged the pedlar away, swearing and
begging them to let him go, turning his rat's

3108
03:58:39,121 --> 03:58:45,660
eyes now and again on Mary, who sat above
him in the carriage a few yards away.

3109
03:58:45,660 --> 03:58:51,430
She neither heard his curses nor saw his ugly
narrow eyes.

3110
03:58:51,430 --> 03:58:56,440
She remembered other eyes that had looked
at her that morning, and another voice that

3111
03:58:56,440 --> 03:59:03,020
had spoken calmly and coldly, saying of his
brother: 'He shall die for this.'

3112
03:59:03,020 --> 03:59:11,100
There was the sentence, thrown out carelessly
on the way to Launceston fair: 'I have never

3113
03:59:11,100 --> 03:59:19,479
killed a man - yet'; and there was the old
woman in the market square: 'There's blood

3114
03:59:19,479 --> 03:59:25,740
on your hands; you'll kill a man one day.'

3115
03:59:25,740 --> 03:59:33,190
All the little things she wanted to forget
rose up and shouted against Jem: his hatred

3116
03:59:33,190 --> 03:59:37,460
of his brother, his cruelty, his bad Merlyn
blood.

3117
03:59:37,460 --> 03:59:47,910
He had gone to Jamaica Inn as he had promised,
and his brother had died, as he had sworn.

3118
03:59:47,910 --> 03:59:52,140
The whole truth was there in front of her
in its ugliness.

3119
03:59:52,140 --> 03:59:59,050
He was a thief, and like a thief in the night,
he had come and gone again.

3120
03:59:59,050 --> 04:00:06,900
When morning came, he would jump on a horse,
and ride away out of Cornwall forever, a murderer

3121
04:00:06,900 --> 04:00:09,210
like his father before him.

3122
04:00:09,210 --> 04:00:16,570
In her imagination, she heard the sound of
his horse on the road, far away in the quiet

3123
04:00:16,570 --> 04:00:17,570
night.

3124
04:00:17,570 --> 04:00:23,021
But the sound she heard was not the dream
thing of her imagination, but the real sound

3125
04:00:23,021 --> 04:00:25,729
of a horse coming towards her.

3126
04:00:25,729 --> 04:00:28,250
She turned her head and listened.

3127
04:00:28,250 --> 04:00:31,680
The sound of a horse drew nearer still.

3128
04:00:31,680 --> 04:00:33,740
She was not alone now as she listened.

3129
04:00:33,740 --> 04:00:41,229
The men looked towards the road, and Richards
went quickly to the inn to call the magistrate.

3130
04:00:41,229 --> 04:00:46,311
The sound of the horseman was loud now as
he came over the top of the hill, and when

3131
04:00:46,311 --> 04:00:50,970
he came into view Mr Bassat came out of the
inn.

3132
04:00:50,970 --> 04:00:53,520
'Stop!' he called.

3133
04:00:53,520 --> 04:00:55,860
'In the name of the King.

3134
04:00:55,860 --> 04:01:00,730
I must ask your business on the road tonight.'

3135
04:01:00,730 --> 04:01:03,650
The horseman turned into the yard.

3136
04:01:03,650 --> 04:01:09,610
When he took off his hat, his thick hair shone
white under the moon, and the voice that spoke

3137
04:01:09,610 --> 04:01:12,680
in answer was gentle and sweet.

3138
04:01:12,680 --> 04:01:21,820
'Mr Bassat of North Hill, I believe,' he said,
and he leant forward, with a note in his hand.

3139
04:01:21,820 --> 04:01:28,890
'I have a message here from Mary Yellan of
Jamaica Inn, who asks for my help in trouble;

3140
04:01:28,890 --> 04:01:34,320
but I see by the company here that I came
too late.

3141
04:01:34,320 --> 04:01:43,600
You remember me, of course; we have met before
- I am the Vicar of Altarnun.'

3142
04:01:43,600 --> 04:01:46,540
CHAPTER FIFTEEN
The Truth Is Told

3143
04:01:46,540 --> 04:01:54,150
Mary sat alone in the living room in the vicar's
house and looked into the fire.

3144
04:01:54,150 --> 04:02:00,690
She had slept for a long time, and now felt
rested, but the peace, which she desired,

3145
04:02:00,690 --> 04:02:02,320
had not yet come to her.

3146
04:02:02,320 --> 04:02:07,170
They had all been kind to her, and patient.

3147
04:02:07,170 --> 04:02:12,311
The vicar had driven her himself in the carriage
to Altarnun, and they arrived there as his

3148
04:02:12,311 --> 04:02:15,420
church clock struck one.

3149
04:02:15,420 --> 04:02:20,790
He called his housekeeper from her home nearby,
the same woman that Mary had spoken with in

3150
04:02:20,790 --> 04:02:22,820
the afternoon.

3151
04:02:22,820 --> 04:02:27,640
She lit a fire and warmed a rough woollen
nightdress in front of it, while Mary took

3152
04:02:27,640 --> 04:02:33,910
off her clothes, and when the bed was ready
for her and the bedclothes turned back, Mary

3153
04:02:33,910 --> 04:02:38,650
allowed herself to be led to it like a child.

3154
04:02:38,650 --> 04:02:43,820
She would have closed her eyes immediately
but an arm came suddenly round her shoulders

3155
04:02:43,820 --> 04:02:48,620
and a voice said in her ear: 'Drink this.'

3156
04:02:48,620 --> 04:02:55,050
Francis Davey himself stood beside the bed,
with a glass in his hand, his strange eyes

3157
04:02:55,050 --> 04:02:58,610
looking into hers, pale and expressionless.

3158
04:02:58,610 --> 04:03:06,410
'You will sleep now,' he said, and she knew
from the bitter taste that he had put some

3159
04:03:06,410 --> 04:03:09,240
powder in the hot drink, which he had made
for her.

3160
04:03:09,240 --> 04:03:16,811
The last thing she remembered was those still
white eyes that told her to forget; and then

3161
04:03:16,811 --> 04:03:17,841
she slept.

3162
04:03:17,841 --> 04:03:22,400
It was nearly four in the afternoon before
she woke.

3163
04:03:22,400 --> 04:03:28,190
When she was dressed, and had gone below to
the living room, to find the fire burning

3164
04:03:28,190 --> 04:03:34,180
and the curtains closed and the vicar out
on some business, it seemed to her that responsibility

3165
04:03:34,180 --> 04:03:37,601
for the murders was hers alone.

3166
04:03:37,601 --> 04:03:44,460
Jem's face was always with her as she had
seen it last, tired and lined in the grey

3167
04:03:44,460 --> 04:03:49,280
light, and there had been a determination
in his eyes then that she had tried not to

3168
04:03:49,280 --> 04:03:50,950
see.

3169
04:03:50,950 --> 04:03:57,630
He had played an unknown part from beginning
to end, and she had shut her eyes to the truth.

3170
04:03:57,630 --> 04:04:04,801
She was a woman, and for no good reason - in
fact, against all reason - she loved him.

3171
04:04:04,801 --> 04:04:10,480
He had kissed her, and she was tied to him
forever.

3172
04:04:10,480 --> 04:04:16,311
She felt herself weakened in mind and body,
she who had been strong before.

3173
04:04:16,311 --> 04:04:23,330
One word to the vicar when he returned, and
a message to the magistrate, and Jem would

3174
04:04:23,330 --> 04:04:29,229
die with a rope round his neck as his father
had done, and she would return to Helford

3175
04:04:29,229 --> 04:04:30,960
and her old life.

3176
04:04:30,960 --> 04:04:34,560
But she knew that the word would never be
given.

3177
04:04:34,560 --> 04:04:41,050
Jem was safe from her, and he could ride away
with a song on his lips, forgetful of her,

3178
04:04:41,050 --> 04:04:47,860
and of his brother, and of God; while she
dragged through the years, bitter and miserable,

3179
04:04:47,860 --> 04:04:53,270
coming in the end to be known as a woman who
had been kissed once in her life and could

3180
04:04:53,270 --> 04:04:58,421
not forget it.

3181
04:04:58,421 --> 04:05:03,150
She heard the vicar's footsteps on the path
outside, and rose hurriedly.

3182
04:05:03,150 --> 04:05:06,240
'Forgive me,' he said.

3183
04:05:06,240 --> 04:05:10,000
'You did not expect me so soon.'

3184
04:05:10,000 --> 04:05:11,271
He took out his watch.

3185
04:05:11,271 --> 04:05:17,060
'You have had supper with me before, Mary
Yellan, and you shall have supper with me

3186
04:05:17,060 --> 04:05:23,820
again; but this time, if you do not mind,
you shall prepare the table and bring the

3187
04:05:23,820 --> 04:05:26,290
food from the kitchen.

3188
04:05:26,290 --> 04:05:32,950
I have some writing to do; that is, if you
have no objection.'

3189
04:05:32,950 --> 04:05:38,610
When the church clock said quarter to seven,
they sat down together at the table and he

3190
04:05:38,610 --> 04:05:40,690
helped her to some cold meat.

3191
04:05:40,690 --> 04:05:48,440
'I understand from Richards, servant to Mr
Bassat, that you suspected the pedlar of the

3192
04:05:48,440 --> 04:05:51,660
murder, and said so to Mr Bassat himself.

3193
04:05:51,660 --> 04:05:59,120
It is a pity for all of us that the locked
room proves that he did not do it.

3194
04:05:59,120 --> 04:06:06,500
He would have done very well as a man to hang,
and saved a lot of trouble.'

3195
04:06:06,500 --> 04:06:12,641
The vicar ate an excellent supper, but Mary
was only playing with her food.

3196
04:06:12,641 --> 04:06:13,810
He watched her.

3197
04:06:13,810 --> 04:06:18,750
'What has the pedlar done, that you hate him?'

3198
04:06:18,750 --> 04:06:21,130
'He attacked me once.'

3199
04:06:21,130 --> 04:06:23,720
'I thought so.

3200
04:06:23,720 --> 04:06:26,200
You managed to fight him off?'

3201
04:06:26,200 --> 04:06:28,610
'I believe I hurt him.

3202
04:06:28,610 --> 04:06:29,780
He didn't touch me again.'

3203
04:06:29,780 --> 04:06:30,780
'No.

3204
04:06:30,780 --> 04:06:33,581
I don't suppose he did.

3205
04:06:33,581 --> 04:06:36,340
When did this happen?'

3206
04:06:36,340 --> 04:06:39,101
'On Christmas Eve.'

3207
04:06:39,101 --> 04:06:42,150
'After I left you in the carriage?'

3208
04:06:42,150 --> 04:06:43,150
'Yes.'

3209
04:06:43,150 --> 04:06:46,710
'I'm beginning to understand.

3210
04:06:46,710 --> 04:06:50,410
You didn't return, then, to the inn that night.

3211
04:06:50,410 --> 04:06:54,280
You met the landlord and his friends on the
road?'

3212
04:06:54,280 --> 04:06:55,280
'Yes.'

3213
04:06:55,280 --> 04:07:01,400
'And they took you with them to the shore
to add to their sport?'

3214
04:07:01,400 --> 04:07:05,540
'Please, Mr Davey, do not ask me anymore.

3215
04:07:05,540 --> 04:07:09,660
I would rather not speak of that night ever
again.

3216
04:07:09,660 --> 04:07:12,931
There are some things that are best buried
deep.'

3217
04:07:12,931 --> 04:07:17,840
'You shall not speak of it, Mary Yellan.

3218
04:07:17,840 --> 04:07:24,760
I blame myself for having allowed you to continue
your journey alone...

3219
04:07:24,760 --> 04:07:31,431
Turning back to the pedlar, though, I feel
it was very careless of the murderer not to

3220
04:07:31,431 --> 04:07:34,210
have looked into the locked room.

3221
04:07:34,210 --> 04:07:36,280
He would most certainly have made the whole
affair more thorough.'

3222
04:07:36,280 --> 04:07:43,040
'You mean, he might have killed the pedlar
too?'

3223
04:07:43,040 --> 04:07:44,040
'Exactly.

3224
04:07:44,040 --> 04:07:50,920
If the murderer had known that he had attacked
you, he would have had a strong enough reason

3225
04:07:50,920 --> 04:07:54,590
to kill the pedlar twice over.'

3226
04:07:54,590 --> 04:08:00,900
Mary cut herself a piece of cake, which she
did not want, and forced it between her lips.

3227
04:08:00,900 --> 04:08:05,860
But the hand that held the knife was shaking.

3228
04:08:05,860 --> 04:08:12,051
'I don't see,' she said, 'how I am involved
in the matter.'

3229
04:08:12,051 --> 04:08:18,730
'You have too low an opinion of yourself.'

3230
04:08:18,730 --> 04:08:28,200
They continued to eat in silence, Mary with
lowered head and eyes fixed on her plate.

3231
04:08:28,200 --> 04:08:32,150
She knew that he was watching her to see the
effect of his words.

3232
04:08:32,150 --> 04:08:40,270
But at last she could wait no longer, and
a question burst from her: 'So Mr Bassat and

3233
04:08:40,270 --> 04:08:46,150
the rest of you have made little progress
after all, and the murderer is still free?'

3234
04:08:46,150 --> 04:08:51,430
'The organization appears to have been far
larger than was formerly supposed.

3235
04:08:51,430 --> 04:08:59,090
In fact, the pedlar even suggested that the
landlord of Jamaica Inn was their leader in

3236
04:08:59,090 --> 04:09:05,760
name only, and that your uncle had orders
from someone above him.

3237
04:09:05,760 --> 04:09:09,790
That of course makes things look very different.

3238
04:09:09,790 --> 04:09:14,660
What have you to say about the pedlar's idea?'

3239
04:09:14,660 --> 04:09:17,730
'It is possible, of course.'

3240
04:09:17,730 --> 04:09:23,011
'I believe that you once made the same suggestion
to me?'

3241
04:09:23,011 --> 04:09:25,771
'I may have done.

3242
04:09:25,771 --> 04:09:26,771
I forget.'

3243
04:09:26,771 --> 04:09:36,640
'If this is so, it would seem that the unknown
leader and the murderer must be the same person.

3244
04:09:36,640 --> 04:09:39,040
Don't you agree?'

3245
04:09:39,040 --> 04:09:43,030
'Well, yes, I suppose so.'

3246
04:09:43,030 --> 04:09:46,250
'That should make the search easier.

3247
04:09:46,250 --> 04:09:52,740
We may forget most of the company, and look
for someone with a brain and some character.

3248
04:09:52,740 --> 04:09:57,980
Did you ever see such a person at Jamaica
Inn?'

3249
04:09:57,980 --> 04:09:59,700
'No, never.'

3250
04:09:59,700 --> 04:10:08,960
'He must have moved about secretly, possibly
in the silence of the night when you and your

3251
04:10:08,960 --> 04:10:10,910
aunt were asleep.

3252
04:10:10,910 --> 04:10:16,580
He would not have come by the road, because
you would have heard the noise of his horse.

3253
04:10:16,580 --> 04:10:19,600
So the man must know the moors.

3254
04:10:19,600 --> 04:10:25,181
That is why Mr Bassat intends to question
every local man within 10 miles.

3255
04:10:25,181 --> 04:10:34,960
So you see the net will close round the murderer,
and if he stays long he will be caught.

3256
04:10:34,960 --> 04:10:37,060
We are all sure of that.

3257
04:10:37,060 --> 04:10:39,560
Have you finished already?

3258
04:10:39,560 --> 04:10:42,689
You have eaten very little.'

3259
04:10:42,689 --> 04:10:43,689
'I'm not hungry.'

3260
04:10:43,689 --> 04:10:44,979
'I'm sorry about that.

3261
04:10:44,979 --> 04:10:48,810
Did I tell you that I saw a friend of yours
today?'

3262
04:10:48,810 --> 04:10:49,810
'No, you didn't.

3263
04:10:49,810 --> 04:10:52,930
I have no friends but yourself.'

3264
04:10:52,930 --> 04:10:55,070
'Thank you, Mary Yellan.

3265
04:10:55,070 --> 04:11:00,090
That's a kind thing to say to me.

3266
04:11:00,090 --> 04:11:04,900
But you're not being strictly truthful, you
know.

3267
04:11:04,900 --> 04:11:08,780
You have a friend; you told me so yourself.'

3268
04:11:08,780 --> 04:11:14,110
'I don't know who you mean, Mr Davey.'

3269
04:11:14,110 --> 04:11:15,440
'Come, now.

3270
04:11:15,440 --> 04:11:22,021
Didn't the landlord's brother take you to
Launceston fair?'

3271
04:11:22,021 --> 04:11:25,811
Under the table, Mary dug her fingernails
into her flesh.

3272
04:11:25,811 --> 04:11:28,511
'The landlord's brother?'

3273
04:11:28,511 --> 04:11:32,360
she repeated in order to delay her answer.

3274
04:11:32,360 --> 04:11:35,431
'I haven't seen him since then.

3275
04:11:35,431 --> 04:11:41,610
I believed him to be away.'

3276
04:11:41,610 --> 04:11:42,717
'No, he has been in the area since Christmas.

3277
04:11:42,717 --> 04:11:43,890
He told me so himself.

3278
04:11:43,890 --> 04:11:51,560
As a matter of fact, it had come to his ears
that I had given you shelter, and he came

3279
04:11:51,560 --> 04:11:54,189
up to me with a message for you.

3280
04:11:54,189 --> 04:11:58,730
"Tell her how sorry I am."

3281
04:11:58,730 --> 04:12:00,800
That is what he said.

3282
04:12:00,800 --> 04:12:05,770
I imagine that he meant that he was sorry
about your aunt.

3283
04:12:05,770 --> 04:12:10,800
It was just before I came away from North
Hill this evening when the discussion had

3284
04:12:10,800 --> 04:12:12,640
ended for the day.'

3285
04:12:12,640 --> 04:12:16,630
'Why was Jem Merlyn present at this discussion?'

3286
04:12:16,630 --> 04:12:21,979
'He had a right, I suppose, as brother of
the dead man.

3287
04:12:21,979 --> 04:12:28,700
He did not appear much moved by his death,
but perhaps they were not close.'

3288
04:12:28,700 --> 04:12:33,590
'Did - did Mr Bassat and the gentleman question
him?'

3289
04:12:33,590 --> 04:12:37,391
'There was a great deal of talk among them
the whole day.

3290
04:12:37,391 --> 04:12:40,771
Young Merlyn appears to have brains.

3291
04:12:40,771 --> 04:12:43,320
His answers were very clever.

3292
04:12:43,320 --> 04:12:47,890
He must have far better brains than his brother
ever had.

3293
04:12:47,890 --> 04:12:50,601
You told me he lived rather riskily, I remember.

3294
04:12:50,601 --> 04:12:56,351
He steals horses, I believe.'

3295
04:12:56,351 --> 04:12:57,431
Mary agreed.

3296
04:12:57,431 --> 04:13:02,170
Her fingers followed a pattern on the tablecloth.

3297
04:13:02,170 --> 04:13:07,320
'He seems to have done that when there was
nothing better to do, but when a chance came

3298
04:13:07,320 --> 04:13:13,979
for him to use his brains, he took it, and
one cannot blame him, I suppose.

3299
04:13:13,979 --> 04:13:19,470
No doubt he was well paid.'

3300
04:13:19,470 --> 04:13:25,160
The gentle voice wore away at her, and she
knew that he had defeated her.

3301
04:13:25,160 --> 04:13:27,900
She could no longer pretend that she did not
care.

3302
04:13:27,900 --> 04:13:30,000
'What will they do to him, Mr Davey?

3303
04:13:30,000 --> 04:13:32,689
What will they do to him?'

3304
04:13:32,689 --> 04:13:41,780
The pale, expressionless eyes looked back
at her, and for the first time she saw a shadow

3305
04:13:41,780 --> 04:13:46,210
pass across them and a momentary surprise.

3306
04:13:46,210 --> 04:13:48,330
'Do?' he said.

3307
04:13:48,330 --> 04:13:49,510
'Why should they do anything?

3308
04:13:49,510 --> 04:13:56,830
I suppose he has made his peace with Mr Bassat
and has nothing more to fear.

3309
04:13:56,830 --> 04:14:04,940
They will hardly try to punish him for old
crimes after the service he has done them.'

3310
04:14:04,940 --> 04:14:07,210
'I don't understand you.

3311
04:14:07,210 --> 04:14:09,729
What service has he done?'

3312
04:14:09,729 --> 04:14:13,580
'Your mind works slowly tonight, Mary Yellan.

3313
04:14:13,580 --> 04:14:22,300
Did you not know that it was Jem Merlyn who
informed against his brother?'

3314
04:14:22,300 --> 04:14:27,500
She looked at him stupidly, her brain refusing
to work.

3315
04:14:27,500 --> 04:14:33,030
She repeated the words after him like a child
who learns a lesson.

3316
04:14:33,030 --> 04:14:37,410
'Jem Merlyn informed against his brother?'

3317
04:14:37,410 --> 04:14:42,610
The vicar pushed away his plate, and began
to clear the table.

3318
04:14:42,610 --> 04:14:44,220
'Yes, certainly.

3319
04:14:44,220 --> 04:14:50,490
It appears that it was Mr Bassat himself who
took away your friend from Launceston that

3320
04:14:50,490 --> 04:14:53,850
night, and carried him off to North Hill.

3321
04:14:53,850 --> 04:15:00,510
"You've stolen my horse," he said, "and you're
as big a criminal as your brother.

3322
04:15:00,510 --> 04:15:07,721
I've the power to throw you into prison tomorrow,
and you wouldn't set eyes on a horse for ten

3323
04:15:07,721 --> 04:15:09,140
years or more.

3324
04:15:09,140 --> 04:15:17,010
But you can go free if you bring me proof
that your brother at Jamaica Inn is the man

3325
04:15:17,010 --> 04:15:18,920
I believe him to be."

3326
04:15:18,920 --> 04:15:22,710
'Your young friend said "No!

3327
04:15:22,710 --> 04:15:26,750
You must catch him yourself if you want him."

3328
04:15:26,750 --> 04:15:34,100
But the magistrate told him about the latest,
bloodiest wreck and suggested he changed his

3329
04:15:34,100 --> 04:15:35,100
mind.

3330
04:15:35,100 --> 04:15:40,870
I understand that your friend escaped from
his chains, though, and ran away in the night;

3331
04:15:40,870 --> 04:15:47,760
but he came back yesterday morning, when they
did not expect to see him again, and went

3332
04:15:47,760 --> 04:15:52,960
straight up to the magistrate and said, as
calmly as you please.

3333
04:15:52,960 --> 04:15:58,630
"Very well, Mr Bassat, you shall have your
proof."

3334
04:15:58,630 --> 04:16:06,040
And that is why I remarked to you just now
that Jem Merlyn has a better brain than his

3335
04:16:06,040 --> 04:16:09,450
brother had.'

3336
04:16:09,450 --> 04:16:16,771
Mary looked blindly before her into space,
her whole mind split, as it were, by his information,

3337
04:16:16,771 --> 04:16:23,130
the evidence she had so fearfully and so painfully
built against the man she loved falling like

3338
04:16:23,130 --> 04:16:25,390
a house of cards.

3339
04:16:25,390 --> 04:16:34,810
'Mr Davey,' she said slowly, 'I believe I
am the biggest fool that ever came out of

3340
04:16:34,810 --> 04:16:35,810
Cornwall.'

3341
04:16:35,810 --> 04:16:42,221
'I believe you are, Mary Yellan,' said the
vicar.

3342
04:16:42,221 --> 04:16:48,620
After the gentle voice that she was used to,
the sharpness of these words was a punishment

3343
04:16:48,620 --> 04:16:50,811
in itself.

3344
04:16:50,811 --> 04:16:55,090
The anxiety and fear had gone from her at
last.

3345
04:16:55,090 --> 04:16:59,720
'What else did Jem Merlyn say and do?'

3346
04:16:59,720 --> 04:17:01,550
she asked.

3347
04:17:01,550 --> 04:17:03,720
The vicar looked at his watch.

3348
04:17:03,720 --> 04:17:10,650
'I wish I had time to tell you,' he said,
'but it is nearly eight already.

3349
04:17:10,650 --> 04:17:14,181
The hours go by too fast for both of us.

3350
04:17:14,181 --> 04:17:22,240
I think we have talked enough about Jem Merlyn
for the present.'

3351
04:17:22,240 --> 04:17:24,530
'Tell me something - was he at North Hill
when you left?'

3352
04:17:24,530 --> 04:17:26,310
'He was.

3353
04:17:26,310 --> 04:17:30,570
In fact, it was his last remark that hurried
me home.'

3354
04:17:30,570 --> 04:17:33,960
'What did he say to you?'

3355
04:17:33,960 --> 04:17:37,610
'He was not speaking to me.

3356
04:17:37,610 --> 04:17:43,730
He told Mr Bassat he intended to ride over
tonight to visit the blacksmith at Warleggan.

3357
04:17:43,730 --> 04:17:51,710
It's a long way from North Hill, but I expect
he can find his way in the dark.'

3358
04:17:51,710 --> 04:17:54,660
'What has it to do with you if he visits the
blacksmith?'

3359
04:17:54,660 --> 04:18:01,870
'He will show him the nail he picked up in
the grass down in the field below Jamaica

3360
04:18:01,870 --> 04:18:02,870
Inn.

3361
04:18:02,870 --> 04:18:08,650
The nail comes from a horse's shoe; the work
was carelessly done, of course.

3362
04:18:08,650 --> 04:18:17,700
The nail was a new one, and Jem Merlyn, being
a stealer of horses, knows the work of every

3363
04:18:17,700 --> 04:18:19,290
blacksmith on the moors.

3364
04:18:19,290 --> 04:18:23,301
"Look here," he said to the magistrate.

3365
04:18:23,301 --> 04:18:28,110
"I found it this morning in the field behind
the inn.

3366
04:18:28,110 --> 04:18:34,800
I'll ride to Warleggan with your permission,
and throw this in Tom Jory's face as an example

3367
04:18:34,800 --> 04:18:36,450
of bad work."'

3368
04:18:36,450 --> 04:18:39,021
'Well, and what then?'

3369
04:18:39,021 --> 04:18:44,310
'Yesterday was Sunday, was it not?

3370
04:18:44,310 --> 04:18:51,900
And on Sunday no blacksmith works unless he
has a special respect for his customer.

3371
04:18:51,900 --> 04:18:59,830
Only one traveller passed Tom Jory's workshop
yesterday, and begged for a new nail for his

3372
04:18:59,830 --> 04:19:05,680
horse's shoe, and the time was, I suppose,
somewhere near seven o'clock in the evening.

3373
04:19:05,680 --> 04:19:16,530
After which, the traveller continued his journey
- a journey which included a visit to Jamaica

3374
04:19:16,530 --> 04:19:17,761
Inn.'

3375
04:19:17,761 --> 04:19:22,230
'How do you know this?' said Mary.

3376
04:19:22,230 --> 04:19:33,380
'Because the traveller was the Vicar of Altarnun,'
he said.

3377
04:19:33,380 --> 04:19:38,970
CHAPTER SIXTEEN
The Night on the Moors

3378
04:19:38,970 --> 04:19:41,630
A silence had fallen on the room.

3379
04:19:41,630 --> 04:19:48,420
Although the fire burnt as steadily as ever,
the air was cold as it had not been before.

3380
04:19:48,420 --> 04:19:54,800
Each waited for the other to speak, and Mary
heard Francis Davey swallow once.

3381
04:19:54,800 --> 04:20:03,470
At last, she looked into his face, and saw
what she expected: the pale, steady eyes looking

3382
04:20:03,470 --> 04:20:12,010
at her across the table, cold no longer, but
burning in his white face like living things.

3383
04:20:12,010 --> 04:20:18,870
She knew now what he wanted her to know, but
still she said nothing, trying to gain time

3384
04:20:18,870 --> 04:20:19,870
to think.

3385
04:20:19,870 --> 04:20:25,729
'There is no longer any need for us to pretend,'
he said.

3386
04:20:25,729 --> 04:20:32,870
'You say to yourself, "What sort of man is
this Vicar of Altarnun?"

3387
04:20:32,870 --> 04:20:39,890
You say, "He is a strange product of nature,
and his world is not my world."

3388
04:20:39,890 --> 04:20:42,250
You are right, Mary Yellan.

3389
04:20:42,250 --> 04:20:52,140
I live in the past - long ago in the beginning
of time, when the rivers and the sea were

3390
04:20:52,140 --> 04:20:57,261
one, and the old gods walked the hills.'

3391
04:20:57,261 --> 04:21:03,700
He rose from his chair and stood before the
fire, a thin black figure with white hair

3392
04:21:03,700 --> 04:21:09,610
and pale eyes, and his voice was gentle now,
as she had known it first.

3393
04:21:09,610 --> 04:21:17,979
'If you studied history you would understand,'
he said, 'but you are a woman, living in the

3394
04:21:17,979 --> 04:21:23,480
nineteenth century, and because of this my
language is strange to you.

3395
04:21:23,480 --> 04:21:28,160
Yes, I am a strange product of nature and
of time.

3396
04:21:28,160 --> 04:21:33,900
I do not belong here, and I was born with
a desire for revenge against our times and

3397
04:21:33,900 --> 04:21:37,189
against the human race.

3398
04:21:37,189 --> 04:21:42,700
Peace is very hard to find in the nineteenth
century.

3399
04:21:42,700 --> 04:21:47,500
The silence has gone, even on the hills.

3400
04:21:47,500 --> 04:21:51,980
I hoped to find it in the church, but its
teaching is false.

3401
04:21:51,980 --> 04:21:57,721
We can talk of these things later, though,
when we are no longer being hunted.

3402
04:21:57,721 --> 04:22:04,060
One thing at least - we have nothing to carry
and can travel light, as they travelled in

3403
04:22:04,060 --> 04:22:07,561
the old days.'

3404
04:22:07,561 --> 04:22:13,940
Mary looked up at him, holding tightly to
the sides of her chair.

3405
04:22:13,940 --> 04:22:18,150
'I don't understand you, Mr Davey.'

3406
04:22:18,150 --> 04:22:21,860
'You do; you understand me very well.

3407
04:22:21,860 --> 04:22:31,340
You know by now that I killed the landlord
of Jamaica Inn, and his wife too; nor would

3408
04:22:31,340 --> 04:22:35,551
the pedlar have lived if I had known of his
existence.

3409
04:22:35,551 --> 04:22:42,090
You have put the story together in your own
mind, while I talked to you just now.

3410
04:22:42,090 --> 04:22:48,940
You know that it was I who directed every
move made by your uncle, and that he was a

3411
04:22:48,940 --> 04:22:51,470
leader in name alone.

3412
04:22:51,470 --> 04:22:58,590
He was powerless without my orders, but the
greater his fame among his companions the

3413
04:22:58,590 --> 04:23:00,160
better he was pleased.

3414
04:23:00,160 --> 04:23:09,439
We were successful, and he served me well;
no other man knew our secret - that we were

3415
04:23:09,439 --> 04:23:10,439
partners.

3416
04:23:10,439 --> 04:23:15,380
'You were the difficulty, Mary Yellan.

3417
04:23:15,380 --> 04:23:19,860
When you came among us, I knew that the end
was near.

3418
04:23:19,860 --> 04:23:26,820
In any case, we had played the game to its
limit and the time had come to make an end.

3419
04:23:26,820 --> 04:23:33,830
How you troubled me with your courage and
your sense of justice, and how I admired you

3420
04:23:33,830 --> 04:23:35,070
for them!

3421
04:23:35,070 --> 04:23:41,190
Of course, you had to hear me in the empty
bedroom at the inn, and had to creep down

3422
04:23:41,190 --> 04:23:48,490
to the kitchen and see the rope on the beam;
that was the first piece of trouble that you

3423
04:23:48,490 --> 04:23:49,490
caused.

3424
04:23:49,490 --> 04:23:55,661
'And then you had to go out on the moor after
your uncle, who had an appointment with me

3425
04:23:55,661 --> 04:24:05,600
on Roughtor, and, losing him in the darkness,
meet myself and tell me your secrets.

3426
04:24:05,600 --> 04:24:14,860
Well, I became your friend, did I not, and
gave you good advice?

3427
04:24:14,860 --> 04:24:19,860
Which, believe me, could not have been improved
on by the magistrate himself.

3428
04:24:19,860 --> 04:24:22,350
Your uncle knew nothing of our strange friendship.

3429
04:24:22,350 --> 04:24:26,570
He caused his own death, by disobeying me.

3430
04:24:26,570 --> 04:24:33,590
I knew something of your determination, and
that time alone would quieten your suspicions.

3431
04:24:33,590 --> 04:24:39,220
But your uncle had to drink himself crazy
on the night before Christmas and, behaving

3432
04:24:39,220 --> 04:24:42,810
like a fool, put the whole country in a fever.

3433
04:24:42,810 --> 04:24:51,771
I knew then that when the rope was round his
neck he would play his last card and name

3434
04:24:51,771 --> 04:24:55,170
me as the leader.

3435
04:24:55,170 --> 04:25:03,950
Therefore he had to die, Mary Yellan, and
your aunt, who was his shadow; and, if you

3436
04:25:03,950 --> 04:25:12,520
had been at Jamaica Inn last night when I
passed by, you too - no, you would not have

3437
04:25:12,520 --> 04:25:16,360
died.'

3438
04:25:16,360 --> 04:25:22,360
He leant down to her and, taking her two hands,
he pulled her to her feet, so that she stood

3439
04:25:22,360 --> 04:25:25,830
level with him, looking into his eyes.

3440
04:25:25,830 --> 04:25:30,931
'No,' he repeated, 'you would not have died.

3441
04:25:30,931 --> 04:25:34,479
You would have come with me as you will come
tonight.'

3442
04:25:34,479 --> 04:25:38,830
She looked back at him, watching his eyes.

3443
04:25:38,830 --> 04:25:45,410
They told her nothing - they were clear and
cold as they had been before - but his hold

3444
04:25:45,410 --> 04:25:47,479
on her arms was firm.

3445
04:25:47,479 --> 04:25:50,910
'You are wrong,' she said.

3446
04:25:50,910 --> 04:25:54,400
'You would have killed me then as you will
kill me now.

3447
04:25:54,400 --> 04:25:58,430
I am not coming with you, Mr Davey.'

3448
04:25:58,430 --> 04:26:05,210
'You have proved yourself a dangerous enemy,
and I prefer to have you by my side.

3449
04:26:05,210 --> 04:26:10,740
In time, we will be able to return to our
first friendship.'

3450
04:26:10,740 --> 04:26:16,680
'Any friendship we have shared was disgusting
and dishonourable.

3451
04:26:16,680 --> 04:26:20,960
You wear the clothes of a priest of God to
hide you from suspicion.

3452
04:26:20,960 --> 04:26:23,550
You talk to me of friendship -'

3453
04:26:23,550 --> 04:26:30,960
'Your refusal and anger please me more than
anything, Mary Yellan,' he replied.

3454
04:26:30,960 --> 04:26:38,250
'There is a fire about you that the women
of the old days possessed.

3455
04:26:38,250 --> 04:26:42,530
Your company is not a thing to be thrown to
one side.

3456
04:26:42,530 --> 04:26:44,780
Are you ready?

3457
04:26:44,780 --> 04:26:50,630
You understand me, the house is empty, and
your cries would be heard by no one.

3458
04:26:50,630 --> 04:26:53,630
I am stronger than you might suppose.

3459
04:26:53,630 --> 04:26:56,030
Your uncle knew my strength!

3460
04:26:56,030 --> 04:27:02,720
I don't want to hurt you, Mary Yellan, but
I shall have to if you try to fight me.

3461
04:27:02,720 --> 04:27:10,300
Come, where is that spirit of adventure that
you have made your own?

3462
04:27:10,300 --> 04:27:12,630
Where is your courage?'

3463
04:27:12,630 --> 04:27:16,771
She saw by the clock that he must already
have used up his allowance of time.

3464
04:27:16,771 --> 04:27:23,870
It was half past eight, and by now, Jem would
have spoken with the blacksmith at Warleggan.

3465
04:27:23,870 --> 04:27:28,290
Twelve miles lay between them perhaps, but
no more.

3466
04:27:28,290 --> 04:27:33,910
She thought rapidly, weighing the chances
of failure and success.

3467
04:27:33,910 --> 04:27:37,610
If she went now with Francis Davey she could
slow him down.

3468
04:27:37,610 --> 04:27:42,950
The law would follow close behind him, and
her presence would show them where he was

3469
04:27:42,950 --> 04:27:44,140
in the end.

3470
04:27:44,140 --> 04:27:50,700
If she refused to go, then there would be
a knife in her heart, at best.

3471
04:27:50,700 --> 04:27:58,060
She smiled then, and looked into his eyes,
having made her decision.

3472
04:27:58,060 --> 04:28:03,840
'I'll come with you, Mr Davey,' she said,
'but you will be sorry in the end.'

3473
04:28:03,840 --> 04:28:06,870
'I'll like you the better for it.

3474
04:28:06,870 --> 04:28:15,450
I'll teach you to live, Mary Yellan, as men
and women have not lived for 4,000 years or

3475
04:28:15,450 --> 04:28:16,450
more.'

3476
04:28:16,450 --> 04:28:20,150
'You'll find me no companion on the road,
Mr Davey.'

3477
04:28:20,150 --> 04:28:21,631
'Road?

3478
04:28:21,631 --> 04:28:24,530
Who spoke of roads?

3479
04:28:24,530 --> 04:28:32,430
We go by the moors and hills, and put our
feet on stone and grass as the ancient men

3480
04:28:32,430 --> 04:28:35,200
did before us.'

3481
04:28:35,200 --> 04:28:37,439
She went into the passage.

3482
04:28:37,439 --> 04:28:44,010
She was filled with the wild spirit of adventure,
and she had no fear of him, and no fear of

3483
04:28:44,010 --> 04:28:46,180
the night.

3484
04:28:46,180 --> 04:28:51,610
Nothing mattered now, because the man she
loved was free and had no mark of blood on

3485
04:28:51,610 --> 04:28:53,070
him.

3486
04:28:53,070 --> 04:28:59,250
She could love him without shame; she knew
that he would come to her again.

3487
04:28:59,250 --> 04:29:04,320
She imagined she heard him ride along the
road after them, and she heard his victorious

3488
04:29:04,320 --> 04:29:06,460
cry.

3489
04:29:06,460 --> 04:29:08,780
She followed Francis Davey.

3490
04:29:08,780 --> 04:29:12,610
The sight of horses was one for which she
was not prepared.

3491
04:29:12,610 --> 04:29:16,210
'Do you not plan to take the carriage?'

3492
04:29:16,210 --> 04:29:17,210
she said.

3493
04:29:17,210 --> 04:29:21,410
'No, Mary, we must travel light and free.

3494
04:29:21,410 --> 04:29:32,450
You can ride - every woman born on a farm
can ride - and I shall lead you.'

3495
04:29:32,450 --> 04:29:35,390
The night was dark, with a cold wind.

3496
04:29:35,390 --> 04:29:39,410
The sky was filled with low cloud, and the
moon was hidden.

3497
04:29:39,410 --> 04:29:45,630
There would be no light on the way, and the
horses would travel unseen.

3498
04:29:45,630 --> 04:29:50,900
She climbed onto hers, wondering whether a
shout and a wild cry for help would wake the

3499
04:29:50,900 --> 04:29:56,390
sleeping village, but even as the thought
passed through her mind she saw the flash

3500
04:29:56,390 --> 04:29:59,391
of steel in his hand, and he smiled.

3501
04:29:59,391 --> 04:30:05,250
'That would be a fool's trick, Mary,' he said.

3502
04:30:05,250 --> 04:30:11,072
'They go to bed early in Altar nun, and by
the time they were awake and rubbing their

3503
04:30:11,072 --> 04:30:19,170
eyes I would be away over the moor and you
- you would be lying on your face in the long

3504
04:30:19,170 --> 04:30:24,720
wet grass with your youth and beauty spoilt.

3505
04:30:24,720 --> 04:30:27,061
Come now!'

3506
04:30:27,061 --> 04:30:28,979
She said nothing.

3507
04:30:28,979 --> 04:30:34,510
She had gone too far in her game of chance,
and must play it to the finish.

3508
04:30:34,510 --> 04:30:41,370
He climbed on the other horse, tied hers to
it, and they set out on their strange journey.

3509
04:30:41,370 --> 04:30:47,840
They came to the edge of the moor and the
rough track leading to the stream, and then

3510
04:30:47,840 --> 04:30:53,310
headed across the stream and beyond to the
great black heart of the moor, where there

3511
04:30:53,310 --> 04:30:56,100
were no tracks and no paths.

3512
04:30:56,100 --> 04:31:03,261
The tors rose up around them and hid the world
behind, and the two horses were lost between

3513
04:31:03,261 --> 04:31:05,880
the steep hills.

3514
04:31:05,880 --> 04:31:10,450
Mary's hopes began to fail, as she looked
over her shoulder at the black hills that

3515
04:31:10,450 --> 04:31:12,280
rose behind her.

3516
04:31:12,280 --> 04:31:16,370
There was an ancient mystery about these moors.

3517
04:31:16,370 --> 04:31:22,320
Francis Davey knew their secrets, and he cut
through the darkness like a blind man in his

3518
04:31:22,320 --> 04:31:23,320
home.

3519
04:31:23,320 --> 04:31:25,620
'Where are we going?'

3520
04:31:25,620 --> 04:31:33,160
she said, at last, and he turned to her, smiling
beneath his wide black hat, and pointed to

3521
04:31:33,160 --> 04:31:34,210
the north.

3522
04:31:34,210 --> 04:31:36,790
'The Atlantic has been my friend before.

3523
04:31:36,790 --> 04:31:40,630
A ship shall carry us from Cornwall.

3524
04:31:40,630 --> 04:31:48,080
You shall see Spain, Mary, and Africa, and
learn something of the sun; you shall feel

3525
04:31:48,080 --> 04:31:52,120
the sand under your feet, if you wish.

3526
04:31:52,120 --> 04:31:56,450
I care little where we go; you shall make
the choice.

3527
04:31:56,450 --> 04:32:00,580
Why do you smile and shake your head?'

3528
04:32:00,580 --> 04:32:05,100
'I smile because everything you say is wild
and impossible.

3529
04:32:05,100 --> 04:32:12,510
You know as well as I do that I shall run
from you at the first chance - at the first

3530
04:32:12,510 --> 04:32:13,850
village perhaps.

3531
04:32:13,850 --> 04:32:20,300
I came with you tonight because you would
have killed me otherwise, but in daylight,

3532
04:32:20,300 --> 04:32:26,320
within sight and sound of men and women, you
will be as powerless as I am now.'

3533
04:32:26,320 --> 04:32:30,681
'I am prepared for the risk.

3534
04:32:30,681 --> 04:32:35,870
You forget that the north coast of Cornwall
is very unlike the south.

3535
04:32:35,870 --> 04:32:41,750
This north coast is as lonely as the moors
themselves, and you will see no man's face

3536
04:32:41,750 --> 04:32:47,340
but mine until we come to the place that I
plan to reach.'

3537
04:32:47,340 --> 04:32:53,530
'Supposing then that the sea is reached, and
we are on your ship, with the coast behind

3538
04:32:53,530 --> 04:32:54,530
us.

3539
04:32:54,530 --> 04:32:58,500
Name any place you please - Africa, or Spain.

3540
04:32:58,500 --> 04:33:05,830
Do you think that I would follow you there
and not tell about you, a murderer of men?'

3541
04:33:05,830 --> 04:33:10,309
'You will have forgotten it by then, Mary
Yellan.'

3542
04:33:10,309 --> 04:33:16,568
'Forgotten that you killed my mother's sister?'

3543
04:33:16,568 --> 04:33:20,229
'Yes, and more besides.

3544
04:33:20,229 --> 04:33:26,719
Forgotten the moors, and Jamaica Inn and your
own foolish feet that crossed my path.

3545
04:33:26,719 --> 04:33:34,359
Forgotten your tears on the road from Launceston,
and the young man who caused them...

3546
04:33:34,359 --> 04:33:38,648
Oh, don't bite your lip and look angry - I
can guess your thoughts.

3547
04:33:38,648 --> 04:33:45,379
I know the dreams and fears of women better
than you do yourself.'

3548
04:33:45,379 --> 04:33:53,309
They rode on in silence, and after a time
it seemed to Mary that the darkness of the

3549
04:33:53,309 --> 04:33:59,299
night became thicker and the air closer, nor
could she see the hills around her as she

3550
04:33:59,299 --> 04:34:00,299
had before.

3551
04:34:00,299 --> 04:34:06,139
The horses picked their way delicately and
now and again stopped as though uncertain

3552
04:34:06,139 --> 04:34:08,119
of their way.

3553
04:34:08,119 --> 04:34:12,920
The ground was soft and dangerous, and though
Mary could no longer see the land on either

3554
04:34:12,920 --> 04:34:19,410
side, she knew by the feel of the soft ground
that they were surrounded by marshes.

3555
04:34:19,410 --> 04:34:25,740
This explained the horses' fear, and she looked
at her companion to discover his feelings.

3556
04:34:25,740 --> 04:34:32,109
He leant forward, looking into the darkness
that every moment became thicker, and she

3557
04:34:32,109 --> 04:34:37,109
saw by his thin, tightly closed mouth that
he was using all his powers to find their

3558
04:34:37,109 --> 04:34:42,549
way, threatened suddenly with this new danger.

3559
04:34:42,549 --> 04:34:47,898
Mary thought of these same marshes as she
had seen them in the light of day - the long

3560
04:34:47,898 --> 04:34:55,309
brown grass blowing in the wind, while beneath
them the black water waited in silence.

3561
04:34:55,309 --> 04:35:00,340
She knew how the people of the moors themselves
could go wrong, so that he who walked with

3562
04:35:00,340 --> 04:35:05,869
confidence one moment could sink the next,
without warning.

3563
04:35:05,869 --> 04:35:11,309
Francis Davey knew the moors, but even he
might lose his way.

3564
04:35:11,309 --> 04:35:16,078
She heard her companion swallow, and the little
trick sharpened her fear.

3565
04:35:16,078 --> 04:35:19,199
He looked to the right and left.

3566
04:35:19,199 --> 04:35:23,559
And then, in front of them, barring their
further progress, there rolled out of the

3567
04:35:23,559 --> 04:35:31,100
night a great bank of low cloud, a white wall
that blocked out everything.

3568
04:35:31,100 --> 04:35:37,418
Francis Davey stopped the horses; they stood
trembling, the steam from their sides rising

3569
04:35:37,418 --> 04:35:39,309
and mixing with the cloud.

3570
04:35:39,309 --> 04:35:44,748
Then he turned to Mary, his white face as
expressionless as ever.

3571
04:35:44,748 --> 04:35:50,139
'The gods have gone against me after all,'
he said.

3572
04:35:50,139 --> 04:35:56,850
'To continue now among the marshes would be
worse than to return.

3573
04:35:56,850 --> 04:36:00,590
We must wait for the daylight.'

3574
04:36:00,590 --> 04:36:07,100
She said nothing, her first hopes returning
to her, but then she remembered that the weather

3575
04:36:07,100 --> 04:36:10,879
would be an enemy to the hunters as well as
to the hunted.

3576
04:36:10,879 --> 04:36:17,148
He urged the horses to the left, away from
the marsh, until they reached firmer ground

3577
04:36:17,148 --> 04:36:22,969
and loose stones, while the white cloud moved
up with them step by step.

3578
04:36:22,969 --> 04:36:30,539
'There will be rest for you, after all, Mary
Yellan,' he said, 'and a hole in the rocks

3579
04:36:30,539 --> 04:36:33,229
for your shelter and stone for your bed.

3580
04:36:33,229 --> 04:36:42,010
Tomorrow may bring the world to you again,
but tonight you shall sleep on Roughtor.'

3581
04:36:42,010 --> 04:36:47,859
The horses climbed slowly out of the cloud
to the black hills beyond.

3582
04:36:47,859 --> 04:36:52,898
Later, Mary sat with her back against a large
stone.

3583
04:36:52,898 --> 04:37:00,020
The great tor's broken top towered above them
while below them the clouds hung unchanged.

3584
04:37:00,020 --> 04:37:02,590
Up here, the air was pure and clean.

3585
04:37:02,590 --> 04:37:08,998
There was a wind that whispered in the stones;
its breath, sharp as a knife and cold, blew

3586
04:37:08,998 --> 04:37:10,629
on the rocks.

3587
04:37:10,629 --> 04:37:17,119
The horses were restless; they stood against
a rock for shelter, and turned now and again

3588
04:37:17,119 --> 04:37:19,510
towards their master.

3589
04:37:19,510 --> 04:37:28,299
He sat apart, a few yards away from his companion,
and sometimes she felt his eyes on her.

3590
04:37:28,299 --> 04:37:34,359
He was king here, alone in the silence, with
the great rocks to guard him and the cloud

3591
04:37:34,359 --> 04:37:36,729
below to hide him.

3592
04:37:36,729 --> 04:37:39,910
She thought how far they were from normal
life.

3593
04:37:39,910 --> 04:37:47,498
Here on the tor the wind whispered of fear,
bringing old memories of violence and hopelessness,

3594
04:37:47,498 --> 04:37:52,741
and there was a wild, lost note that sounded
in the stone high above Mary's head, on the

3595
04:37:52,741 --> 04:37:59,369
very top of Roughtor, as if the gods themselves
stood there with their great heads lifted

3596
04:37:59,369 --> 04:38:00,748
to the sky.

3597
04:38:00,748 --> 04:38:07,320
She imagined she could hear the whisper of
a thousand voices and the marching of a thousand

3598
04:38:07,320 --> 04:38:12,219
feet, and she could see the stones turning
into men beside her.

3599
04:38:12,219 --> 04:38:20,318
Their faces were inhuman, older than time,
as rough as the stone; and they spoke in a

3600
04:38:20,318 --> 04:38:25,148
language that she could not understand, and
their hands and feet were curved like the

3601
04:38:25,148 --> 04:38:26,168
feet of birds.

3602
04:38:26,168 --> 04:38:34,439
They turned their stone eyes on her, and looked
through her and beyond, paying no attention,

3603
04:38:34,439 --> 04:38:40,648
and she knew that she was like a leaf in the
wind, while they lived on, undying creatures

3604
04:38:40,648 --> 04:38:43,639
of ancient times.

3605
04:38:43,639 --> 04:38:49,529
They came towards her, shoulder to shoulder,
neither seeing nor hearing her, but moving

3606
04:38:49,529 --> 04:38:58,029
like blind things to destroy her...

3607
04:38:58,029 --> 04:39:03,229
She woke from this dream to reality, feeling
the vicar's hand on her mouth.

3608
04:39:03,229 --> 04:39:08,119
She would have struggled with him, but he
held her fast, speaking coldly in her ear

3609
04:39:08,119 --> 04:39:11,221
and telling her to be still.

3610
04:39:11,221 --> 04:39:16,699
He forced her hands behind her back and tied
them, using his own belt.

3611
04:39:16,699 --> 04:39:21,930
Then he took a cloth from the pocket of his
coat and folded it, and put it in her mouth,

3612
04:39:21,930 --> 04:39:27,379
tying it behind her head so that any sound
was now impossible.

3613
04:39:27,379 --> 04:39:31,498
When he had done this he helped her to her
feet, and he led her a little way beyond the

3614
04:39:31,498 --> 04:39:33,619
rocks to the slope of the hill.

3615
04:39:33,619 --> 04:39:38,920
'I have to do this, Mary, for both of us,'
he said.

3616
04:39:38,920 --> 04:39:43,290
'When we set out last night I did not expect
this cloud.

3617
04:39:43,290 --> 04:39:52,030
Listen to this, and you will understand why
I have tied you up, and why your silence may

3618
04:39:52,030 --> 04:39:53,558
still save us.'

3619
04:39:53,558 --> 04:39:56,888
He pointed downwards to the white cloud below.

3620
04:39:56,888 --> 04:40:01,978
'Listen,' he said again.

3621
04:40:01,978 --> 04:40:06,148
The darkness had broken above their heads
and morning had come.

3622
04:40:06,148 --> 04:40:10,570
To the east, a faint light came before the
pale sun.

3623
04:40:10,570 --> 04:40:15,770
The cloud was with them still, and hid the
moors below like a white sheet.

3624
04:40:15,770 --> 04:40:22,040
Then she listened, as he had told her, and
far away, from beneath the cloud, there came

3625
04:40:22,040 --> 04:40:24,840
a sound between a cry and a call.

3626
04:40:24,840 --> 04:40:32,030
It was too faint at first to tell what it
was; unlike a human voice, unlike the shouting

3627
04:40:32,030 --> 04:40:34,770
of men.

3628
04:40:34,770 --> 04:40:37,478
It came nearer, and Francis Davey turned to
Mary.

3629
04:40:37,478 --> 04:40:41,568
'Do you know what it is?' he said.

3630
04:40:41,568 --> 04:40:45,238
She looked back at him, and shook her head.

3631
04:40:45,238 --> 04:40:47,298
She had never heard the sound before.

3632
04:40:47,298 --> 04:40:53,200
'I'd forgotten that Mr Bassat keeps hunting
dogs in his stables.

3633
04:40:53,200 --> 04:40:58,558
It's a pity for both of us that I didn't remember.'

3634
04:40:58,558 --> 04:41:05,208
She understood; and with sudden fear of that
distant eager crying, she looked up at her

3635
04:41:05,208 --> 04:41:12,790
companion and from him to the two horses standing
as patiently as ever by the side of the rock.

3636
04:41:12,790 --> 04:41:20,110
'Yes,' he said, following her eyes, 'we must
let them loose and drive them down to the

3637
04:41:20,110 --> 04:41:21,110
moors below.

3638
04:41:21,110 --> 04:41:25,450
They would only lead the dogs to us.'

3639
04:41:25,450 --> 04:41:31,370
She watched him, sick at heart, as he untied
the horses and led them to the steep slope

3640
04:41:31,370 --> 04:41:32,918
of the hill.

3641
04:41:32,918 --> 04:41:38,048
Then he bent down to the ground, picked up
stones in his hands, and rained blow after

3642
04:41:38,048 --> 04:41:44,250
blow on their sides; they ran off in fear,
kicking stones and earth as they went, and

3643
04:41:44,250 --> 04:41:46,419
so disappeared into the white clouds below.

3644
04:41:46,419 --> 04:41:55,100
The crying of the dogs came nearer now, deep
and continuous, and Francis Davey ran to Mary,

3645
04:41:55,100 --> 04:42:00,090
pulling off his long black coat and throwing
his hat away on to the grass.

3646
04:42:00,090 --> 04:42:02,100
'Come,' he said.

3647
04:42:02,100 --> 04:42:10,208
'Friend or enemy, we are both in danger now.'

3648
04:42:10,208 --> 04:42:15,458
They climbed up the hill among the stones
and rocks, he with his arm round her, because

3649
04:42:15,458 --> 04:42:21,290
her tied hands made progress difficult; and
they ran in and out of pools, struggled knee-deep

3650
04:42:21,290 --> 04:42:27,208
in wet grass, climbing higher and higher to
the top of Roughtor.

3651
04:42:27,208 --> 04:42:35,708
Here, on the very top, the stone was strangely
shaped, twisted into the form of a roof.

3652
04:42:35,708 --> 04:42:40,520
Mary lay beneath this great stone, breathless
and bleeding.

3653
04:42:40,520 --> 04:42:45,548
He reached down to her, and though she shook
her head and made signs that she could climb

3654
04:42:45,548 --> 04:42:51,360
no further, he bent and dragged her to her
feet again, cutting at the belt that tied

3655
04:42:51,360 --> 04:42:54,228
her and tearing the cloth from her mouth.

3656
04:42:54,228 --> 04:43:03,658
'Save yourself then, if you can!' he shouted,
his eyes burning in his pale face, his white

3657
04:43:03,658 --> 04:43:05,798
hair blowing in the wind.

3658
04:43:05,798 --> 04:43:11,510
She held on to a table of stone some 10 feet
from the ground, while he climbed above her

3659
04:43:11,510 --> 04:43:17,540
and beyond, his thin black figure hanging
on the smooth surface of the rock.

3660
04:43:17,540 --> 04:43:23,340
The crying of the dogs was unearthly, coming
as it did from the sheet of cloud below, and

3661
04:43:23,340 --> 04:43:28,998
the sound was increased by the cries and shouting
of men, a confusion that filled the air with

3662
04:43:28,998 --> 04:43:32,978
sound and was the more terrible because it
was unseen.

3663
04:43:32,978 --> 04:43:39,298
The high clouds moved across the sky, and
the yellow sun swam into view between them.

3664
04:43:39,298 --> 04:43:45,190
The cloud below her melted away, and the land
that it had covered for so long looked up

3665
04:43:45,190 --> 04:43:49,458
at the sky, pale and new-born.

3666
04:43:49,458 --> 04:43:54,250
Mary looked down the sloping hillside; there
were little dots of men standing knee-deep

3667
04:43:54,250 --> 04:44:00,790
in the long grass, while the dogs ran in front
of them like rats among the fallen rocks.

3668
04:44:00,790 --> 04:44:07,878
They followed the track fast, SO men or more,
shouting and pointing up to the great tables

3669
04:44:07,878 --> 04:44:15,290
of rock, and as they came near, the sound
of the dogs filled the cracks and the hollows.

3670
04:44:15,290 --> 04:44:21,510
Somebody shouted again, and a man who knelt
on the ground about 50 yards from Mary lifted

3671
04:44:21,510 --> 04:44:23,908
his gun to his shoulder and fired.

3672
04:44:23,908 --> 04:44:31,388
The shot hit the rock without touching her,
and when he rose to his feet, she saw that

3673
04:44:31,388 --> 04:44:35,298
the man was Jem, and that he had not seen
her.

3674
04:44:35,298 --> 04:44:41,208
The dogs were running in and out among the
stones, and one of them jumped up at the rock

3675
04:44:41,208 --> 04:44:42,610
beneath her.

3676
04:44:42,610 --> 04:44:50,498
Then Jem fired once more; and, looking beyond
her, Mary saw the tall black figure of Francis

3677
04:44:50,498 --> 04:44:57,280
Davey standing out against the sky, on a wide,
flat rock high above her head.

3678
04:44:57,280 --> 04:45:04,910
He stood for a moment, his hair blowing in
the wind; and then he threw his arms wide,

3679
04:45:04,910 --> 04:45:12,690
as a bird throws his wings to fly, and fell
- down from his high rock to the wet grass

3680
04:45:12,690 --> 04:45:18,280
and the little scattered stones below.

3681
04:45:18,280 --> 04:45:21,350
CHAPTER SEVENTEEN
A New Life

3682
04:45:21,350 --> 04:45:26,720
It was a hard, bright day in early January.

3683
04:45:26,720 --> 04:45:32,190
The holes in the road, which were generally
thick with mud or water, were covered with

3684
04:45:32,190 --> 04:45:35,578
thin ice, and the wheel tracks were white.

3685
04:45:35,578 --> 04:45:39,020
The air was cold.

3686
04:45:39,020 --> 04:45:44,820
Mary walked alone on the moor, and wondered
why it was that Kilmar, to the left of her,

3687
04:45:44,820 --> 04:45:47,120
no longer seemed threatening.

3688
04:45:47,120 --> 04:45:53,530
The moors were still empty, and the hills
were friendless, but the old sense of evil

3689
04:45:53,530 --> 04:45:58,238
had left them and she could walk on them without
fear.

3690
04:45:58,238 --> 04:46:03,718
She was free now to go where she chose, and
her thoughts turned to Helford and the green

3691
04:46:03,718 --> 04:46:05,690
valleys of the south.

3692
04:46:05,690 --> 04:46:13,620
She had a strange desire in her heart for
home and the sight of warm, friendly faces.

3693
04:46:13,620 --> 04:46:19,780
She remembered with pain every smell and sound
that had belonged to her for so long.

3694
04:46:19,780 --> 04:46:25,450
She was from the soil and would return to
it again, rooted to the earth as her fathers

3695
04:46:25,450 --> 04:46:28,208
before her had been.

3696
04:46:28,208 --> 04:46:34,020
Helford had given birth to her, and when she
died, she would be part of it once more.

3697
04:46:34,020 --> 04:46:40,750
Only among the woods and streams of her own
Helford valley would she know peace again.

3698
04:46:40,750 --> 04:46:47,030
There was a cart coming towards her from Kilmar,
across the white moor.

3699
04:46:47,030 --> 04:46:50,798
It was the one moving thing on the silent
plain.

3700
04:46:50,798 --> 04:46:56,270
She watched it with suspicion, for there were
no houses on this moor except Trewartha, and

3701
04:46:56,270 --> 04:46:59,260
Trewartha, she knew, stood empty.

3702
04:46:59,260 --> 04:47:03,558
She had not seen its owner since he had fired
past her at Roughtor.

3703
04:47:03,558 --> 04:47:10,840
'He's an ungrateful devil, like the rest of
his family,' the magistrate had said.

3704
04:47:10,840 --> 04:47:17,048
'If I hadn't helped him, he'd be in prison
now, with a long stay in front of him to break

3705
04:47:17,048 --> 04:47:18,270
his spirit.

3706
04:47:18,270 --> 04:47:20,510
I admit he did well.

3707
04:47:20,510 --> 04:47:27,308
He was the means of finding you, Mary, and
that black-coated murderer, but he's never

3708
04:47:27,308 --> 04:47:33,298
even thanked me for clearing his name in the
business, and has taken himself to the world's

3709
04:47:33,298 --> 04:47:34,360
end, for all I know.

3710
04:47:34,360 --> 04:47:40,918
There's never been a Merlyn yet that came
to any good, and he'll go the same way as

3711
04:47:40,918 --> 04:47:41,918
the rest of them.'

3712
04:47:41,918 --> 04:47:46,680
The cart came nearer to the slope of the hill.

3713
04:47:46,680 --> 04:47:52,148
The horse bent to pull its load, and she saw
that it was struggling with a strange pile

3714
04:47:52,148 --> 04:47:55,500
of pots and pans and furniture.

3715
04:47:55,500 --> 04:47:59,100
Someone was setting out on a journey with
his house on his back.

3716
04:47:59,100 --> 04:48:05,478
Even then, she did not realize the truth,
and it was not until the cart was below her

3717
04:48:05,478 --> 04:48:11,648
and the driver, walking by its side, looked
up to her and waved that she recognized Jem.

3718
04:48:11,648 --> 04:48:17,520
'Are you better?' he called, from beside the
cart.

3719
04:48:17,520 --> 04:48:22,498
'I heard that you were ill, and had been staying
in bed.'

3720
04:48:22,498 --> 04:48:27,308
'You must have heard wrong,' said Mary.

3721
04:48:27,308 --> 04:48:29,388
'I've been around the house at North Hill.

3722
04:48:29,388 --> 04:48:33,878
There's never been much the matter with me
except a hatred for this area.'

3723
04:48:33,878 --> 04:48:40,138
'There was some talk that you were to settle
there, and be a companion to Mrs Bassat.

3724
04:48:40,138 --> 04:48:45,318
Well, you'll lead an easy enough life with
them, I dare say.'

3725
04:48:45,318 --> 04:48:46,340
'No.

3726
04:48:46,340 --> 04:48:49,340
I'm going back home to Helford.'

3727
04:48:49,340 --> 04:48:51,718
'What will you do there?'

3728
04:48:51,718 --> 04:48:58,048
'I shall try to start the farm again, or at
least work my way to it, because I haven't

3729
04:48:58,048 --> 04:48:59,770
the money yet.

3730
04:48:59,770 --> 04:49:01,900
I've friends there who will help me.'

3731
04:49:01,900 --> 04:49:04,648
'Where will you live?'

3732
04:49:04,648 --> 04:49:08,120
'I would be welcome in any house in the village.

3733
04:49:08,120 --> 04:49:11,760
We're good neighbours in the south, you know.'

3734
04:49:11,760 --> 04:49:17,208
'I've never had neighbours, so I cannot say,
but I've always had the feeling that it would

3735
04:49:17,208 --> 04:49:20,760
be like living in a box, to live in a village.

3736
04:49:20,760 --> 04:49:26,998
You put your nose over your gate into another
man's garden, and if his flowers are better

3737
04:49:26,998 --> 04:49:32,260
than yours there's an argument; and you know
that if you cook a rabbit for your supper

3738
04:49:32,260 --> 04:49:35,228
he'll have the smell of it in his kitchen.

3739
04:49:35,228 --> 04:49:39,128
That's no life for anyone!

3740
04:49:39,128 --> 04:49:47,360
Here's my home, Mary, all the home I've ever
had, here on the cart, and I'll take it with

3741
04:49:47,360 --> 04:49:50,370
me and set it up wherever I want to.

3742
04:49:50,370 --> 04:49:58,068
I've been a wanderer since I was a boy; never
any ties, nor roots, nor wishes, for any length

3743
04:49:58,068 --> 04:50:02,408
of time; and I dare say I'll die a wanderer
too.

3744
04:50:02,408 --> 04:50:06,128
It's the only life in the world for me.'

3745
04:50:06,128 --> 04:50:12,780
'There's no peace, Jem, in wandering, and
no quiet.

3746
04:50:12,780 --> 04:50:18,540
There'll come a time when you'll want your
own piece of ground, and your four walls,

3747
04:50:18,540 --> 04:50:23,860
and your roof, and somewhere to rest your
poor, tired bones.'

3748
04:50:23,860 --> 04:50:31,998
'The whole country belongs to me, Mary, with
the sky for a roof and the earth for a bed.

3749
04:50:31,998 --> 04:50:33,378
You don't understand.

3750
04:50:33,378 --> 04:50:37,990
You're a woman, and your home is everything
to you.

3751
04:50:37,990 --> 04:50:41,840
I've never lived like that, and never shall.

3752
04:50:41,840 --> 04:50:46,680
I'll sleep on the hills one night, and in
a city the next.

3753
04:50:46,680 --> 04:50:53,638
I like to find my fortune here and there and
everywhere, with strangers for company and

3754
04:50:53,638 --> 04:50:55,718
passers-by for friends.

3755
04:50:55,718 --> 04:51:03,480
Today I meet a man on the road, and travel
with him for an hour or for a year, and tomorrow

3756
04:51:03,480 --> 04:51:05,228
he is gone again.

3757
04:51:05,228 --> 04:51:08,920
We speak a different language, you and I.'

3758
04:51:08,920 --> 04:51:12,458
'Which way will you go?'

3759
04:51:12,458 --> 04:51:16,010
'Somewhere east of the river.

3760
04:51:16,010 --> 04:51:17,120
It doesn't matter to me.

3761
04:51:17,120 --> 04:51:23,568
I'll never come west again - not until I'm
old and grey, and have forgotten many things.

3762
04:51:23,568 --> 04:51:26,228
I thought of going to the north.

3763
04:51:26,228 --> 04:51:33,241
They're rich up there, and open to new ideas;
there'll be a fortune there for a man who

3764
04:51:33,241 --> 04:51:34,668
goes to find it.

3765
04:51:34,668 --> 04:51:41,080
Perhaps I'll have money one day, and buy horses
instead of stealing them.'

3766
04:51:41,080 --> 04:51:45,170
'It's an ugly black country in the north.'

3767
04:51:45,170 --> 04:51:48,490
'I don't worry about the colour of the soil.

3768
04:51:48,490 --> 04:51:52,398
Moorland soil is black, isn't it?

3769
04:51:52,398 --> 04:51:56,760
And so is the rain when it falls among your
pigs down at Helford.

3770
04:51:56,760 --> 04:51:58,158
What's the difference?'

3771
04:51:58,158 --> 04:52:06,238
'You talk just to argue with me, Jem - there's
no sense in what you say.'

3772
04:52:06,238 --> 04:52:13,040
'How can I be sensible when you lean against
my horse with your hair blowing in the wind?

3773
04:52:13,040 --> 04:52:19,158
I know that in five or ten minutes' time I
shall be over that hill without you.

3774
04:52:19,158 --> 04:52:25,600
My face will be turned towards the river and
you will be walking back to North Hill to

3775
04:52:25,600 --> 04:52:27,818
drink tea with Mr Bassat.'

3776
04:52:27,818 --> 04:52:33,690
'Delay your journey, then, and come to North
Hill too.'

3777
04:52:33,690 --> 04:52:36,430
'Don't be a fool, Mary.

3778
04:52:36,430 --> 04:52:43,780
Can you see me drinking tea with the magistrate,
and dancing his children on my knee?

3779
04:52:43,780 --> 04:52:48,138
I don't belong to his class, and neither do
you.'

3780
04:52:48,138 --> 04:52:49,728
'I know that.

3781
04:52:49,728 --> 04:52:53,668
And I'm going back to Helford because of it.

3782
04:52:53,668 --> 04:52:58,668
I want to smell the river again, and walk
in my own country.'

3783
04:52:58,668 --> 04:53:05,728
'Go on, then; turn your back on me and start
walking now.

3784
04:53:05,728 --> 04:53:09,128
You'll come to a road that will take you to
Helford.'

3785
04:53:09,128 --> 04:53:14,270
'You're very hard today, and cruel.'

3786
04:53:14,270 --> 04:53:19,078
'I'm hard with my horses when they won't do
as I say but that doesn't mean that I love

3787
04:53:19,078 --> 04:53:20,700
them any the less.'

3788
04:53:20,700 --> 04:53:28,930
'You've never loved anything in your life,'
said Mary 'I haven't had much use for the

3789
04:53:28,930 --> 04:53:31,818
word, that's why,' he told her.

3790
04:53:31,818 --> 04:53:36,398
'It's past midday already, and I ought to
be on the road.

3791
04:53:36,398 --> 04:53:43,860
If you were a man I'd ask you to come with
me, and you'd jump on to the seat and put

3792
04:53:43,860 --> 04:53:49,350
your hands in your pockets and ride beside
me for as long as it pleased you.'

3793
04:53:49,350 --> 04:53:52,620
'I'd do that now if you'd take me south.'

3794
04:53:52,620 --> 04:54:01,530
'Yes, but I'm going north - and you're not
a man, you're only a woman, as you'd learn

3795
04:54:01,530 --> 04:54:03,990
if you came with me.

3796
04:54:03,990 --> 04:54:08,200
I'm going now.

3797
04:54:08,200 --> 04:54:09,600
Goodbye.'

3798
04:54:09,600 --> 04:54:15,520
He took her face in his hands and kissed it,
and she saw that he was laughing.

3799
04:54:15,520 --> 04:54:23,078
'When you're an old woman down in Helford,
you'll remember that, and it will have to

3800
04:54:23,078 --> 04:54:26,968
last you to the end of your days.

3801
04:54:26,968 --> 04:54:34,760
"He stole horses," you'll say to yourself,
"and he didn't care for women; but if I had

3802
04:54:34,760 --> 04:54:40,390
not been so proud I'd have been with him now."'

3803
04:54:40,390 --> 04:54:45,398
He climbed onto the cart and looked down at
her, waving his whip.

3804
04:54:45,398 --> 04:54:54,068
'I'll do 50 miles before tonight,' he said,
'and sleep like a child at the end of it,

3805
04:54:54,068 --> 04:54:56,540
in a tent by the side of the road.

3806
04:54:56,540 --> 04:55:02,048
I'll light a fire, and cook some eggs for
my supper.

3807
04:55:02,048 --> 04:55:06,360
Will you think of me or not?'

3808
04:55:06,360 --> 04:55:14,318
But she did not listen; she stood with her
face towards the south, twisting her hands

3809
04:55:14,318 --> 04:55:15,828
and saying nothing.

3810
04:55:15,828 --> 04:55:23,200
Beyond those hills, the empty moors turned
to green grass, and the green grass to valleys

3811
04:55:23,200 --> 04:55:24,860
and to streams.

3812
04:55:24,860 --> 04:55:30,998
The peace and quiet of Helford waited for
her beside the running water.

3813
04:55:30,998 --> 04:55:38,638
'It's not pride,' she told him; 'you know
it's not pride; there's a sickness in my heart

3814
04:55:38,638 --> 04:55:43,600
for home and all the things I've lost.'

3815
04:55:43,600 --> 04:55:47,430
He said nothing, but whistled to the horse.

3816
04:55:47,430 --> 04:55:54,878
'Wait,' said Mary, 'wait, and hold him still,
and give me your hand.'

3817
04:55:54,878 --> 04:56:01,780
He laid the whip to one side, and reached
down to her, and swung her up beside him on

3818
04:56:01,780 --> 04:56:03,748
the driver's seat.

3819
04:56:03,748 --> 04:56:07,638
'What now?' he said.

3820
04:56:07,638 --> 04:56:09,959
'And where do you want me to take you?

3821
04:56:09,959 --> 04:56:15,770
You have your back to Helford, do you know
that?'

3822
04:56:15,770 --> 04:56:21,128
'Yes, I know,' she said.

3823
04:56:21,128 --> 04:56:29,600
'If you come with me it will be a hard life,
and a wild one at times, Mary, with no staying

3824
04:56:29,600 --> 04:56:33,760
anywhere, and little rest or comfort.

3825
04:56:33,760 --> 04:56:40,620
You'll get a poor exchange for your farm and
little hope of the peace you look for.'

3826
04:56:40,620 --> 04:56:44,068
'I'll take the risk, Jem.'

3827
04:56:44,068 --> 04:56:47,150
'Do you love me, Mary?'

3828
04:56:47,150 --> 04:56:49,958
'I believe so, Jem.'

3829
04:56:49,958 --> 04:56:52,068
'Better than Helford?'

3830
04:56:52,068 --> 04:56:55,578
'I can't ever answer that.'

3831
04:56:55,578 --> 04:56:59,388
'Why are you sitting here beside me, then?'

3832
04:56:59,388 --> 04:57:11,860
'Because I want to, because I must; because
now and forever this is where I want to be,'

3833
04:57:11,860 --> 04:57:14,190
said Mary.

3834
04:57:14,190 --> 04:57:21,048
He laughed then, and took her hand, and whipped
the horse; and she did not look back over

3835
04:57:21,048 --> 04:57:25,640
her shoulder again, but set her face north
towards the river.

3836
04:57:25,640 --> 04:57:25,740
- THE END -

